\par 
\par We are unknown, we knowers, ourselves to ourselves: this has its own
\par good reason. We have never searched for ourselves--how should it then
\par come to pass, that we should ever _find_ ourselves? Rightly has it been
\par said: "Where your treasure is, there will your heart be also." _Our_
\par treasure is there, where stand the hives of our knowledge. It is to
\par those hives that we are always striving; as born creatures of flight,
\par and as the honey-gatherers of the spirit, we care really in our hearts
\par only for one thing--to bring something "home to the hive!"
\par 
\par As far as the rest of life with its so-called "experiences" is
\par concerned, which of us has even sufficient serious interest? or
\par sufficient time? In our dealings with such points of life, we are, I
\par fear, never properly to the point; to be precise, our heart is not
\par there, and certainly not our ear. Rather like one who, delighting
\par in a divine distraction, or sunken in the seas of his own soul, in
\par whose ear the clock has just thundered with all its force its twelve
\par strokes of noon, suddenly wakes up, and asks himself, "What has in
\par point of fact just struck?" so do we at times rub afterwards, as it
\par were, our puzzled ears, and ask in complete astonishment and complete
\par embarrassment, "Through what have we in point of fact just lived?"
\par further, "Who are we in point of fact?" and count, _after they have
\par struck_, as I have explained, all the twelve throbbing beats of the
\par clock of our experience, of our life, of our being--ah!--and count
\par wrong in the endeavour. Of necessity we remain strangers to ourselves,
\par we understand ourselves not, in ourselves we are bound to be mistaken,
\par for of us holds good to all eternity the motto, "Each one is the
\par farthest away from himself"--as far as ourselves are concerned we are
\par not "knowers."
\par 
\par 
\par 2.
\par 
\par My thoughts concerning the _genealogy_ of our moral prejudices--for
\par they constitute the issue in this polemic--have their first, bald,
\par and provisional expression in that collection of aphorisms entitled
\par _Human, all-too-Human, a Book for Free Minds_, the writing of which
\par was begun in Sorrento, during a winter which allowed me to gaze over
\par the broad and dangerous territory through which my mind had up to that
\par time wandered. This took place in the winter of 1876-77; the thoughts
\par themselves are older. They were in their substance already the same
\par thoughts which I take up again in the following treatises:--we hope
\par that they have derived benefit from the long interval, that they have
\par grown riper, clearer, stronger, more complete. The fact, however,
\par that I still cling to them even now, that in the meanwhile they have
\par always held faster by each other, have, in fact, grown out of their
\par original shape and into each other, all this strengthens in my mind the
\par joyous confidence that they must have been originally neither separate
\par disconnected capricious nor sporadic phenomena, but have sprung from
\par a common root, from a fundamental "_fiat_" of knowledge, whose empire
\par reached to the soul's depth, and that ever grew more definite in its
\par voice, and more definite in its demands. That is the only state of
\par affairs that is proper in the case of a philosopher.
\par 
\par We have no right to be "_disconnected_"; we must neither err
\par "disconnectedly" nor strike the truth "disconnectedly." Rather with
\par the necessity with which a tree bears its fruit, so do our thoughts,
\par our values, our Yes's and No's and If's and Whether's, grow connected
\par and interrelated, mutual witnesses of _one_ will, _one_ health, _one_
\par kingdom, _one_ sun--as to whether they are to _your_ taste, these
\par fruits of ours?--But what matters that to the trees? What matters that
\par to us, us the philosophers?
\par 
\par 
\par 3.
\par 
\par Owing to a scrupulosity peculiar to myself, which I confess
\par reluctantly,--it concerns indeed _morality_,--a scrupulosity, which
\par manifests itself in my life at such an early period, with so much
\par spontaneity, with so chronic a persistence and so keen an opposition
\par to environment, epoch, precedent, and ancestry that I should have
\par been almost entitled to style it my "_\'e2 priori_"--my curiosity and my
\par suspicion felt themselves betimes bound to halt at the question, of
\par what in point of actual fact was the _origin_ of our "Good" and of
\par our "Evil." Indeed, at the boyish age of thirteen the problem of the
\par origin of Evil already haunted me: at an age "when games and God divide
\par one's heart," I devoted to that problem my first childish attempt
\par at the literary game, my first philosophic essay--and as regards my
\par infantile solution of the problem, well, I gave quite properly the
\par honour to God, and made him the _father_ of evil. Did my own "_\'e2
\par priori_" demand that precise solution from me? that new, immoral, or
\par at least "amoral" "_\'e2 priori_" and that "categorical imperative" which
\par was its voice (but oh! how hostile to the Kantian article, and how
\par pregnant with problems!), to which since then I have given more and
\par more attention, and indeed what is more than attention. Fortunately
\par I soon learned to separate theological from moral prejudices, and
\par I gave up looking for a _supernatural_ origin of evil. A certain
\par amount of historical and philological education, to say nothing of
\par an innate faculty of psychological discrimination _par excellence_
\par succeeded in transforming almost immediately my original problem into
\par the following one:--Under what conditions did Man invent for himself
\par those judgments of values, "Good" and "Evil"? _And what intrinsic value
\par do they possess in themselves?_ Have they up to the present hindered
\par or advanced human well-being? Are they a symptom of the distress,
\par impoverishment, and degeneration of Human Life? Or, conversely, is
\par it in them that is manifested the fulness, the strength, and the
\par will of Life, its courage, its self-confidence, its future? On this
\par point I found and hazarded in my mind the most diverse answers, I
\par established distinctions in periods, peoples, and castes, I became a
\par specialist in my problem, and from my answers grew new questions, new
\par investigations, new conjectures, new probabilities; until at last I had
\par a land of my own and a soil of my own, a whole secret world growing and
\par flowering, like hidden gardens of whose existence no one could have an
\par inkling--oh, how happy are we, we finders of knowledge, provided that
\par we know how to keep silent sufficiently long.
\par 
\par 
\par 4.
\par 
\par My first impulse to publish some of my hypotheses concerning the origin
\par of morality I owe to a clear, well-written, and even precocious little
\par book, in which a perverse and vicious kind of moral philosophy (your
\par real English kind) was definitely presented to me for the first time;
\par and this attracted me--with that magnetic attraction, inherent in that
\par which is diametrically opposed and antithetical to one's own ideas.
\par The title of the book was _The Origin of the Moral Emotions_; its
\par author, Dr. Paul R\'e9e; the year of its appearance, 1877. I may almost
\par say that I have never read anything in which every single dogma and
\par conclusion has called forth from me so emphatic a negation as did that
\par book; albeit a negation tainted by either pique or intolerance. I
\par referred accordingly both in season and out of season in the previous
\par works, at which I was then working, to the arguments of that book, not
\par to refute them--for what have I got to do with mere refutations but
\par substituting, as is natural to a positive mind, for an improbable
\par theory one which is more probable, and occasionally no doubt, for one
\par philosophic error, another. In that early period I gave, as I have
\par said, the first public expression to those theories of origin to which
\par these essays are devoted, but with a clumsiness which I was the last
\par to conceal from myself, for I was as yet cramped, being still without
\par a special language for these special subjects, still frequently liable
\par to relapse and to vacillation. To go into details, compare what I say
\par in _Human, all-too-Human_, part i., about the parallel early history
\par of Good and Evil, Aph. 45 (namely, their origin from the castes of the
\par aristocrats and the slaves); similarly, Aph. 136 et seq., concerning
\par the birth and value of ascetic morality; similarly, Aphs. 96, 99,
\par vol. ii., Aph. 89, concerning the Morality of Custom, that far older
\par and more original kind of morality which is _toto c\'9clo_ different
\par from the altruistic ethics (in which Dr. R\'e9e, like all the English
\par moral philosophers, sees the ethical "Thing-in-itself"); finally,
\par Aph. 92. Similarly, Aph. 26 in _Human, all-too-Human_, part ii., and
\par Aph. 112, the _Dawn of Day_, concerning the origin of Justice as a
\par balance between persons of approximately equal power (equilibrium as
\par the hypothesis of all contract, consequently of all law); similarly,
\par concerning the origin of Punishment, _Human, all-too-Human_, part
\par ii., Aphs. 22, 23, in regard to which the deterrent object is neither
\par essential nor original (as Dr. R\'e9e thinks:--rather is it that this
\par object is only imported, under certain definite conditions, and always
\par as something extra and additional).
\par 
\par 
\par 5.
\par 
\par In reality I had set my heart at that time on something much more
\par important than the nature of the theories of myself or others
\par concerning the origin of morality (or, more precisely, the real
\par function from my view of these theories was to point an end to which
\par they were one among many means). The issue for me was the value
\par of morality, and on that subject I had to place myself in a state
\par of abstraction, in which I was almost alone with my great teacher
\par Schopenhauer, to whom that book, with all its passion and inherent
\par contradiction (for that book also was a polemic), turned for present
\par help as though he were still alive. The issue was, strangely enough,
\par the value of the "un-egoistic" instincts, the instincts of pity,
\par self-denial, and self-sacrifice which Schopenhauer had so persistently
\par painted in golden colours, deified and etherealised, that eventually
\par they appeared to him, as it were, high and dry, as "intrinsic values
\par in themselves," on the strength of which he uttered both to Life
\par and to himself his own negation. But against _these very_ instincts
\par there voiced itself in my soul a more and more fundamental mistrust, a
\par scepticism that dug ever deeper and deeper: and in this very instinct
\par I saw the _great_ danger of mankind, its most sublime temptation and
\par seduction--seduction to what? to nothingness?--in these very instincts
\par I saw the beginning of the end, stability, the exhaustion that gazes
\par backwards, the will turning _against_ Life, the last illness announcing
\par itself with its own mincing melancholy: I realised that the morality
\par of pity which spread wider and wider, and whose grip infected even
\par philosophers with its disease, was the most sinister symptom of our
\par modern European civilisation; I realised that it was the route along
\par which that civilisation slid on its way to--a new Buddhism?--a European
\par Buddhism?--_Nihilism_? This exaggerated estimation in which modern
\par philosophers have held pity, is quite a new phenomenon: up to that time
\par philosophers were absolutely unanimous as to the worthlessness of pity.
\par I need only mention Plato, Spinoza, La Rochefoucauld, and Kant--four
\par minds as mutually different as is possible, but united on one point;
\par their contempt of pity.
\par 
\par 
\par 6.
\par 
\par This problem of the value of pity and of the pity-morality (I am an
\par opponent of the modern infamous emasculation of our emotions) seems at
\par the first blush a mere isolated problem, a note of interrogation for
\par itself; he, however, who once halts at this problem, and learns how to
\par put questions, will experience what I experienced:--a new and immense
\par vista unfolds itself before him, a sense of potentiality seizes him
\par like a vertigo, every species of doubt, mistrust, and fear springs
\par up, the belief in morality, nay, in all morality, totters,--finally a
\par new demand voices itself. Let us speak out this _new demand_: we need
\par a _critique_ of moral values, _the value of these values_ is for the
\par first time to be called into question--and for this purpose a knowledge
\par is necessary of the conditions and circumstances out of which these
\par values grew, and under which they experienced their evolution and
\par their distortion (morality as a result, as a symptom, as a mask, as
\par Tartuffism, as disease, as a misunderstanding; but also morality as a
\par cause, as a remedy, as a stimulant, as a fetter, as a drug), especially
\par as such a knowledge has neither existed up to the present time nor is
\par even now generally desired. The value of these "values" was taken for
\par granted as an indisputable fact, which was beyond all question. No one
\par has, up to the present, exhibited the faintest doubt or hesitation in
\par judging the "good man" to be of a higher value than the "evil man," of
\par a higher value with regard specifically to human progress, utility,
\par and prosperity generally, not forgetting the future. What? Suppose the
\par converse were the truth! What? Suppose there lurked in the "good man"
\par a symptom of retrogression, such as a danger, a temptation, a poison,
\par a _narcotic_, by means of which the present _battened on the future_!
\par More comfortable and less risky perhaps than its opposite, but also
\par pettier, meaner! So that morality would really be saddled with the
\par guilt, if the _maximum potentiality of the power and splendour_ of the
\par human species were never to be attained? So that really morality would
\par be the danger of dangers?
\par 
\par 
\par 7.
\par 
\par Enough, that after this vista had disclosed itself to me, I myself had
\par reason to search for learned, bold, and industrious colleagues (I am
\par doing it even to this very day). It means traversing with new clamorous
\par questions, and at the same time with new eyes, the immense, distant,
\par and completely unexplored land of morality--of a morality which has
\par actually existed and been actually lived! and is this not practically
\par equivalent to first _discovering_ that land? If, in this context, I
\par thought, amongst others, of the aforesaid Dr. R\'e9e, I did so because I
\par had no doubt that from the very nature of his questions he would be
\par compelled to have recourse to a truer method, in order to obtain his
\par answers. Have I deceived myself on that score? I wished at all events
\par to give a better direction of vision to an eye of such keenness, and
\par such impartiality. I wished to direct him to the real _history of
\par morality_, and to warn him, while there was yet time, against a world
\par of English theories that culminated in _the blue vacuum of heaven_.
\par Other colours, of course, rise immediately to one's mind as being a
\par hundred times more potent than blue for a genealogy of morals:--for
\par instance, grey, by which I mean authentic facts capable of definite
\par proof and having actually existed, or, to put it shortly, the whole
\par of that long hieroglyphic script (which is so hard to decipher) about
\par the past history of human morals. This script was unknown to Dr. R\'e9e;
\par but he had read Darwin:--and so in his philosophy the Darwinian beast
\par and that pink of modernity, the demure weakling and dilettante, who
\par "bites no longer," shake hands politely in a fashion that is at least
\par instructive, the latter exhibiting a certain facial expression of
\par refined and good-humoured indolence, tinged with a touch of pessimism
\par and exhaustion; as if it really did not pay to take all these things--I
\par mean moral problems--so seriously. I, on the other hand, think that
\par there are no subjects which pay better for being taken seriously; part
\par of this payment is, that perhaps eventually they admit of being taken
\par gaily. This gaiety indeed, or, to use my own language, this joyful
\par wisdom, is a payment; a payment for a protracted, brave, laborious, and
\par burrowing seriousness, which, it goes without saying, is the attribute
\par of but a few. But on that day on which we say from the fullness of our
\par hearts, "Forward! our old morality too is fit material for Comedy,"
\par we shall have discovered a new plot, and a new possibility for the
\par Dionysian drama entitled The Soul's Fate--and he will speedily utilise
\par it, one can wager safely, he, the great ancient eternal dramatist of
\par the comedy of our existence.
\par 
\par 
\par 8.
\par 
\par If this writing be obscure to any individual, and jar on his ears, I
\par do not think that it is necessarily I who am to blame. It is clear
\par enough, on the hypothesis which I presuppose, namely, that the reader
\par has first read my previous writings and has not grudged them a certain
\par amount of trouble: it is not, indeed, a simple matter to get really at
\par their essence. Take, for instance, my _Zarathustra_; I allow no one
\par to pass muster as knowing that book, unless every single word therein
\par has at some time wrought in him a profound wound, and at some time
\par exercised on him a profound enchantment: then and not till then can he
\par enjoy the privilege of participating reverently in the halcyon element,
\par from which that work is born, in its sunny brilliance, its distance,
\par its spaciousness, its certainty. In other cases the aphoristic form
\par produces difficulty, but this is only because this form is treated
\par _too casually_. An aphorism properly coined and cast into its final
\par mould is far from being "deciphered" as soon as it has been read; on
\par the contrary, it is then that it first requires _to be expounded_--of
\par course for that purpose an art of exposition is necessary. The third
\par essay in this book provides an example of what is offered, of what in
\par such cases I call exposition: an aphorism is prefixed to that essay,
\par the essay itself is its commentary. Certainly one _quality_ which
\par nowadays has been best forgotten--and that is why it will take some
\par time yet for my writings to become readable--is essential in order
\par to practise reading as an art--a quality for the exercise of which it
\par is necessary to be a cow, and under no circumstances a modern man!--
\par rumination.
\par 
\par Sils-Maria, Upper Engadine, July 1887.
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par FIRST ESSAY. "GOOD AND EVIL," "GOOD AND BAD."
\par 
\par 
\par 1.
\par 
\par Those English psychologists, who up to the present are the only
\par philosophers who are to be thanked for any endeavour to get as far
\par as a history of the origin of morality--these men, I say, offer us
\par in their own personalities no paltry problem;--they even have, if I
\par am to be quite frank about it, in their capacity of living riddles,
\par an advantage over their books--_they themselves are interesting!_
\par These English psychologists--what do they really mean? We always
\par find them voluntarily or involuntarily at the same task of pushing
\par to the front the _partie honteuse_ of our inner world, and looking
\par for the efficient, governing, and decisive principle in that precise
\par quarter where the intellectual self-respect of the race would be
\par the most reluctant to find it (for example, in the _vis inerti\'e6_ of
\par habit, or in forgetfulness, or in a blind and fortuitous mechanism
\par and association of ideas, or in some factor that is purely passive,
\par reflex, molecular, or fundamentally stupid)--what is the real motive
\par power which always impels these psychologists in precisely _this_
\par direction? Is it an instinct for human disparagement somewhat sinister,
\par vulgar, and malignant, or perhaps incomprehensible even to itself? or
\par perhaps a touch of pessimistic jealousy, the mistrust of disillusioned
\par idealists who have become gloomy, poisoned, and bitter? or a petty
\par subconscious enmity and rancour against Christianity (and Plato), that
\par has conceivably never crossed the threshold of consciousness? or just a
\par vicious taste for those elements of life which are bizarre, painfully
\par paradoxical, mystical, and illogical? or, as a final alternative, a
\par dash of each of these motives--a little vulgarity, a little gloominess,
\par a little anti-Christianity, a little craving for the necessary piquancy?
\par 
\par But I am told that it is simply a case of old frigid and tedious frogs
\par crawling and hopping around men and inside men, as if they were as
\par thoroughly at home there, as they would be in a _swamp_.
\par 
\par I am opposed to this statement, nay, I do not believe it; and if, in
\par the impossibility of knowledge, one is permitted to wish, so do I wish
\par from my heart that just the converse metaphor should apply, and that
\par these analysts with their psychological microscopes should be, at
\par bottom, brave, proud, and magnanimous animals who know how to bridle
\par both their hearts and their smarts, and have specifically trained
\par themselves to sacrifice what is desirable to what is true, any truth
\par in fact, even the simple, bitter, ugly, repulsive, unchristian, and
\par immoral truths--for there are truths of that description.
\par 
\par 
\par 2.
\par 
\par All honour, then, to the noble spirits who would fain dominate these
\par historians of morality. But it is certainly a pity that they lack the
\par _historical sense_ itself, that they themselves are quite deserted
\par by all the beneficent spirits of history. The whole train of their
\par thought runs, as was always the way of old-fashioned philosophers, on
\par thoroughly unhistorical lines: there is no doubt on this point. The
\par crass ineptitude of their genealogy of morals is immediately apparent
\par when the question arises of ascertaining the origin of the idea and
\par judgment of "good." "Man had originally," so speaks their decree,
\par "praised and called 'good' altruistic acts from the standpoint of
\par those on whom they were conferred, that is, those to whom they were
\par _useful_; subsequently the origin of this praise was _forgotten_, and
\par altruistic acts, simply because, as a sheer matter of habit, they were
\par praised as good, came also to be felt as good--as though they contained
\par in themselves some intrinsic goodness." The thing is obvious:--this
\par initial derivation contains already all the typical and idiosyncratic
\par traits of the English psychologists--we have "utility," "forgetting,"
\par "habit," and finally "error," the whole assemblage forming the basis
\par of a system of values, on which the higher man has up to the present
\par prided himself as though it were a kind of privilege of man in general.
\par This pride _must_ be brought low, this system of values _must_ lose its
\par values: is that attained?
\par 
\par Now the first argument that comes ready to my hand is that the real
\par homestead of the concept "good" is sought and located in the wrong
\par place: the judgment "good" did not originate among those to whom
\par goodness was shown. Much rather has it been the good themselves,
\par that is, the aristocratic, the powerful, the high-stationed, the
\par high-minded, who have felt that they themselves were good, and that
\par their actions were good, that is to say of the first order, in
\par contradistinction to all the low, the low-minded, the vulgar, and
\par the plebeian. It was out of this pathos of distance that they first
\par arrogated the right to create values for their own profit, and to
\par coin the names of such values: what had they to do with utility? The
\par standpoint of utility is as alien and as inapplicable as it could
\par possibly be, when we have to deal with so volcanic an effervescence of
\par supreme values, creating and demarcating as they do a hierarchy within
\par themselves: it is at this juncture that one arrives at an appreciation
\par of the contrast to that tepid temperature, which is the presupposition
\par on which every combination of worldly wisdom and every calculation of
\par practical expediency is always based--and not for one occasional, not
\par for one exceptional instance, but chronically. The pathos of nobility
\par and distance, as I have said, the chronic and despotic _esprit de
\par corps_ and fundamental instinct of a higher dominant race coming into
\par association with a meaner race, an "under race," this is the origin of
\par the antithesis of good and bad.
\par 
\par (The masters' right of giving names goes so far that it is permissible
\par to look upon language itself as the expression of the power of the
\par masters: they say "this _is_ that, and that," they seal finally every
\par object and every event with a sound, and thereby at the same time take
\par possession of it.) It is because of this origin that the word "good"
\par is far from having any necessary connection with altruistic acts, in
\par accordance with the superstitious belief of these moral philosophers.
\par On the contrary, it is on the occasion of the _decay_ of aristocratic
\par values, that the antitheses between "egoistic" and "altruistic"
\par presses more and more heavily on the human conscience--it is, to use
\par my own language, the _herd instinct_ which finds in this antithesis an
\par expression in many ways. And even then it takes a considerable time
\par for this instinct to become sufficiently dominant, for the valuation
\par to be inextricably dependent on this antithesis (as is the case in
\par contemporary Europe); for to-day that prejudice is predominant, which,
\par acting even now with all the intensity of an obsession and brain
\par disease, holds that "moral," "altruistic," and "_d\'e9sint\'e9ress\'e9_" are
\par concepts of equal value.
\par 
\par 
\par 3.
\par 
\par In the second place, quite apart from the fact that this hypothesis as
\par to the genesis of the value "good" cannot be historically upheld, it
\par suffers from an inherent psychological contradiction. The utility of
\par altruistic conduct has presumably been the origin of its being praised,
\par and this origin has become _forgotten_:--But in what conceivable way is
\par this forgetting _possible_! Has perchance the utility of such conduct
\par ceased at some given moment? The contrary is the case. This utility has
\par rather been experienced every day at all times, and is consequently
\par a feature that obtains a new and regular emphasis with every fresh
\par day; it follows that, so far from vanishing from the consciousness, so
\par far indeed from being forgotten, it must necessarily become impressed
\par on the consciousness with ever-increasing distinctness. How much
\par more logical is that contrary theory (it is not the truer for that)
\par which is represented, for instance, by Herbert Spencer, who places
\par the concept "good" as essentially similar to the concept "useful,"
\par "purposive," so that in the judgments "good" and "bad" mankind is
\par simply summarising and investing with a sanction its _unforgotten_ and
\par _unforgettable_ experiences concerning the "useful-purposive" and the
\par "mischievous-non-purposive." According to this theory, "good" is the
\par attribute of that which has previously shown itself useful; and so
\par is able to claim to be considered "valuable in the highest degree,"
\par "valuable in itself." This method of explanation is also, as I have
\par said, wrong, but at any rate the explanation itself is coherent, and
\par psychologically tenable.
\par 
\par 
\par 4.
\par 
\par The guide-post which first put me on the right track was this
\par question--what is the true etymological significance of the various
\par symbols for the idea "good" which have been coined in the various
\par languages? I then found that they all led back to _the same evolution
\par of the same idea_--that everywhere "aristocrat," "noble" (in the
\par social sense), is the root idea, out of which have necessarily
\par developed "good" in the sense of "with aristocratic soul," "noble,"
\par in the sense of "with a soul of high calibre," "with a privileged
\par soul"--a development which invariably runs parallel with that other
\par evolution by which "vulgar," "plebeian," "low," are made to change
\par finally into "bad." The most eloquent proof of this last contention
\par is the German word "_schlecht_" itself: this word is identical with
\par "_schlicht_"--(compare "_schlechtweg_" and "_schlechterdings_")--which,
\par originally and as yet without any sinister innuendo, simply denoted
\par the plebeian man in contrast to the aristocratic man. It is at the
\par sufficiently late period of the Thirty Years' War that this sense
\par becomes changed to the sense now current. From the standpoint of
\par the Genealogy of Morals this discovery seems to be substantial: the
\par lateness of it is to be attributed to the retarding influence exercised
\par in the modern world by democratic prejudice in the sphere of all
\par questions of origin. This extends, as will shortly be shown, even to
\par the province of natural science and physiology, which, _prima facie_
\par is the most objective. The extent of the mischief which is caused by
\par this prejudice (once it is free of all trammels except those of its own
\par malice), particularly to Ethics and History, is shown by the notorious
\par case of Buckle: it was in Buckle that that _plebeianism_ of the modern
\par spirit, which is of English origin, broke out once again from its
\par malignant soil with all the violence of a slimy volcano, and with that
\par salted, rampant, and vulgar eloquence with which up to the present time
\par all volcanoes have spoken.
\par 
\par 
\par 5.
\par 
\par With regard to our problem, which can justly be called an intimate
\par problem, and which elects to appeal to only a limited number of ears:
\par it is of no small interest to ascertain that in those words and roots
\par which denote "good" we catch glimpses of that arch-trait, on the
\par strength of which the aristocrats feel themselves to be beings of
\par a higher order than their fellows. Indeed, they call themselves in
\par perhaps the most frequent instances simply after their superiority
\par in power (_e.g._ "the powerful," "the lords," "the commanders"), or
\par after the most obvious sign of their superiority, as for example
\par "the rich," "the possessors" (that is the meaning of _arya_; and the
\par Iranian and Slav languages correspond). But they also call themselves
\par after some _characteristic idiosyncrasy_; and this is the case which
\par now concerns us. They name themselves, for instance, "the truthful":
