\par of the contradiction, with which he was confronted, by the Homeric
\par world, an age magnificent indeed, but at the same time so awful and
\par so violent, by making two ages out of one, which he henceforth placed
\par one behind each other--first, the age of the heroes and demigods, as
\par that world had remained in the memories of the aristocratic families,
\par who found therein their own ancestors; secondly, the bronze age, as
\par that corresponding age appeared to the descendants of the oppressed,
\par spoiled, ill-treated, exiled, enslaved; namely, as an age of bronze,
\par as I have said, hard, cold, terrible, without feelings and without
\par conscience, crushing everything, and bespattering everything with
\par blood. Granted the truth of the theory now believed to be true, that
\par the very _essence of all civilisation_ is to _train_ out of man, the
\par beast of prey, a tame and civilised animal, a domesticated animal,
\par it follows indubitably that we must regard as the real _tools of
\par civilisation_ all those instincts of reaction and resentment, by the
\par help of which the aristocratic races, together with their ideals,
\par were finally degraded and overpowered; though that has not yet come
\par to be synonymous with saying that the bearers of those tools also
\par _represented_ the civilisation. It is rather the contrary that is
\par not only probable--nay, it is _palpable_ to-day; these bearers of
\par vindictive instincts that have to be bottled up, these descendants of
\par all European and non-European slavery, especially of the pre-Aryan
\par population--these people, I say, represent the _decline_ of humanity!
\par These "tools of civilisation" are a disgrace to humanity, and
\par constitute in reality more of an argument against civilisation, more
\par of a reason why civilisation should be suspected. One may be perfectly
\par justified in being always afraid of the blonde beast that lies at
\par the core of all aristocratic races, and in being on one's guard: but
\par who would not a hundred times prefer to be afraid, when one at the
\par same time admires, than to be immune from fear, at the cost of being
\par perpetually obsessed with the loathsome spectacle of the distorted, the
\par dwarfed, the stunted, the envenomed? And is that not our fate? What
\par produces to-day our repulsion towards "man"?--for we _suffer_ from
\par "man," there is no doubt about it. It is not fear; it is rather that
\par we have nothing more to fear from men; it is that the worm "man" is in
\par the foreground and pullulates; it is that the "tame man," the wretched
\par mediocre and unedifying creature, has learnt to consider himself a goal
\par and a pinnacle, an inner meaning, an historic principle, a "higher
\par man"; yes, it is that he has a certain right so to consider himself,
\par in so far as he feels that in contrast to that excess of deformity,
\par disease, exhaustion, and effeteness whose odour is beginning to pollute
\par present-day Europe, he at any rate has achieved a relative success, he
\par at any rate still says "yes" to life.
\par 
\par 
\par 12.
\par 
\par I cannot refrain at this juncture from uttering a sigh and one last
\par hope. What is it precisely which I find intolerable? That which I alone
\par cannot get rid of, which makes me choke and faint? Bad air! bad air!
\par That something misbegotten comes near me; that I must inhale the odour
\par of the entrails of a misbegotten soul!--That excepted, what can one
\par not endure in the way of need, privation, bad weather, sickness, toil,
\par solitude? In point of fact, one manages to get over everything, born
\par as one is to a burrowing and battling existence; one always returns
\par once again to the light, one always lives again one's golden hour of
\par victory--and then one stands as one was born, unbreakable, tense, ready
\par for something more difficult, for something more distant, like a bow
\par stretched but the tauter by every strain. But from time to time do ye
\par grant me--assuming that "beyond good and evil" there are goddesses who
\par can grant--one glimpse, grant me but one glimpse only, of something
\par perfect, fully realised, happy, mighty, triumphant, of something
\par that still gives cause for fear! A glimpse of a man that justifies
\par the existence of man, a glimpse of an incarnate human happiness that
\par realises and redeems, for the sake of which one may hold fast to _the
\par belief in man_! For the position is this: in the dwarfing and levelling
\par of the European man lurks _our_ greatest peril, for it is this outlook
\par which fatigues--we see to-day nothing which wishes to be greater, we
\par surmise that the process is always still backwards, still backwards
\par towards something more attenuated, more inoffensive, more cunning,
\par more comfortable, more mediocre, more indifferent, more Chinese, more
\par Christian--man, there is no doubt about it, grows always "better"
\par --the destiny of Europe lies even in this--that in losing the fear of
\par man, we have also lost the hope in man, yea, the will to be man. The
\par sight of man now fatigues.--What is present-day Nihilism if it is not
\par _that_?--We are tired of _man_.
\par 
\par 
\par 13.
\par 
\par But let us come back to it; the problem of another origin of the
\par _good_--of the good, as the resentful man has thought it out--demands
\par its solution. It is not surprising that the lambs should bear a grudge
\par against the great birds of prey, but that is no reason for blaming the
\par great birds of prey for taking the little lambs. And when the lambs
\par say among themselves, "These birds of prey are evil, and he who is as
\par far removed from being a bird of prey, who is rather its opposite,
\par a lamb,--is he not good?" then there is nothing to cavil at in the
\par setting up of this ideal, though it may also be that the birds of prey
\par will regard it a little sneeringly, and perchance say to themselves,
\par "_We_ bear no grudge against them, these good lambs, we even like them:
\par nothing is tastier than a tender lamb." To require of strength that it
\par should not express itself as strength, that it should not be a wish to
\par overpower, a wish to overthrow, a wish to become master, a thirst for
\par enemies and antagonisms and triumphs, is just as absurd as to require
\par of weakness that it should express itself as strength. A quantum of
\par force is just such a quantum of movement, will, action--rather it
\par is nothing else than just those very phenomena of moving, willing,
\par acting, and can only appear otherwise in the misleading errors of
\par language (and the fundamental fallacies of reason which have become
\par petrified therein), which understands, and understands wrongly, all
\par working as conditioned by a worker, by a "subject." And just exactly
\par as the people separate the lightning from its flash, and interpret the
\par latter as a thing done, as the working of a subject which is called
\par lightning, so also does the popular morality separate strength from the
\par expression of strength, as though behind the strong man there existed
\par some indifferent neutral _substratum_, which enjoyed a _caprice and
\par option_ as to whether or not it should express strength. But there
\par is no such _substratum_, there is no "being" behind doing, working,
\par becoming; "the doer" is a mere appanage to the action. The action is
\par everything. In point of fact, the people duplicate the doing, when they
\par make the lightning lighten, that is a "doing-doing": they make the same
\par phenomenon first a cause, and then, secondly, the effect of that cause.
\par The scientists fail to improve matters when they say, "Force moves,
\par force causes," and so on. Our whole science is still, in spite of all
\par its coldness, of all its freedom from passion, a dupe of the tricks of
\par language, and has never succeeded in getting rid of that superstitious
\par changeling "the subject" (the atom, to give another instance, is such
\par a changeling, just as the Kantian "Thing-in-itself"). What wonder,
\par if the suppressed and stealthily simmering passions of revenge and
\par hatred exploit for their own advantage this belief, and indeed hold no
\par belief with a more steadfast enthusiasm than this--"that the strong
\par has the _option_ of being weak, and the bird of prey of being a lamb."
\par Thereby do they win for themselves the right of attributing to the
\par birds of prey the _responsibility_ for being birds of prey: when the
\par oppressed, down-trodden, and overpowered say to themselves with the
\par vindictive guile of weakness, "Let us be otherwise than the evil,
\par namely, good! and good is every one who does not oppress, who hurts
\par no one, who does not attack, who does not pay back, who hands over
\par revenge to God, who holds himself, as we do, in hiding; who goes out
\par of the way of evil, and demands, in short, little from life; like
\par ourselves the patient, the meek, the just,"--yet all this, in its cold
\par and unprejudiced interpretation, means nothing more than "once for
\par all, the weak are weak; it is good to do _nothing for which we are not
\par strong enough_"; but this dismal state of affairs, this prudence of the
\par lowest order, which even insects possess (which in a great danger are
\par fain to sham death so as to avoid doing "too much"), has, thanks to
\par the counterfeiting and self-deception of weakness, come to masquerade
\par in the pomp of an ascetic, mute, and expectant virtue, just as though
\par the _very_ weakness of the weak--that is, forsooth, its _being_, its
\par working, its whole unique inevitable inseparable reality--were a
\par voluntary result, something wished, chosen, a deed, an act of _merit_.
\par This kind of man finds the belief in a neutral, free-choosing "subject"
\par _necessary_ from an instinct of self-preservation, of self-assertion,
\par in which every lie is fain to sanctify itself. The subject (or, to
\par use popular language, the _soul_) has perhaps proved itself the best
\par dogma in the world simply because it rendered possible to the horde
\par of mortal, weak, and oppressed individuals of every kind, that most
\par sublime specimen of self-deception, the interpretation of weakness as
\par freedom, of being this, or being that, as _merit_.
\par 
\par 
\par 14.
\par 
\par Will any one look a little into--right into--the mystery of how _ideals
\par are manufactured_ in this world? Who has the courage to do it? Come!
\par 
\par Here we have a vista opened into these grimy workshops. Wait just a
\par moment, dear Mr. Inquisitive and Foolhardy; your eye must first grow
\par accustomed to this false changing light--Yes! Enough! Now speak! What
\par is happening below down yonder? Speak out that what you see, man of the
\par most dangerous curiosity--for now _I_ am the listener.
\par 
\par "I see nothing, I hear the more. It is a cautious, spiteful, gentle
\par whispering and muttering together in all the corners and crannies. It
\par seems to me that they are lying; a sugary softness adheres to every
\par sound. Weakness is turned to _merit_, there is no doubt about it--it is
\par just as you say."
\par 
\par Further!
\par 
\par "And the impotence which requites not, is turned to 'goodness,' craven
\par baseness to meekness, submission to those whom one hates, to obedience
\par (namely, obedience to one of whom they say that he ordered this
\par submission--they call him God). The inoffensive character of the weak,
\par the very cowardice in which he is rich, his standing at the door, his
\par forced necessity of waiting, gain here fine names, such as 'patience,'
\par which is also called 'virtue'; not being able to avenge one's self, is
\par called not wishing to avenge one's self, perhaps even forgiveness (for
\par _they_ know not what they do--we alone know what _they_ do). They also
\par talk of the 'love of their enemies' and sweat thereby."
\par 
\par Further!
\par 
\par "They are miserable, there is no doubt about it, all these whisperers
\par and counterfeiters in the corners, although they try to get warm by
\par crouching close to each other, but they tell me that their misery is
\par a favour and distinction given to them by God, just as one beats the
\par dogs one likes best; that perhaps this misery is also a preparation, a
\par probation, a training; that perhaps it is still more something which
\par will one day be compensated and paid back with a tremendous interest in
\par gold, nay in happiness. This they call 'Blessedness.'"
\par 
\par Further!
\par 
\par "They are now giving me to understand, that not only are they better
\par men than the mighty, the lords of the earth, whose spittle they have
\par got to lick (not out of fear, not at all out of fear! But because
\par God ordains that one should honour all authority)--not only are they
\par better men, but that they also have a 'better time,' at any rate,
\par will one day have a 'better time.' But enough! Enough! I can endure
\par it no longer. Bad air! Bad air! These workshops _where ideals are
\par manufactured_--verily they reek with the crassest lies."
\par 
\par Nay. Just one minute! You are saying nothing about the masterpieces
\par of these virtuosos of black magic, who can produce whiteness, milk,
\par and innocence out of any black you like: have you not noticed what a
\par pitch of refinement is attained by their _chef d'\'9cuvre_, their most
\par audacious, subtle, ingenious, and lying artist-trick? Take care! These
\par cellar-beasts, full of revenge and hate--what do they make, forsooth,
\par out of their revenge and hate? Do you hear these words? Would you
\par suspect, if you trusted only their words, that you are among men of
\par resentment and nothing else?
\par 
\par "I understand, I prick my ears up again (ah! ah! ah! and I hold my
\par nose). Now do I hear for the first time that which they have said so
\par often: 'We good, _we are the righteous_'--what they demand they call
\par not revenge but 'the triumph of _righteousness_'; what they hate is
\par not their enemy, no, they hate 'unrighteousness,' 'godlessness'; what
\par they believe in and hope is not the hope of revenge, the intoxication
\par of sweet revenge (--"sweeter than honey," did Homer call it?), but the
\par victory of God, of the _righteous_ _God_ over the 'godless'; what is
\par left for them to love in this world is not _their_ brothers in hate,
\par but their 'brothers in love,' as they say, all the good and righteous
\par on the earth."
\par 
\par And how do they name that which serves them as a solace against all
\par the troubles of life--their phantasmagoria of their anticipated future
\par blessedness?
\par 
\par "How? Do I hear right? They call it 'the last judgment,' the advent of
\par their kingdom, 'the kingdom of God'--but _in the meanwhile_ they live
\par 'in faith,' 'in love,' 'in hope.'"
\par 
\par Enough! Enough!
\par 
\par 
\par 15.
\par 
\par In the faith in what? In the love for what? In the hope of what? These
\par weaklings!--they also, forsooth, wish to be the strong some time; there
\par is no doubt about it, some time _their_ kingdom also must come--"the
\par kingdom of God" is their name for it, as has been mentioned: they are
\par so meek in everything! Yet in order to experience _that_ kingdom it
\par is necessary to live long, to live beyond death,--yes, _eternal_ life
\par is necessary so that one can make up for ever for that earthly life
\par "in faith," "in love," "in hope." Make up for what? Make up by what?
\par Dante, as it seems to me, made a crass mistake when with awe-inspiring
\par ingenuity he placed that inscription over the gate of his hell, "Me too
\par made eternal love": at any rate the following inscription would have
\par a much better right to stand over the gate of the Christian Paradise
\par and its "eternal blessedness"--"Me too made eternal hate"--granted
\par of course that a truth may rightly stand over the gate to a lie! For
\par what is the blessedness of that Paradise? Possibly we could quickly
\par surmise it; but it is better that it should be explicitly attested by
\par an authority who in such matters is not to be disparaged, Thomas of
\par Aquinas, the great teacher and saint. "_Beati in regno celesti_" says
\par he, as gently as a lamb, "_videbunt p\'9cnas damnatorum, ut beatitudo
\par illis magis complaceat_." Or if we wish to hear a stronger tone, a word
\par from the mouth of a triumphant father of the Church, who warned his
\par disciples against the cruel ecstasies of the public spectacles--But
\par why? Faith offers us much more,--says he, _de Spectac._, c. 29
\par ss.,--something much stronger; thanks to the redemption, joys of quite
\par another kind stand at our disposal; instead of athletes we have our
\par martyrs; we wish for blood, well, we have the blood of Christ--but
\par what then awaits us on the day of his return, of his triumph. And
\par then does he proceed, does this enraptured visionary: "_at enim
\par supersunt alia spectacula, ille ultimas et perpetuus judicii dies, ille
\par nationibus insperatus, ille derisus, cum tanta s\'e6culi vetustas et tot
\par ejus nativitates uno igne haurientur. Qu\'e6 tunc spectaculi latitudo!
\par Quid admirer! quid rideam! Ubigaudeam! Ubi exultem, spectans tot et
\par tantos reges, qui in c\'9clum recepti nuntiabantur, cum ipso Jove et ipsis
\par suis testibus in imis tenebris congemescentes! Item pr\'e6sides_" (the
\par provincial governors) "_persecutores dominici nominis s\'e6vioribus quam
\par ipsi flammis s\'e6vierunt insultantibus contra Christianos liquescentes!
\par Quos pr\'e6terea sapientes illos philosophos coram discipulis suis una
\par conflagrantibus erubescentes, quibus nihil ad deum pertinere suadebant,
\par quibus animas aut nullas aut non in pristina corpora redituras
\par affirmabant! Etiam poetas non ad Rhadamanti nec ad Minois, sed ad
\par inopinati Christi tribunal palpitantes! Tunc magis trag\'9cdi audiendi,
\par magis scilicet vocales_" (with louder tones and more violent shrieks)
\par "_in sua propria calamitate; tunc histriones cognoscendi, solutiores
\par multo per ignem; tunc spectandus auriga in flammea rota totus rubens,
\par tunc xystici contemplandi non in gymnasiis, sed in igne jaculati, nisi
\par quod ne tunc quidem illos velim vivos, ut qui malim ad eos potius
\par conspectum insatiabilem conferre, qui in dominum scevierunt. Hic est
\par ille, dicam fabri aut qu\'e6stuari\'e6 filius_" (as is shown by the whole of
\par the following, and in particular by this well-known description of the
\par mother of Jesus from the Talmud, Tertullian is henceforth referring to
\par the Jews), "_sabbati destructor, Samarites et d\'e6monium habens. Hic est
\par quem a Juda redemistis, hic est ille arundine et colaphis diverberatus,
\par sputamentis de decoratus, felle et acete potatus. Hic est, quem
\par clam discentes subripuerunt, ut resurrexisse dicatur vel hortulanus
\par detraxit, ne lactuc\'e6 su\'e6 frequentia commeantium laderentur. Ut talia
\par species, ut talibus exultes, quis tibi pr\'e6tor aut consul aut sacerdos
\par de sua liberalitate prastabit? Et tamen h\'e6c jam habemus quodammodo per
\par fidem spiritu imaginante repr\'e6sentata. Ceterum qualia illa sunt, qu\'e6
\par nec oculus vidit nec auris audivit nec in cor hominis ascenderunt?_" (I
\par Cor. ii. 9.) "_Credo circo et utraque cavea_" (first and fourth row,
\par or, according to others, the comic and the tragic stage) "_et omni
\par studio gratiora._" _Per fidem_: so stands it written.
\par 
\par 
\par 16.
\par 
\par Let us come to a conclusion. The two _opposing values_, "good and bad,"
\par "good and evil," have fought a dreadful, thousand-year fight in the
\par world, and though indubitably the second value has been for a long time
\par in the preponderance, there are not wanting places where the fortune
\par of the fight is still undecisive. It can almost be said that in the
\par meanwhile the fight reaches a higher and higher level, and that in the
\par meanwhile it has become more and more intense, and always more and more
\par psychological; so that nowadays there is perhaps no more decisive mark
\par of the _higher nature_, of the more psychological nature, than to be in
\par that sense self-contradictory, and to be actually still a battleground
\par for those two opposites. The symbol of this fight, written in a writing
\par which has remained worthy of perusal throughout the course of history
\par up to the present time, is called "Rome against Jud\'e6a, Jud\'e6a against
\par Rome." Hitherto there has been no greater event than _that_ fight,
\par the putting of _that_ question, _that_ deadly antagonism. Rome found
\par in the Jew the incarnation of the unnatural, as though it were its
\par diametrically opposed monstrosity, and in Rome the Jew was held to
\par be _convicted of hatred_ of the whole human race: and rightly so, in
\par so far as it is right to link the well-being and the future of the
\par human race to the unconditional mastery of the aristocratic values, of
\par the Roman values. What, conversely, did the Jews feel against Rome?
\par One can surmise it from a thousand symptoms, but it is sufficient to
\par carry one's mind back to the Johannian Apocalypse, that most obscene
\par of all the written outbursts, which has revenge on its conscience.
\par (One should also appraise at its full value the profound logic of the
\par Christian instinct, when over this very book of hate it wrote the name
\par of the Disciple of Love, that self-same disciple to whom it attributed
\par that impassioned and ecstatic Gospel--therein lurks a portion of
\par truth, however much literary forging may have been necessary for
\par this purpose.) The Romans were the strong and aristocratic; a nation
\par stronger and more aristocratic has never existed in the world, has
\par never even been dreamed of; every relic of them, every inscription
\par enraptures, granted that one can divine _what_ it is that writes the
\par inscription. The Jews, conversely, were that priestly nation of
\par resentment par excellence, possessed by a unique genius for popular
\par morals: just compare with the Jews the nations with analogous gifts,
\par such as the Chinese or the Germans, so as to realise afterwards what is
\par first rate, and what is fifth rate.
\par 
\par Which of them has been provisionally victorious, Rome or Jud\'e6a? but
\par there is not a shadow of doubt; just consider to whom in Rome itself
\par nowadays you bow down, as though before the quintessence of all the
\par highest values--and not only in Rome, but almost over half the world,
\par everywhere where man has been tamed or is about to be tamed--to _three
\par Jews_, as we know, and _one Jewess_ (to Jesus of Nazareth, to Peter
\par the fisher, to Paul the tent-maker, and to the mother of the aforesaid
\par Jesus, named Mary). This is very remarkable: Rome is undoubtedly
\par defeated. At any rate there took place in the Renaissance a brilliantly
\par sinister revival of the classical ideal, of the aristocratic valuation
\par of all things: Rome herself, like a man waking up from a trance,
\par stirred beneath the burden of the new Judaised Rome that had been built
\par over her, which presented the appearance of an \'9ccumenical synagogue
\par and was called the "Church": but immediately Jud\'e6a triumphed again,
\par thanks to that fundamentally popular (German and English) movement
\par of revenge, which is called the Reformation, and taking also into
\par account its inevitable corollary, the restoration of the Church--the
\par restoration also of the ancient graveyard peace of classical Rome.
\par Jud\'e6a proved yet once more victorious over the classical ideal in the
\par French Revolution, and in a sense which was even more crucial and even
\par more profound: the last political aristocracy that existed in Europe,
\par that of the _French_ seventeenth and eighteenth centuries, broke into
\par pieces beneath the instincts of a resentful populace--never had the
\par world heard a greater jubilation, a more uproarious enthusiasm: indeed,
\par there took place in the midst of it the most monstrous and unexpected
\par phenomenon; the ancient ideal _itself_ swept before the eyes and
\par conscience of humanity with all its life and with unheard-of splendour,
\par and in opposition to resentment's lying war-cry of _the prerogative
\par of the most_, in opposition to the will to lowliness, abasement, and
\par equalisation, the will to a retrogression and twilight of humanity,
\par there rang out once again, stronger, simpler, more penetrating than
\par ever, the terrible and enchanting counter-warcry of _the prerogative of
\par the few_! Like a final signpost to other ways, there appeared Napoleon,
\par the most unique and violent anachronism that ever existed, and in him
\par the incarnate problem _of the aristocratic ideal in itself_--consider
\par well what a problem it is:--Napoleon, that synthesis of Monster and
\par Superman.
\par 
\par 
\par 17.
\par 
\par Was it therewith over? Was that greatest of all antitheses of ideals
\par thereby relegated _ad acta_ for all time? Or only postponed, postponed
\par for a long time? May there not take place at some time or other a
\par much more awful, much more carefully prepared flaring up of the old
\par conflagration? Further! Should not one wish _that_ consummation with
\par all one's strength?--will it one's self? demand it one's self? He who
\par at this juncture begins, like my readers, to reflect, to think further,
\par will have difficulty in coming quickly to a conclusion,--ground enough
\par for me to come myself to a conclusion, taking it for granted that for
\par some time past what I mean has been sufficiently clear, what I exactly
\par _mean_ by that dangerous motto which is inscribed on the body of my
\par last book: _Beyond Good and Evil_--at any rate that is not the same as
\par "Beyond Good and Bad."
\par 
\par 
\par Note.--I avail myself of the opportunity offered by this treatise to
\par express, openly and formally, a wish which up to the present has only
\par been expressed in occasional conversations with scholars, namely,
\par that some Faculty of philosophy should, by means of a series of prize
\par essays, gain the glory of having promoted the further study of the
\par _history of morals_--perhaps this book may serve to give forcible
\par impetus in such a direction. With regard to a possibility of this
\par character, the following question deserves consideration. It merits
\par quite as much the attention of philologists and historians as of actual
\par professional philosophers.
\par 
\par "_What indication of the history of the evolution of the moral ideas is
\par afforded by philology, and especially by etymological investigation?_"
\par 
\par On the other hand, it is of course equally necessary to induce
\par physiologists and doctors to be interested in these problems (_of the
\par value of the valuations_ which have prevailed up to the present): in
\par this connection the professional philosophers may be trusted to act
\par as the spokesmen and intermediaries in these particular instances,
\par after, of course, they have quite succeeded in transforming the
\par relationship between philosophy and physiology and medicine, which
\par is originally one of coldness and suspicion, into the most friendly
\par and fruitful reciprocity. In point of fact, all tables of values,
\par all the "thou shalts" known to history and ethnology, need primarily
\par a _physiological_, at any rate in preference to a psychological,
\par elucidation and interpretation; all equally require a critique from
\par medical science. The question, "What is the _value_ of this or that
\par table of 'values' and morality?" will be asked from the most varied
\par standpoints. For instance, the question of "valuable _for what_" can
\par never be analysed with sufficient nicety. That, for instance, which
\par would evidently have value with regard to promoting in a race the
\par greatest possible powers of endurance (or with regard to increasing its
\par adaptability to a specific climate, or with regard to the preservation
\par of the greatest number) would have nothing like the same value, if it
\par were a question of evolving a stronger species. In gauging values,
\par the good of the majority and the good of the minority are opposed
\par standpoints: we leave it to the na\'efvet\'e9 of English biologists to regard
\par the former standpoint as _intrinsically_ superior. _All_ the sciences
\par have now to pave the way for the future task of the philosopher; this
\par task being understood to mean, that he must solve the problem of
\par _value_, that he has to fix the _hierarchy of values_.
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par SECOND ESSAY. "GUILT," "BAD CONSCIENCE," AND THE LIKE.
\par 
\par 
\par 1.
\par 
\par The breeding of an animal that _can promise_--is not this just that
\par very paradox of a task which nature has set itself in regard to man? Is
\par not this the very problem of man? The fact that this problem has been
\par to a great extent solved, must appear all the more phenomenal to one
\par who can estimate at its full value that force of _forgetfulness_ which
\par works in opposition to it. Forgetfulness is no mere _vis inerti\'e6_,
\par as the superficial believe, rather is it a power of obstruction,
\par active and, in the strictest sense of the word, positive--a power
\par responsible for the fact that what we have lived, experienced, taken
\par into ourselves, no more enters into consciousness during the process
\par of digestion (it might be called psychic absorption) than all the
\par whole manifold process by which our physical nutrition, the so-called
\par "incorporation," is carried on. The temporary shutting of the doors
\par and windows of consciousness, the relief from the clamant alarums and
\par excursions, with which our subconscious world of servant organs works
\par in mutual co-operation and antagonism; a little quietude, a little
\par _tabula rasa_ of the consciousness, so as to make room again for the
\par new, and above all for the more noble functions and functionaries, room
\par for government, foresight, predetermination (for our organism is on an
\par oligarchic model)--this is the utility, as I have said, of the active
\par forgetfulness, which is a very sentinel and nurse of psychic order,
\par repose, etiquette; and this shows at once why it is that there can
\par exist no happiness, no gladness, no hope, no pride, no real _present_,
\par without forgetfulness. The man in whom this preventative apparatus is
\par damaged and discarded, is to be compared to a dyspeptic, and it is
\par something more than a comparison--he can "get rid of" nothing. But
\par this very animal who finds it necessary to be forgetful, in whom, in
\par fact, forgetfulness represents a force and a form of _robust_ health,
\par has reared for himself an opposition-power, a memory, with whose help
\par forgetfulness is, in certain instances, kept in check--in the cases,
\par namely, where promises have to be made;--so that it is by no means
\par a mere passive inability to get rid of a once indented impression,
\par not merely the indigestion occasioned by a once pledged word, which
\par one cannot dispose of, but an _active_ refusal to get rid of it, a
\par continuing and a wish to continue what has once been willed, an actual
\par _memory of the will_; so that between the original "I will," "I shall
\par do," and the actual discharge of the will, its act, we can easily
\par interpose a world of new strange phenomena, circumstances, veritable
\par volitions, without the snapping of this long chain of the will. But
\par what is the underlying hypothesis of all this? How thoroughly, in order
\par to be able to regulate the future in this way, must man have first
\par learnt to distinguish between necessitated and accidental phenomena, to
\par think causally, to see the distant as present and to anticipate it, to
\par fix with certainty what is the end, and what is the means to that end;
\par above all, to reckon, to have power to calculate--how thoroughly must
\par man have first become _calculable, disciplined, necessitated_ even for
\par himself and his own conception of himself, that, like a man entering
\par into a promise, he could guarantee himself _as a future_.
\par 
\par 
\par 2.
\par 
\par This is simply the long history of the origin of _responsibility_.
\par That task of breeding an animal which can make promises, includes, as
\par we have already grasped, as its condition and preliminary, the more
\par immediate task of first _making_ man to a certain extent, necessitated,
\par uniform, like among his like, regular, and consequently calculable. The
\par immense work of what I have called, "morality of custom"[1] (cp. _Dawn
\par of Day_, Aphs. 9, 14, and 16), the actual work of man on himself during
\par the longest period of the human race, his whole prehistoric work,
\par finds its meaning, its great justification (in spite of all its innate
\par hardness, despotism, stupidity, and idiocy) in this fact: man, with
\par the help of the morality of customs and of social strait-waistcoats,
\par was _made_ genuinely calculable. If, however, we place ourselves at
\par the end of this colossal process, at the point where the tree finally
\par matures its fruits, when society and its morality of custom finally
\par bring to light that to which it was only the means, then do we find as
\par the ripest fruit on its tree the _sovereign individual_, that resembles
\par only himself, that has got loose from the morality of custom, the
\par autonomous "super-moral" individual (for "autonomous" and "moral" are
\par mutually-exclusive terms),--in short, the man of the personal, long,
\par and independent will, _competent to promise_, and we find in him a
\par proud consciousness (vibrating in every fibre), of _what_ has been at
\par last achieved and become vivified in him, a genuine consciousness of
\par power and freedom, a feeling of human perfection in general. And this
\par man who has grown to freedom, who is really _competent_ to promise,
\par this lord of the _free_ will, this sovereign--how is it possible for
\par him not to know how great is his superiority over everything incapable
\par of binding itself by promises, or of being its own security, how great
\par is the trust, the awe, the reverence that he awakes--he "deserves"
\par all three--not to know that with this mastery over himself he is
\par necessarily also given the mastery over circumstances, over nature,
\par over all creatures with shorter wills, less reliable characters?
\par The "free" man, the owner of a long unbreakable will, finds in this
\par possession his _standard of value_: looking out from himself upon
\par the others, he honours or he despises, and just as necessarily as he
\par honours his peers, the strong and the reliable (those who can bind
\par themselves by promises),--that is, every one who promises like a
\par sovereign, with difficulty, rarely and slowly, who is sparing with his
\par trusts but confers _honour_ by the very fact of trusting, who gives
\par his word as something that can be relied on, because he knows himself
\par strong enough to keep it even in the teeth of disasters, even in the
\par "teeth of fate,"--so with equal necessity will he have the heel of his
\par foot ready for the lean and empty jackasses, who promise when they have
\par no business to do so, and his rod of chastisement ready for the liar,
\par who already breaks his word at the very minute when it is on his lips.
\par The proud knowledge of the extraordinary privilege of _responsibility_,
\par the consciousness of this rare freedom, of this power over himself and
\par over fate, has sunk right down to his innermost depths, and has become
\par an instinct, a dominating instinct--what name will he give to it, to
\par this dominating instinct, if he needs to have a word for it? But there
\par is no doubt about it--the sovereign man calls it his _conscience_.
\par 
\par 
\par 3.
\par 
\par His conscience?--One apprehends at once that the idea "conscience,"
\par which is here seen in its supreme manifestation, supreme in fact to
\par almost the point of strangeness, should already have behind it a long
\par history and evolution. The ability to guarantee one's self with all
\par due pride, and also at the same time to _say yes_ to one's self--that
\par is, as has been said, a ripe fruit, but also a _late_ fruit:--How long
\par must needs this fruit hang sour and bitter on the tree! And for an even
\par longer period there was not a glimpse of such a fruit to to be had--no
\par one had taken it on himself to promise it, although everything on the
\par tree was quite ready for it, and everything was maturing for that very
\par consummation. "How is a memory to be made for the man-animal? How is an
\par impression to be so deeply fixed upon this ephemeral understanding,
\par half dense, and half silly, upon this incarnate forgetfulness, that
\par it will be permanently present?" As one may imagine, this primeval
\par problem was not solved by exactly gentle answers and gentle means;
\par perhaps there is nothing more awful and more sinister in the early
\par history of man than his _system of mnemonics_. "Something is burnt in
\par so as to remain in his memory: only that which never stops _hurting_
\par remains in his memory." This is an axiom of the oldest (unfortunately
\par also the longest) psychology in the world. It might even be said that
\par wherever solemnity, seriousness, mystery, and gloomy colours are now
\par found in the life of the men and of nations of the world, there is some
\par _survival_ of that horror which was once the universal concomitant of
\par all promises, pledges, and obligations. The past, the past with all
\par its length, depth, and hardness, wafts to us its breath, and bubbles
\par up in us again, when we become "serious." When man thinks it necessary
\par to make for himself a memory, he never accomplishes it without blood,
\par tortures, and sacrifice; the most dreadful sacrifices and forfeitures
\par (among them the sacrifice of the first-born), the most loathsome
\par mutilation (for instance, castration), the most cruel rituals of all
\par the religious cults (for all religions are really at bottom systems
\par of cruelty)--all these things originate from that instinct which
\par found in pain its most potent mnemonic. In a certain sense the whole
\par of asceticism is to be ascribed to this: certain ideas have got to
\par be made inextinguishable, omnipresent, "fixed," with the object of
\par hypnotising the whole nervous and intellectual system through these
\par "fixed ideas"--and the ascetic methods and modes of life are the means
\par of freeing those ideas from the competition of all other ideas so as to
\par make them "unforgettable." The worse memory man had, the ghastlier the
\par signs presented by his customs; the severity of the penal laws affords
\par in particular a gauge of the extent of man's difficulty in conquering
\par forgetfulness, and in keeping a few primal postulates of social
\par intercourse ever present to the minds of those who were the slaves
\par of every momentary emotion and every momentary desire. We Germans do
\par certainly not regard ourselves as an especially cruel and hard-hearted
\par nation, still less as an especially casual and happy-go-lucky one;
\par but one has only to look at our old penal ordinances in order to
\par realise what a lot of trouble it takes in the world to evolve a
\par "nation of thinkers" (I mean: _the_ European nation which exhibits at
\par this very day the maximum of reliability, seriousness, bad taste, and
\par positiveness, which has on the strength of these qualities a right to
\par train every kind of European mandarin). These Germans employed terrible
\par means to make for themselves a memory, to enable them to master their
\par rooted plebeian instincts and the brutal crudity of those instincts:
\par think of the old German punishments, for instance, stoning (as far back
\par as the legend, the millstone falls on the head of the guilty man),
\par breaking on the wheel (the most original invention and speciality of
\par the German genius in the sphere of punishment), dart-throwing, tearing,
\par or trampling by horses ("quartering"), boiling the criminal in oil or
\par wine (still prevalent in the fourteenth and fifteenth centuries), the
\par highly popular flaying ("slicing into strips"), cutting the flesh out
\par of the breast; think also of the evil-doer being besmeared with honey,
\par and then exposed to the flies in a blazing sun. It was by the help of
\par such images and precedents that man eventually kept in his memory five
\par or six "I will nots" with regard to which he had already given his
\par _promise_, so as to be able to enjoy the advantages of society--and
\par verily with the help of this kind of memory man eventually attained
\par "reason"! Alas! reason, seriousness, mastery over the emotions, all
\par these gloomy, dismal things which are called reflection, all these
\par privileges and pageantries of humanity: how dear is the price that they
\par have exacted! How much blood and cruelty is the foundation of all "good
\par things"!
\par 
\par 
\par 4.
\par 
\par But how is it that that other melancholy object, the consciousness of
\par sin, the whole "bad conscience," came into the world? And it is here
\par that we turn back to our genealogists of morals. For the second time
\par I say--or have I not said it yet?--that they are worth nothing. Just
\par their own five-spans-long limited modern experience; no knowledge of
\par the past, and no wish to know it; still less a historic instinct, a
\par power of "second sight" (which is what is really required in this
\par case)--and despite this to go in for the history of morals. It stands
\par to reason that this must needs produce results which are removed from
\par the truth by something more than a respectful distance.
\par 
\par Have these current genealogists of morals ever allowed themselves to
\par have even the vaguest notion, for instance, that the cardinal moral
\par idea of "ought"[2] originates from the very material idea of "owe"? Or
\par that punishment developed as a retaliation absolutely independently
\par of any preliminary hypothesis of the freedom or determination of the
\par will?--And this to such an extent, that a high degree of civilisation
\par was always first necessary for the animal man to begin to make those
\par much more primitive distinctions of "intentional," "negligent,"
\par "accidental," "responsible," and their contraries, and apply them
\par in the assessing of punishment. That idea--"the wrong-doer deserves
\par punishment _because_ he might have acted otherwise," in spite of the
\par fact that it is nowadays so cheap, obvious, natural, and inevitable,
\par and that it has had to serve as an illustration of the way in which
\par the sentiment of justice appeared on earth, is in point of fact
\par an exceedingly late, and even refined form of human judgment and
\par inference; the placing of this idea back at the beginning of the world
\par is simply a clumsy violation of the principles of primitive psychology.
\par Throughout the longest period of human history punishment was _never_
\par based on the responsibility of the evil-doer for his action, and was
\par consequently not based on the hypothesis that only the guilty should
\par be punished;--on the contrary, punishment was inflicted in those days
\par for the same reason that parents punish their children even nowadays,
\par out of anger at an injury that they have suffered, an anger which vents
\par itself mechanically on the author of the injury--but this anger is kept
\par in bounds and modified through the idea that every injury has somewhere
\par or other its _equivalent_ price, and can really be paid off, even
\par though it be by means of pain to the author. Whence is it that this
\par ancient deep-rooted and now perhaps ineradicable idea has drawn its
\par strength, this idea of an equivalency between injury and pain? I have
\par already revealed its origin, in the contractual relationship between
\par _creditor_ and _ower_, that is as old as the existence of legal rights
\par at all, and in its turn points back to the primary forms of purchase,
\par sale, barter, and trade.
\par 
\par 
\par 5.
\par 
\par The realisation of these contractual relations excites, of course (as
\par would be already expected from our previous observations), a great
\par deal of suspicion and opposition towards the primitive society which
\par made or sanctioned them. In this society promises will be made; in
\par this society the object is to provide the promiser with a memory;
\par in this society, so may we suspect, there will be full scope for
\par hardness, cruelty, and pain: the "ower," in order to induce credit
\par in his promise of repayment, in order to give a guarantee of the
\par earnestness and sanctity of his promise, in order to drill into his
\par own conscience the duty, the solemn duty, of repayment, will, by
\par virtue of a contract with his creditor to meet the contingency of
\par his not paying, pledge something that he still possesses, something
\par that he still has in his power, for instance, his life or his wife,
\par or his freedom or his body (or under certain religious conditions
\par even his salvation, his soul's welfare, even his peace in the grave;
\par so in Egypt, where the corpse of the ower found even in the grave no
\par rest from the creditor--of course, from the Egyptian standpoint, this
\par peace was a matter of particular importance). But especially has the
\par creditor the power of inflicting on the body of the ower all kinds of
\par pain and torture--the power, for instance, of cutting off from it an
\par amount that appeared proportionate to the greatness of the debt;--this
\par point of view resulted in the universal prevalence at an early date of
\par precise schemes of valuation, frequently horrible in the minuteness
\par and meticulosity of their application, _legally_ sanctioned schemes of
\par valuation for individual limbs and parts of the body. I consider it as
\par already a progress, as a proof of a freer, less petty, and more Roman
\par conception of law, when the Roman Code of the Twelve Tables decreed
\par that it was immaterial how much or how little the creditors in such a
\par contingency cut off, "si plus minusve secuerunt, ne fraude esto." Let
\par us make the logic of the whole of this equalisation process clear; it
\par is strange enough. The equivalence consists in this: instead of an
\par advantage directly compensatory of his injury (that is, instead of an
\par equalisation in money, lands, or some kind of chattel), the creditor
\par is granted by way of repayment and compensation a certain _sensation
\par of satisfaction_--the satisfaction of being able to vent, without any
\par trouble, his power on one who is powerless, the delight "_de faire le
\par mal pour le plaisir de le faire_," the joy in sheer violence: and this
\par joy will be relished in proportion to the lowness and humbleness of
\par the creditor in the social scale, and is quite apt to have the effect
\par of the most delicious dainty, and even seem the foretaste of a higher
\par social position. Thanks to the punishment of the "ower," the creditor
\par participates in the rights of the masters. At last he too, for once in
\par a way, attains the edifying consciousness of being able to despise and
\par ill-treat a creature--as an "inferior"--or at any rate of _seeing_ him
\par being despised and ill-treated, in case the actual power of punishment,
\par the administration of punishment, has already become transferred to the
\par "authorities." The compensation consequently consists in a claim on
\par cruelty and a right to draw thereon.
\par 
\par 
\par 6.
\par 
\par It is then in _this_ sphere of the law of contract that we find the
\par cradle of the whole moral world of the ideas of "guilt," "conscience,"
\par "duty," the "sacredness of duty,"--their commencement, like the
\par commencement of all great things in the world, is thoroughly and
\par continuously saturated with blood. And should we not add that this
\par world has never really lost a certain savour of blood and torture (not
\par even in old Kant; the categorical imperative reeks of cruelty). It was
\par in this sphere likewise that there first became formed that sinister
\par and perhaps now indissoluble association of the ideas of "guilt" and
\par "suffering." To put the question yet again, why can suffering be a
\par compensation for "owing"?--Because the _infliction_ of suffering
\par produces the highest degree of happiness, because the injured party
\par will get in exchange for his loss (including his vexation at his loss)
\par an extraordinary counter-pleasure: the _infliction_ of suffering--a
\par real _feast_, something that, as I have said, was all the more
\par appreciated the greater the paradox created by the rank and social
\par status of the creditor. These observations are purely conjectural; for,
\par apart from the painful nature of the task, it is hard to plumb such
\par profound depths: the clumsy introduction of the idea of "revenge" as a
\par connecting-link simply hides and obscures the view instead of rendering
\par it clearer (revenge itself simply leads back again to the identical
\par problem--"How can the infliction of suffering be a satisfaction?").
\par In my opinion it is repugnant to the delicacy, and still more to the
\par hypocrisy of tame domestic animals (that is, modern men; that is,
\par ourselves), to realise with all their energy the extent to which
\par _cruelty_ constituted the great joy and delight of ancient man, was
\par an ingredient which seasoned nearly all his pleasures, and conversely
\par the extent of the na\'efvet\'e9 and innocence with which he manifested his
\par need for cruelty, when he actually made as a matter of principle
\par "disinterested malice" (or, to use Spinoza's expression, the _sympathia
\par malevolens_) into a _normal_ characteristic of man--as consequently
\par something to which the conscience says a hearty yes. The more profound
\par observer has perhaps already had sufficient opportunity for noticing
\par this most ancient and radical joy and delight of mankind; in _Beyond
\par Good and Evil_, Aph. 188 (and even earlier, in _The Dawn of Day_, Aphs.
\par 18, 77, 113), I have cautiously indicated the continually growing
\par spiritualisation and "deification" of cruelty, which pervades the
\par whole history of the higher civilisation (and in the larger sense even
\par constitutes it). At any rate the time is not so long past when it was
\par impossible to conceive of royal weddings and national festivals on a
\par grand scale, without executions, tortures, or perhaps an _auto-da-f\'e9_",
\par or similarly to conceive of an aristocratic household, without a
\par creature to serve as a butt for the cruel and malicious baiting of the
\par inmates. (The reader will perhaps remember Don Quixote at the court of
\par the Duchess: we read nowadays the whole of _Don Quixote_ with a bitter
\par taste in the mouth, almost with a sensation of torture, a fact which
\par would appear very strange and very incomprehensible to the author and
\par his contemporaries--they read it with the best conscience in the world
\par as the gayest of books; they almost died with laughing at it.) The
\par sight of suffering does one good, the infliction of suffering does one
\par more good--this is a hard maxim, but none the less a fundamental maxim,
\par old, powerful, and "human, all-too-human"; one, moreover, to which
\par perhaps even the apes as well would subscribe: for it is said that in
\par inventing bizarre cruelties they are giving abundant proof of their
\par future humanity, to which, as it were, they are playing the prelude.
\par Without cruelty, no feast: so teaches the oldest and longest history of
\par man--and in punishment too is there so much of the festive.
\par 
\par 
\par 7.
\par 
\par Entertaining, as I do, these thoughts, I am, let me say in parenthesis,
\par fundamentally opposed to helping our pessimists to new water for the
\par discordant and groaning mills of their disgust with life; on the
\par contrary, it should be shown specifically that, at the time when
\par mankind was not yet ashamed of its cruelty, life in the world was
\par brighter than it is nowadays when there are pessimists. The darkening
\par of the heavens over man has always increased in proportion to the
\par growth of man's shame _before man_. The tired pessimistic outlook,
\par the mistrust of the riddle of life, the icy negation of disgusted
\par ennui, all those are not the signs of the _most evil_ age of the human
\par race: much rather do they come first to the light of day, as the
\par swamp-flowers, which they are, when the swamp to which they belong,
\par comes into existence--I mean the diseased refinement and moralisation,
\par thanks to which the "animal man" has at last learnt to be ashamed of
\par all his instincts. On the road to angelhood (not to use in this context
\par a harder word) man has developed that dyspeptic stomach and coated
\par tongue, which have made not only the joy and innocence of the animal
\par repulsive to him, but also life itself:--so that sometimes he stands
\par with stopped nostrils before his own self, and, like Pope Innocent the
\par Third, makes a black list of his own horrors ("unclean generation,
\par loathsome nutrition when in the maternal body, badness of the matter
\par out of which man develops, awful stench, secretion of saliva, urine,
\par and excrement"). Nowadays, when suffering is always trotted out
\par as the first argument _against_ existence, as its most sinister
\par query, it is well to remember the times when men judged on converse
\par principles because they could not dispense with the _infliction_ of
\par suffering, and saw therein a magic of the first order, a veritable
\par bait of seduction to life.
\par 
\par Perhaps in those days (this is to solace the weaklings) pain did not
\par hurt so much as it does nowadays: any physician who has treated negroes
\par (granted that these are taken as representative of the prehistoric
\par man) suffering from severe internal inflammations which would bring
\par a European, even though he had the soundest constitution, almost to
\par despair, would be in a position to come to this conclusion. Pain has
\par _not_ the same effect with negroes. (The curve of human sensibilities
\par to pain seems indeed to sink in an extraordinary and almost sudden
\par fashion, as soon as one has passed the upper ten thousand or ten
\par millions of over-civilised humanity, and I personally have no doubt
\par that, by comparison with one painful night passed by one single
\par hysterical chit of a cultured woman, the suffering of all the animals
\par taken together who have been put to the question of the knife, so as
\par to give scientific answers, are simply negligible.) We may perhaps
\par be allowed to admit the possibility of the craving for cruelty not
\par necessarily having become really extinct: it only requires, in view
\par of the fact that pain hurts more nowadays, a certain sublimation and
\par subtilisation, it must especially be translated to the imaginative and
\par psychic plane, and be adorned with such smug euphemisms, that even the
\par most fastidious and hypocritical conscience could never grow suspicious
\par of their real nature ("Tragic pity" is one of these euphemisms:
\par another is "_les nostalgies de la croix_"). What really raises one's
\par indignation against suffering is not suffering intrinsically, but
\par the senselessness of suffering; such a _senselessness_, however,
\par existed neither in Christianity, which interpreted suffering into a
\par whole mysterious salvation-apparatus, nor in the beliefs of the naive
\par ancient man, who only knew how to find a meaning in suffering from
\par the standpoint of the spectator, or the inflictor of the suffering.
\par In order to get the secret, undiscovered, and unwitnessed suffering
\par out of the world it was almost compulsory to invent gods and a
\par hierarchy of intermediate beings, in short, something which wanders
\par even among secret places, sees even in the dark, and makes a point
\par of never missing an interesting and painful spectacle. It was with
\par the help of such inventions that life got to learn the _tour de
\par force_, which has become part of its stock-in-trade, the _tour de
\par force_ of self-justification, of the justification of evil; nowadays
\par this would perhaps require other auxiliary devices (for instance,
\par life as a riddle, life as a problem of knowledge). "Every evil is
\par justified in the sight of which a god finds edification," so rang the
\par logic of primitive sentiment--and, indeed, was it only of primitive?
\par The gods conceived as friends of spectacles of cruelty--oh how far
\par does this primeval conception extend even nowadays into our European
\par civilisation! One would perhaps like in this context to consult Luther
\par and Calvin. It is at any rate certain that even the Greeks knew no
\par more piquant seasoning for the happiness of their gods than the joys
\par of cruelty. What, do you think, was the mood with which Homer makes
\par his gods look down upon the fates of men? What final meaning have at
\par bottom the Trojan War and similar tragic horrors? It is impossible to
\par entertain any doubt on the point: they were intended as festival games
\par for the gods, and, in so far as the poet is of a more godlike breed
\par than other men, as festival games also for the poets. It was in just
\par this spirit and no other, that at a later date the moral philosophers
\par of Greece conceived the eyes of God as still looking down on the moral
\par struggle, the heroism, and the self-torture of the virtuous; the
\par Heracles of duty was on a stage, and was conscious of the fact; virtue
\par without witnesses was something quite unthinkable for this nation of
\par actors. Must not that philosophic invention, so audacious and so fatal,
\par which was then absolutely new to Europe, the invention of "free will,"
\par of the absolute spontaneity of man in good and evil, simply have been
\par made for the specific purpose of justifying the idea, that the interest
\par of the gods in humanity and human virtue was _inexhaustible_?
\par 
\par There would never on the stage of this free-will world be a dearth of
\par really new, really novel and exciting situations, plots, catastrophes.
\par A world thought out on completely deterministic lines would be easily
\par guessed by the gods, and would consequently soon bore them--sufficient
\par reason for these _friends of the gods_, the philosophers, not to
\par ascribe to their gods such a deterministic world. The whole of ancient
\par humanity is full of delicate consideration for the spectator, being as
\par it is a world of thorough publicity and theatricality, which could not
\par conceive of happiness without spectacles and festivals.--And, as has
\par already been said, even in great punishment there is so much which is
\par festive.
\par 
\par 
\par 8.
\par 
\par The feeling of "ought," of personal obligation (to take up again
\par the train of our inquiry), has had, as we saw, its origin in the
\par oldest and most original personal relationship that there is, the
\par relationship between buyer and seller, creditor and ower: here it
\par was that individual confronted individual, and that individual
\par _matched himself against_ individual. There has not yet been found
\par a grade of civilisation so low, as not to manifest some trace of
\par this relationship. Making prices, assessing values, thinking out
\par equivalents, exchanging--all this preoccupied the primal thoughts
\par of man to such an extent that in a certain sense it constituted
\par _thinking_ itself: it was here that was trained the oldest form of
\par sagacity, it was here in this sphere that we can perhaps trace the
\par first commencement of man's pride, of his feeling of superiority over
\par other animals. Perhaps our word "Mensch" (_manas_) still expresses
\par just something of _this_ self-pride: man denoted himself as the being
\par who measures values, who values and measures, as the "assessing"
\par animal _par excellence_. Sale and purchase, together with their
\par psychological concomitants, are older than the origins of any form of
\par social organisation and union: it is rather from the most rudimentary
\par form of individual right that the budding consciousness of exchange,
\par commerce, debt, right, obligation, compensation was first transferred
\par to the rudest and most elementary of the social complexes (in their
\par relation to similar complexes), the habit of comparing force with
\par force, together with that of measuring, of calculating. His eye was
\par now focussed to this perspective; and with that ponderous consistency
\par characteristic of ancient thought, which, though set in motion with
\par difficulty, yet proceeds inflexibly along the line on which it has
\par started, man soon arrived at the great generalisation, "everything has
\par its price, _all_ can be paid for," the oldest and most naive moral
\par canon of _justice_, the beginning of all "kindness," of all "equity,"
\par of all "goodwill," of all "objectivity" in the world. Justice in this
\par initial phase is the goodwill among people of about equal power to come
\par to terms with each other, to come to an understanding again by means of
\par a settlement, and with regard to the less powerful, to _compel_ them
\par to agree among themselves to a settlement.
\par 
\par 
\par 9.
\par 
\par Measured always by the standard of antiquity (this antiquity, moreover,
\par is present or again possible at all periods), the community stands to
\par its members in that important and radical relationship of creditor to
\par his "owers." Man lives in a community, man enjoys the advantages of
\par a community (and what advantages! we occasionally underestimate them
\par nowadays), man lives protected, spared, in peace and trust, secure
\par from certain injuries and enmities, to which the man outside the
\par community, the "peaceless" man, is exposed,--a German understands the
\par original meaning of "Elend" (_\'ealend_),--secure because he has entered
\par into pledges and obligations to the community in respect of these very
\par injuries and enmities. What happens _when this is not the case_? The
\par community, the defrauded creditor, will get itself paid, as well as it
\par can, one can reckon on that. In this case the question of the direct
\par damage done by the offender is quite subsidiary: quite apart from
\par this the criminal[3] is above all a breaker, a breaker of word and
\par covenant _to the whole_, as regards all the advantages and amenities
\par of the communal life in which up to that time he had participated. The
\par criminal is an "ower" who not only fails to repay the advances and
\par advantages that have been given to him, but even sets out to attack
\par his creditor: consequently he is in the future not only, as is fair,
\par deprived of all these advantages and amenities--he is in addition
\par reminded of the _importance_ of those advantages. The wrath of the
\par injured creditor, of the community, puts him back in the wild and
\par outlawed status from which he was previously protected: the community
\par repudiates him--and now every kind of enmity can vent itself on him.
\par Punishment is in this stage of civilisation simply the copy, the mimic,
\par of the normal treatment of the hated, disdained, and conquered enemy,
\par who is not only deprived of every right and protection but of every
\par mercy; so we have the martial law and triumphant festival of the _v\'e6
\par victis_! in all its mercilessness and cruelty. This shows why war
\par itself (counting the sacrificial cult of war) has produced all the
\par forms under which punishment has manifested itself in history.
\par 
\par 
\par 10.
\par 
\par As it grows more powerful, the community tends to take the offences of
\par the individual less seriously, because they are now regarded as being
\par much less revolutionary and dangerous to the corporate existence: the
\par evil-doer is no more outlawed and put outside the pale, the common
\par wrath can no longer vent itself upon him with its old licence,--on
\par the contrary, from this very time it is against this wrath, and
\par particularly against the wrath of those directly injured, that the
\par evil-doer is carefully shielded and protected by the community. As, in
\par fact, the penal law develops, the following characteristics become
\par more and more clearly marked: compromise with the wrath of those
\par directly affected by the misdeed; a consequent endeavour to localise
\par the matter and to prevent a further, or indeed a general spread of
\par the disturbance; attempts to find equivalents and to settle the whole
\par matter (compositio); above all, the will, which manifests itself with
\par increasing definiteness, to treat every offence as in a certain degree
\par capable of _being paid off_, and consequently, at any rate up to a
\par certain point, to _isolate_ the offender from his act. As the power and
\par the self-consciousness of a community increases, so proportionately
\par does the penal law become mitigated; conversely every weakening and
\par jeopardising of the community revives the harshest forms of that law.
\par The creditor has always grown more humane proportionately as he has
\par grown more rich; finally the amount of injury he can endure without
\par really suffering becomes the criterion of his wealth. It is possible
\par to conceive of a society blessed with so great a _consciousness of its
\par own power_ as to indulge in the most aristocratic luxury of letting
\par its wrong-doers go _scot-free_.--"What do my parasites matter to me?"
\par might society say. "Let them live and flourish! I am strong enough for
\par it."--The justice which began with the maxim, "Everything can be paid
\par off, everything must be paid off," ends with connivance at the escape
\par of those who cannot pay to escape--it ends, like every good thing on
\par earth, by _destroying itself_.--The self-destruction of Justice! we
\par know the pretty name it calls itself--_Grace!_ it remains, as is
\par obvious, the privilege of the strongest, better still, their super-law.
\par 
\par 
\par 11.
\par 
\par A deprecatory word here against the attempts, that have lately been
\par made, to find the origin of justice on quite another basis--namely,
\par on that of _resentment_. Let me whisper a word in the ear of the
\par psychologists, if they would fain study revenge itself at close
\par quarters: this plant blooms its prettiest at present among Anarchists
\par and anti-Semites, a hidden flower, as it has ever been, like the
\par violet, though, forsooth, with another perfume. And as like must
\par necessarily emanate from like, it will not be a matter for surprise
\par that it is just in such circles that we see the birth of endeavours (it
\par is their old birthplace--compare above, First Essay, paragraph 14),
\par to sanctify _revenge_ under the name of _justice_ (as though Justice
\par were at bottom merely a _development_ of the consciousness of injury),
\par and thus with the rehabilitation of revenge to reinstate generally
\par and collectively all the _reactive_ emotions. I object to this last
\par point least of all. It even seems _meritorious_ when regarded from the
\par standpoint of the whole problem of biology (from which standpoint the
\par value of these emotions has up to the present been underestimated).
\par And that to which I alone call attention, is the circumstance that
\par it is the spirit of revenge itself, from which develops this new
\par nuance of scientific equity (for the benefit of hate, envy, mistrust,
\par jealousy, suspicion, rancour, revenge). This scientific "equity"
\par stops immediately and makes way for the accents of deadly enmity and
\par prejudice, so soon as another group of emotions comes on the scene,
\par which in my opinion are of a much higher biological value than these
\par reactions, and consequently have a paramount claim to the valuation
\par and appreciation of science: I mean the really _active_ emotions, such
\par as personal and material ambition, and so forth. (E. D\'fchring, _Value
\par of Life; Course of Philosophy_, and _passim_.) So much against this
\par tendency in general: but as for the particular maxim of D\'fchring's,
\par that the home of Justice is to be found in the sphere of the reactive
\par feelings, our love of truth compels us drastically to invert his own
\par proposition and to oppose to him this other maxim: the _last_ sphere
\par conquered by the spirit of justice is the sphere of the feeling of
\par reaction! When it really comes about that the just man remains just
\par even as regards his injurer (and not merely cold, moderate, reserved,
\par indifferent: being just is always a _positive_ state); when, in spite
\par of the strong provocation of personal insult, contempt, and calumny,
\par the lofty and clear objectivity of the just and judging eye (whose
\par glance is as profound as it is gentle) is untroubled, why then we have
\par a piece of perfection, a past master of the world--something, in fact,
\par which it would not be wise to expect, and which should not at any
\par rate be too easily _believed_. Speaking generally, there is no doubt
\par but that even the justest individual only requires a little dose of
\par hostility, malice, or innuendo to drive the blood into his brain and
\par the fairness _from_ it. The active man, the attacking, aggressive man
\par is always a hundred degrees nearer to justice than the man who merely
\par reacts; he certainly has no need to adopt the tactics, necessary in the
\par case of the reacting man, of making false and biassed valuations of his
\par object. It is, in point of fact, for this reason that the aggressive
\par man has at all times enjoyed the stronger, bolder, more aristocratic,
\par and also _freer_ outlook, the _better_ conscience. On the other hand,
\par we already surmise who it really is that has on his conscience the
\par invention of the "bad conscience,"--the resentful man! Finally, let man
\par look at himself in history. In what sphere up to the present has the
\par whole administration of law, the actual need of law, found its earthly
\par home? Perchance in the sphere of the reacting man? Not for a minute:
\par rather in that of the active, strong, spontaneous, aggressive man? I
\par deliberately defy the above-mentioned agitator (who himself makes this
\par self-confession, "the creed of revenge has run through all my works
\par and endeavours like the red thread of Justice"), and say, that judged
\par historically law in the world represents the very war _against_ the
\par reactive feelings, the very war waged on those feelings by the powers
\par of activity and aggression, which devote some of their strength to
\par damming and keeping within bounds this effervescence of hysterical
\par reactivity, and to forcing it to some compromise. Everywhere where
\par justice is practised and justice is maintained, it is to be observed
\par that the stronger power, when confronted with the weaker powers which
\par are inferior to it (whether they be groups, or individuals), searches
\par for weapons to put an end to the senseless fury of resentment, while
\par it carries on its object, partly by taking the victim of resentment
\par out of the clutches of revenge, partly by substituting for revenge a
\par campaign of its own against the enemies of peace and order, partly
\par by finding, suggesting, and occasionally enforcing settlements,
\par partly by standardising certain equivalents for injuries, to which
\par equivalents the element of resentment is henceforth finally referred.
\par The most drastic measure, however, taken and effectuated by the supreme
\par power, to combat the preponderance of the feelings of spite and
\par vindictiveness--it takes this measure as soon as it is at all strong
\par enough to do so--is the foundation of _law_, the imperative declaration
\par of what in its eyes is to be regarded as just and lawful, and what
\par unjust and unlawful: and while, after the foundation of law, the
\par supreme power treats the aggressive and arbitrary acts of individuals,
\par or of whole groups, as a violation of law, and a revolt against
\par itself, it distracts the feelings of its subjects from the immediate
\par injury inflicted by such a violation, and thus eventually attains the
\par very opposite result to that always desired by revenge, which sees
\par and recognises nothing but the standpoint of the injured party. From
\par henceforth the eye becomes trained to a more and more _impersonal_
\par valuation of the deed, even the eye of the injured party himself
\par (though this is in the final stage of all, as has been previously
\par remarked)--on this principle "right" and "wrong" first manifest
\par themselves after the foundation of law (and not, as D\'fchring maintains,
\par only after the act of violation). To talk of intrinsic right and
\par intrinsic wrong is absolutely non-sensical; intrinsically, an injury,
\par an oppression, an exploitation, an annihilation can be nothing wrong,
\par inasmuch as life is _essentially_ (that is, in its cardinal functions)
\par something which functions by injuring, oppressing, exploiting, and
\par annihilating, and is absolutely inconceivable without such a character.
\par It is necessary to make an even more serious confession:--viewed from
\par the most advanced biological standpoint, conditions of legality can be
\par only _exceptional conditions_, in that they are partial restrictions
\par of the real life-will, which makes for power, and in that they are
\par subordinated to the life-will's general end as particular means,
\par that is, as means to create _larger_ units of strength. A legal
\par organisation, conceived of as sovereign and universal, not as a weapon
\par in a fight of complexes of power, but as a weapon _against_ fighting,
\par generally something after the style of D\'fchring's communistic model
\par of treating every will as equal with every other will, would be a
\par principle _hostile to life_, a destroyer and dissolver of man, an
\par outrage on the future of man, a symptom of fatigue, a secret cut to
\par Nothingness.--
\par 
\par 
\par 12.
\par 
\par A word more on the origin and end of punishment--two problems which
\par are or ought to be kept distinct, but which unfortunately are usually
\par lumped into one. And what tactics have our moral genealogists employed
\par up to the present in these cases? Their inveterate na\'efvet\'e9. They find
\par out some "end" in the punishment, for instance, revenge and deterrence,
\par and then in all their innocence set this end at the beginning, as the
\par _causa fiendi_ of the punishment, and--they have done the trick. But
\par the patching up of a history of the origin of law is the last use to
\par which the "End in Law"[4] ought to be put. Perhaps there is no more
\par pregnant principle for any kind of history than the following, which,
\par difficult though it is to master, _should_ none the less be _mastered_
\par in every detail.--The origin of the existence of a thing and its final
\par utility, its practical application and incorporation in a system of
\par ends, are _toto c\'9clo_ opposed to each other--everything, anything,
\par which exists and which prevails anywhere, will always be put to new
\par purposes by a force superior to itself, will be commandeered afresh,
\par will be turned and transformed to new uses; all "happening" in the
\par organic world consists of _overpowering_ and dominating, and again all
\par overpowering and domination is a new interpretation and adjustment,
\par which must necessarily obscure or absolutely extinguish the subsisting
\par "meaning" and "end." The most perfect comprehension of the utility
\par of any physiological organ (or also of a legal institution, social
\par custom, political habit, form in art or in religious worship) does not
\par for a minute imply any simultaneous comprehension of its origin: this
\par may seem uncomfortable and unpalatable to the older men,--for it has
\par been the immemorial belief that understanding the final cause or the
\par utility of a thing, a form, an institution, means also understanding
\par the reason for its origin: to give an example of this logic, the eye
\par was made to see, the hand was made to grasp. So even punishment was
\par conceived as invented with a view to punishing. But all ends and all
\par utilities are only _signs_ that a Will to Power has mastered a less
\par powerful force, has impressed thereon out of its own self the meaning
\par of a function; and the whole history of a "Thing," an organ, a custom,
\par can on the same principle be regarded as a continuous "sign-chain"
\par of perpetually new interpretations and adjustments, whose causes, so
\par far from needing to have even a mutual connection, sometimes follow
\par and alternate with each other absolutely haphazard. Similarly, the
\par evolution of a "thing," of a custom, is anything but its _progressus_
\par to an end, still less a logical and direct _progressus_ attained
\par with the minimum expenditure of energy and cost: it is rather the
\par succession of processes of subjugation, more or less profound, more
\par or less mutually independent, which operate on the thing itself; it
\par is, further, the resistance which in each case invariably displayed
\par this subjugation, the Protean wriggles by way of defence and reaction,
\par and, further, the results of successful counter-efforts. The form is
\par fluid, but the meaning is even more so--even inside every individual
\par organism the case is the same: with every genuine growth of the whole,
\par the "function" of the individual organs becomes shifted,--in certain
\par cases a partial perishing of these organs, a diminution of their
\par numbers (for instance, through annihilation of the connecting members),
\par can be a symptom of growing strength and perfection. What I mean is
\par this: even partial _loss of utility_, decay, and degeneration, loss of
\par function and purpose, in a word, death, appertain to the conditions
\par of the genuine _progressus_; which always appears in the shape of
\par a will and way to _greater_ power, and is always realised at the
\par expense of innumerable smaller powers. The magnitude of a "progress"
\par is gauged by the greatness of the sacrifice that it requires: humanity
\par as a mass sacrificed to the prosperity of the one _stronger_ species
\par of Man--that _would be_ a progress. I emphasise all the more this
\par cardinal characteristic of the historic method, for the reason that in
\par its essence it runs counter to predominant instincts and prevailing
\par taste, which much prefer to put up with absolute casualness, even with
\par the mechanical senselessness of all phenomena, than with the theory
\par of a power-will, in exhaustive play throughout all phenomena. The
\par democratic idiosyncrasy against everything which rules and wishes to
\par rule, the modern _misarchism_ (to coin a bad word for a bad thing),
\par has gradually but so thoroughly transformed itself into the guise of
\par intellectualism, the most abstract intellectualism, that even nowadays
\par it penetrates and _has the right_ to penetrate step by step into the
\par most exact and apparently the most objective sciences: this tendency
\par has, in fact, in my view already dominated the whole of physiology
\par and biology, and to their detriment, as is obvious, in so far as
\par it has spirited away a radical idea, the idea of true _activity_.
\par The tyranny of this idiosyncrasy, however, results in the theory
\par of "adaptation" being pushed forward into the van of the argument,
\par exploited; adaptation--that means to say, a second-class activity, a
\par mere capacity for "reacting"; in fact, life itself has been defined
\par (by Herbert Spencer) as an increasingly effective internal adaptation
\par to external circumstances. This definition, however, fails to realise
\par the real essence of life, its will to power. It fails to appreciate the
\par paramount superiority enjoyed by those plastic forces of spontaneity,
\par aggression, and encroachment with their new interpretations and
\par tendencies, to the operation of which adaptation is only a natural
\par corollary: consequently the sovereign office of the highest
\par functionaries in the organism itself (among which the life-will appears
\par as an active and formative principle) is repudiated. One remembers
\par Huxley's reproach to Spencer of his "administrative Nihilism": but it
\par is a case of something much _more_ than "administration."
\par 
\par 
\par 13.
\par 
\par To return to our subject, namely _punishment_, we must make
\par consequently a double distinction: first, the relatively permanent
\par _element_, the custom, the act, the "drama," a certain rigid sequence
\par of methods of procedure; on the other hand, the fluid element, the
\par meaning, the end, the expectation which is attached to the operation of
\par such procedure. At this point we immediately assume, _per analogiam_
\par (in accordance with the theory of the historic method, which we have
\par elaborated above), that the procedure itself is something older and
\par earlier than its utilisation in punishment, that this utilisation was
\par _introduced_ and interpreted into the procedure (which had existed
\par for a long time, but whose employment had another meaning), in short,
\par that the case is _different_ from that hitherto supposed by our _na\'eff_
\par genealogists of morals and of law, who thought that the procedure was
\par _invented_ for the purpose of punishment, in the same way that the hand
\par had been previously thought to have been invented for the purpose of
\par grasping. With regard to the other element in _punishment_, its fluid
\par element, its meaning, the idea of punishment in a very late stage of
\par civilisation (for instance, contemporary Europe) is not content with
\par manifesting merely one meaning, but manifests a whole synthesis "of
\par meanings." The past general history of punishment, the history of its
\par employment for the most diverse ends, crystallises eventually into
\par a kind of unity, which is difficult to analyse into its parts, and
\par which, it is necessary to emphasise, absolutely defies definition.
\par (It is nowadays impossible to say definitely _the precise reason_
\par for punishment: all ideas, in which a whole process is promiscuously
\par comprehended, elude definition; it is only that which has no history,
\par which can be defined.) At an earlier stage, on the contrary, that
\par synthesis of meanings appears much less rigid and much more elastic; we
\par can realise how in each individual case the elements of the synthesis
\par change their value and their position, so that now one element and
\par now another stands out and predominates over the others, nay, in
\par certain cases one element (perhaps the end of deterrence) seems to
\par eliminate all the rest. At any rate, so as to give some idea of the
\par uncertain, supplementary, and accidental nature of the meaning of
\par punishment and of the manner in which one identical procedure can
\par be employed and adapted for the most diametrically opposed objects,
\par I will at this point give a scheme that has suggested itself to
\par me, a scheme itself based on comparatively small and accidental
\par material.--Punishment, as rendering the criminal harmless and incapable
\par of further injury.--Punishment, as compensation for the injury
\par sustained by the injured party, in any form whatsoever (including
\par the form of sentimental compensation).--Punishment, as an isolation
\par of that which disturbs the equilibrium, so as to prevent the further
\par spreading of the disturbance.--Punishment as a means of inspiring
\par fear of those who determine and execute the punishment.--Punishment
\par as a kind of compensation for advantages which the wrong-doer has
\par up to that time enjoyed (for example, when he is utilised as a
\par slave in the mines).--Punishment, as the elimination of an element
\par of decay (sometimes of a whole branch, as according to the Chinese
\par laws, consequently as a means to the purification of the race, or
\par the preservation of a social type).---Punishment as a festival, as
\par the violent oppression and humiliation of an enemy that has at last
\par been subdued.--Punishment as a mnemonic, whether for him who suffers
\par the punishment--the so-called "correction," or for the witnesses of
\par its administration. Punishment, as the payment of a fee stipulated
\par for by the power which protects the evil-doer from the excesses of
\par revenge.--Punishment, as a compromise with the natural phenomenon
\par of revenge, in so far as revenge is still maintained and claimed
\par as a privilege by the stronger races.--Punishment as a declaration
\par and measure of war against an enemy of peace, of law, of order,
\par of authority, who is fought by society with the weapons which war
\par provides, as a spirit dangerous to the community, as a breaker of the
\par contract on which the community is based, as a rebel, a traitor, and a
\par breaker of the peace.
\par 
\par 
\par 14.
\par 
\par This list is certainly not complete; it is obvious that punishment
\par is overloaded with utilities of all kinds. This makes it all the
\par more permissible to eliminate one supposed utility, which passes, at
\par any rate in the popular mind, for its most essential utility, and
\par which is just what even now provides the strongest support for that
\par faith in punishment which is nowadays for many reasons tottering.
\par Punishment is supposed to have the value of exciting in the guilty
\par the consciousness of guilt; in punishment is sought the proper
\par instrumentum of that psychic reaction which becomes known as a "bad
\par conscience," "remorse." But this theory is even, from the point of
\par view of the present, a violation of reality and psychology: and how
\par much more so is the case when we have to deal with the longest period
\par of man's history, his primitive history! Genuine remorse is certainly
\par extremely rare among wrong-doers and the victims of punishment; prisons
\par and houses of correction are not _the_ soil on which this worm of
\par remorse pullulates for choice--this is the unanimous opinion of all
\par conscientious observers, who in many cases arrive at such a judgment
\par with enough reluctance and against their own personal wishes. Speaking
\par generally, punishment hardens and numbs, it produces concentration, it
\par sharpens the consciousness of alienation, it strengthens the power of
\par resistance. When it happens that it breaks the man's energy and brings
\par about a piteous prostration and abjectness, such a result is certainly
\par even less salutary than the average effect of punishment, which is
\par characterised by a harsh and sinister doggedness. The thought of those
\par _prehistoric_ millennia brings us to the unhesitating conclusion,
\par that it was simply through punishment that the evolution of the
\par consciousness of guilt was most forcibly retarded--at any rate in the
\par victims of the punishing power. In particular, let us not underestimate
\par the extent to which, by the very sight of the judicial and executive
\par procedure, the wrong-doer is himself prevented from feeling that his
\par deed, the character of his act, is _intrinsically_ reprehensible: for
\par he sees clearly the same kind of acts practised in the service of
\par justice, and then called good, and practised with a good conscience;
\par acts such as espionage, trickery, bribery, trapping, the whole
\par intriguing and insidious art of the policeman and the informer--the
\par whole system, in fact, manifested in the different kinds of punishment
\par (a system not excused by passion, but based on principle), of robbing,
\par oppressing, insulting, imprisoning, racking, murdering.--All this
\par he sees treated by his judges, not as acts meriting censure and
\par condemnation _in themselves_, but only in a particular context and
\par application. It was not on this soil that grew the "bad conscience,"
\par that most sinister and interesting plant of our earthly vegetation--
\par in point of fact, throughout a most lengthy period, no suggestion of
\par having to do with a "guilty man" manifested itself in the consciousness
\par of the man who judged and punished. One had merely to deal with an
\par author of an injury, an irresponsible piece of fate. And the man
\par himself, on whom the punishment subsequently fell like a piece of fate,
\par was occasioned no more of an "inner pain" than would be occasioned by
\par the sudden approach of some uncalculated event, some terrible natural
\par catastrophe, a rushing, crushing avalanche against which there is no
\par resistance.
\par 
\par 
\par 15.
\par 
\par This truth came insidiously enough to the consciousness of Spinoza (to
\par the disgust of his commentators, who (like Kuno Fischer, for instance)
\par give themselves no end of _trouble_ to misunderstand him on this
\par point), when one afternoon (as he sat raking up who knows what memory)
\par he indulged in the question of what was really left for him personally
\par of the celebrated _morsus conscienti\'e6_--Spinoza, who had relegated
\par "good and evil" to the sphere of human imagination, and indignantly
\par defended the honour of his "free" God against those blasphemers who
\par affirmed that God did everything _sub ratione boni_ ("but this was
\par tantamount to subordinating God to fate, and would really be the
\par greatest of all absurdities"). For Spinoza the world had returned
\par again to that innocence in which it lay before the discovery of the
\par bad conscience: what, then, had happened to the _morsus conscienti\'e6_?
\par "The antithesis of _gaudium_," said he at last to himself,--"A sadness
\par accompanied by the recollection of a past event which has turned out
\par contrary to all expectation" (_Eth_. III., Propos. XVIII. Schol.
\par i. ii.). Evil-doers have throughout thousands of years felt when
\par overtaken by punishment _exactly like Spinoza_, on the subject of
\par their "offence": "here is something which went wrong contrary to my
\par anticipation," not "I ought not to have done this."--They submitted
\par themselves to punishment, just as one submits one's self to a disease,
\par to a misfortune, or to death, with that stubborn and resigned fatalism
\par which gives the Russians, for instance, even nowadays, the advantage
\par over us Westerners, in the handling of life. If at that period there
\par was a critique of action, the criterion was prudence: the real _effect_
\par of punishment is unquestionably chiefly to be found in a sharpening
\par of the sense of prudence, in a lengthening of the memory, in a will
\par to adopt more of a policy of caution, suspicion, and secrecy; in the
\par recognition that there are many things which are unquestionably beyond
\par one's capacity; in a kind of improvement in self-criticism. The broad
\par effects which can be obtained by punishment in man and beast, are the
\par increase of fear, the sharpening of the sense of cunning, the mastery
\par of the desires: so it is that punishment _tames_ man, but does not make
\par him "better"--it would be more correct even to go so far as to assert
\par the contrary ("Injury makes a man cunning," says a popular proverb: so
\par far as it makes him cunning, it makes him also bad. Fortunately, it
\par often enough makes him stupid).
\par 
\par 
\par 16.
\par 
\par At this juncture I cannot avoid trying to give a tentative and
\par provisional expression to my own hypothesis concerning the origin of
\par the bad conscience: it is difficult to make it fully appreciated,
\par and it requires continuous meditation, attention, and digestion. I
\par regard the bad conscience as the serious illness which man was bound
\par to contract under the stress of the most radical change which he has
\par ever experienced--that change, when he found himself finally imprisoned
\par within the pale of society and of peace.
\par 
\par Just like the plight of the water-animals, when they were compelled
\par either to become land-animals or to perish, so was the plight of these
\par half-animals, perfectly adapted as they were to the savage life of war,
\par prowling, and adventure--suddenly all their instincts were rendered
\par worthless and "switched off." Henceforward they had to walk on their
\par feet--"carry themselves," whereas heretofore they had been carried by
\par the water: a terrible heaviness oppressed them. They found themselves
\par clumsy in obeying the simplest directions, confronted with this new
\par and unknown world they had no longer their old guides--the regulative
\par instincts that had led them unconsciously to safety--they were reduced,
\par were those unhappy creatures, to thinking, inferring, calculating,
\par putting together causes and results, reduced to that poorest and most
\par erratic organ of theirs, their "consciousness." I do not believe
\par there was ever in the world such a feeling of misery, such a leaden
\par discomfort--further, those old instincts had not immediately ceased
\par their demands! Only it was difficult and rarely possible to gratify
\par them: speaking broadly, they were compelled to satisfy themselves by
\par new and, as it were, hole-and-corner methods. All instincts which
\par do not find a vent without, _turn inwards_--this is what I mean by
\par the growing "internalisation" of man: consequently we have the first
\par growth in man, of what subsequently was called his soul. The whole
\par inner world, originally as thin as if it had been stretched between
\par two layers of skin, burst apart and expanded proportionately, and
\par obtained depth, breadth, and height, when man's external outlet
\par became _obstructed_. These terrible bulwarks, with which the social
\par organisation protected itself against the old instincts of freedom
\par (punishments belong pre-eminently to these bulwarks), brought it
\par about that all those instincts of wild, free, prowling man became
\par turned backwards against man himself. Enmity, cruelty, the delight
\par in persecution, in surprises, change, destruction--the turning all
\par these instincts against their own possessors: this is the origin of
\par the "bad conscience." It was man, who, lacking external enemies and
\par obstacles, and imprisoned as he was in the oppressive narrowness and
\par monotony of custom, in his own impatience lacerated, persecuted,
\par gnawed, frightened, and ill-treated himself; it was this animal in the
\par hands of the tamer, which beat itself against the bars of its cage; it
\par was this being who, pining and yearning for that desert home of which
\par it had been deprived, was compelled to create out of its own self, an
\par adventure, a torture-chamber, a hazardous and perilous desert--it was
\par this fool, this homesick and desperate prisoner--who invented the "bad
\par conscience." But thereby he introduced that most grave and sinister
\par illness, from which mankind has not yet recovered, the suffering of
\par man from the disease called man, as the result of a violent breaking
\par from his animal past, the result, as it were, of a spasmodic plunge
\par into a new environment and new conditions of existence, the result of
\par a declaration of war against the old instincts, which up to that time
\par had been the staple of his power, his joy, his formidableness. Let
\par us immediately add that this fact of an animal ego turning against
\par itself, taking part against itself, produced in the world so novel,
\par profound, unheard-of, problematic, inconsistent, and _pregnant_ a
\par phenomenon, that the aspect of the world was radically altered thereby.
\par In sooth, only divine spectators could have appreciated the drama
\par that then began, and whose end baffles conjecture as yet--a drama too
\par subtle, too wonderful, too paradoxical to warrant its undergoing a
\par non-sensical and unheeded performance on some random grotesque planet!
\par Henceforth man is to be counted as one of the most unexpected and
\par sensational lucky shots in the game of the "big baby" of Heracleitus,
\par whether he be called Zeus or Chance--he awakens on his behalf the
\par interest, excitement, hope, almost the confidence, of his being the
\par harbinger and forerunner of something, of man being no end, but only a
\par stage, an interlude, a bridge, a great promise.
\par 
\par 
\par 17.
\par 
\par It is primarily involved in this hypothesis of the origin of the bad
\par conscience, that that alteration was no gradual and no voluntary
\par alteration, and that it did not manifest itself as an organic
\par adaptation to new conditions, but as a break, a jump, a necessity, an
\par inevitable fate, against which there was no resistance and never a
\par spark of resentment. And secondarily, that the fitting of a hitherto
\par unchecked and amorphous population into a fixed form, starting as
\par it had done in an act of violence, could only be accomplished by
\par acts of violence and nothing else--that the oldest "State" appeared
\par consequently as a ghastly tyranny, a grinding ruthless piece of
\par machinery, which went on working, till this raw material of a
\par semi-animal populace was not only thoroughly kneaded and elastic, but
\par also _moulded_. I used the word "State": my meaning is self-evident,
\par namely, a herd of blonde beasts of prey, a race of conquerors and
\par masters, which with all its warlike organisation and all its organising
\par power pounces with its terrible claws on a population, in numbers
\par possibly tremendously superior, but as yet formless, as yet nomad.
\par Such is the origin of the "State." That fantastic theory that makes it
\par begin with a contract is, I think, disposed of. He who can command,
\par he who is a master by "nature," he who comes on the scene forceful
\par in deed and gesture--what has he to do with contracts? Such beings
\par defy calculation, they come like fate, without cause, reason, notice,
\par excuse, they are there like the lightning is there, too terrible, too
\par sudden, too convincing, too "different," to be personally even hated.
\par Their work is an instinctive creating and impressing of forms, they
\par are the most involuntary, unconscious artists that there are:--their
\par appearance produces instantaneously a scheme of sovereignty which is
\par live, in which the functions are partitioned and apportioned, in which
\par above all no part is received or finds a place, until pregnant with
\par a "meaning" in regard to the whole. They are ignorant of the meaning
\par of guilt, responsibility, consideration, are these born organisers;
\par in them predominates that terrible artist-egoism, that gleams like
\par brass, and that knows itself justified to all eternity, in its work,
\par even as a mother in her child. It is not in _them_ that there grew
\par the bad conscience, that is elementary--but it would not have grown
\par _without_ them, repulsive growth as it was, it would be missing, had
\par not a tremendous quantity of freedom been expelled from the world by
\par the stress of their hammer-strokes, their artist violence, or been at
\par any rate made invisible and, as it were, _latent_. This _instinct of
\par freedom_ forced into being latent--it is already clear--this instinct
\par of freedom forced back, trodden back, imprisoned within itself, and
\par finally only able to find vent and relief in itself; this, only this,
\par is the beginning of the "bad conscience."
\par 
\par 
\par 18.
\par 
\par Beware of thinking lightly of this phenomenon, by reason of its initial
\par painful ugliness. At bottom it is the same active force which is at
\par work on a more grandiose scale in those potent artists and organisers,
\par and builds states, which here, internally, on a smaller and pettier
\par scale and with a retrogressive tendency, makes itself a bad science in
\par the "labyrinth of the breast," to use Goethe's phrase, and which builds
\par negative ideals; it is, I repeat, that identical _instinct of freedom_
\par (to use my own language, the will to power): only the material, on
\par which this force with all its constructive and tyrannous nature is
\par let loose, is here man himself, his whole old animal self--and not as
\par in the case of that more grandiose and sensational phenomenon, the
\par _other_ man, _other_ men. This secret self-tyranny, this cruelty of
\par the artist, this delight in giving a form to one's self as a piece of
\par difficult, refractory, and suffering material, in burning in a will, a
\par critique, a contradiction, a contempt, a negation; this sinister and
\par ghastly labour of love on the part of a soul, whose will is cloven
\par in two within itself, which makes itself suffer from delight in the
\par infliction of suffering; this wholly _active_ bad conscience has
\par finally (as one already anticipates)--true fountainhead as it is of
\par idealism and imagination--produced an abundance of novel and amazing
\par beauty and affirmation, and perhaps has really been the first to
\par give birth to beauty at all. What would beauty be, forsooth, if its
\par contradiction had not first been presented to consciousness, if the
\par ugly had not first said to itself, "I am ugly"? At any rate, after this
\par hint the problem of how far idealism and beauty can be traced in such
\par opposite ideas as "_selflessness_," _self-denial_, _self-sacrifice_,
\par becomes less problematical; and indubitably in future we shall
\par certainly know the real and original character of the _delight_
\par experienced by the self-less, the self-denying, the self-sacrificing:
\par this delight is a phase of cruelty.--So much provisionally for the
\par origin of "altruism" as a _moral_ value, and the marking out the ground
\par from which this value has grown: it is only the bad conscience, only
\par the will for self-abuse, that provides the necessary conditions for the
\par existence of altruism as a _value_.
\par 
\par 
\par 19.
\par 
\par Undoubtedly the bad conscience is an illness, but an illness like
\par pregnancy is an illness. If we search out the conditions under which
\par this illness reaches its most terrible and sublime zenith, we shall see
\par what really first brought about its entry into the world. But to do
\par this we must take a long breath, and we must first of all go back once
\par again to an earlier point of view. The relation at civil law of the
\par ower to his creditor (which has already been discussed in detail), has
\par been interpreted once again (and indeed in a manner which historically
\par is exceedingly remarkable and suspicious) into a relationship, which
\par is perhaps more incomprehensible to us moderns than to any other era;
\par that is, into the relationship of the _existing_ generation to its
\par _ancestors_. Within the original tribal association--we are talking of
\par primitive times--each living generation recognises a legal obligation
\par towards the earlier generation, and particularly towards the earliest,
\par which founded the family (and this is something much more than a mere
\par sentimental obligation, the existence of which, during the longest
\par period of man's history, is by no means indisputable). There prevails
\par in them the conviction that it is only thanks to sacrifices and efforts
\par of their ancestors, that the race _persists_ at all--and that this
\par has to be _paid back_ to them by sacrifices and services. Thus is
\par recognised the _owing_ of a debt, which accumulates continually by
\par reason of these ancestors never ceasing in their subsequent life as
\par potent spirits to secure by their power new privileges and advantages
\par to the race. Gratis, perchance? But there is no gratis for that raw
\par and "mean-souled" age. What return can be made?--Sacrifice (at first,
\par nourishment, in its crudest sense), festivals, temples, tributes of
\par veneration, above all, obedience--since all customs are, _qu\'e2_ works of
\par the ancestors, equally their precepts and commands--are the ancestors
\par ever given enough? This suspicion remains and grows: from time to time
\par it extorts a great wholesale ransom, something monstrous in the way of
\par repayment of the creditor (the notorious sacrifice of the first-born,
\par for example, blood, human blood in any case). The _fear_ of ancestors
\par and their power, the consciousness of owing debts to them, necessarily
\par increases, according to this kind of logic, in the exact proportion
\par that the race itself increases, that the race itself becomes more
\par victorious, more independent, more honoured, more feared. This, and not
\par the contrary, is the fact. Each step towards race decay, all disastrous
\par events, all symptoms of degeneration, of approaching disintegration,
\par always _diminish_ the fear of the founders' spirit, and whittle away
\par the idea of his sagacity, providence, and potent presence. Conceive
\par this crude kind of logic carried to its climax: it follows that the
\par ancestors of the _most powerful_ races must, through the growing fear
\par that they exercise on the imaginations, grow themselves into monstrous
\par dimensions, and become relegated to the gloom of a divine mystery that
\par transcends imagination--the ancestor becomes at last necessarily
\par transfigured into a _god_. Perhaps this is the very origin of the gods,
\par that is, an origin from _fear_! And those who feel bound to add, "but
\par from piety also," will have difficulty in maintaining this theory,
\par with regard to the primeval and longest period of the human race. And
\par of course this is even more the case as regards the _middle_ period,
\par the formative period of the aristocratic races--the aristocratic
\par races which have given back with interest to their founders, the
\par ancestors (heroes, gods), all those qualities which in the meanwhile
\par have appeared in themselves, that is, the aristocratic qualities. We
\par will later on glance again at the ennobling and promotion of the gods
\par (which of course is totally distinct from their "sanctification"): let
\par us now provisionally follow to its end the course of the whole of this
\par development of the consciousness of "owing."
\par 
\par 
\par 20.
\par 
\par According to the teaching of history, the consciousness of owing
\par debts to the deity by no means came to an end with the decay of the
\par clan organisation of society; just as mankind has inherited the
\par ideas of "good" and "bad" from the race-nobility (together with its
\par fundamental tendency towards establishing social distinctions), so
\par with the heritage of the racial and tribal gods it has also inherited
\par the incubus of debts as yet unpaid and the desire to discharge them.
\par The transition is effected by those large populations of slaves and
\par bondsmen, who, whether through compulsion or through submission and
\par "_mimicry,_" have accommodated themselves to the religion of their
\par masters; through this channel these inherited tendencies inundate
\par the world. The feeling of owing a debt to the deity has grown
\par continuously for several centuries, always in the same proportion in
\par which the idea of God and the consciousness of God have grown and
\par become exalted among mankind. (The whole history of ethnic fights,
\par victories, reconciliations, amalgamations, everything, in fact, which
\par precedes the eventual classing of all the social elements in each great
\par race-synthesis, are mirrored in the hotch-potch genealogy of their
\par gods, in the legends of their fights, victories, and reconciliations.
\par Progress towards universal empires invariably means progress towards
\par universal deities; despotism, with its subjugation of the independent
\par nobility, always paves the way for some system or other of monotheism.)
\par The appearance of the Christian god, as the record god up to this time,
\par has for that very reason brought equally into the world the record
\par amount of guilt consciousness. Granted that we have gradually started
\par on the _reverse_ movement, there is no little probability in the
\par deduction, based on the continuous decay in the belief in the Christian
\par god, to the effect that there also already exists a considerable
\par decay in the human consciousness of owing (ought); in fact, we cannot
\par shut our eyes to the prospect of the complete and eventual triumph of
\par atheism freeing mankind from all this feeling of obligation to their
\par origin, their _causa prima_. Atheism and a kind of second innocence
\par complement and supplement each other.
\par 
\par 
\par 21.
\par 
\par So much for my rough and preliminary sketch of the interrelation of
\par the ideas "ought" (owe) and "duty" with the postulates of religion. I
\par have intentionally shelved up to the present the actual moralisation
\par of these ideas (their being pushed back into the conscience, or more
\par precisely the interweaving of the _bad_ conscience with the idea of
\par God), and at the end of the last paragraph used language to the effect
\par that this moralisation did not exist, and that consequently these ideas
\par had necessarily come to an end, by reason of what had happened to their
\par hypothesis, the credence in our "creditor," in God. The actual facts
\par differ terribly from this theory. It is with the moralisation of the
\par ideas "ought" and "duty," and with their being pushed back into the
\par _bad_ conscience, that comes the first actual attempt to _reverse_ the
\par direction of the development we have just described, or at any rate
\par to arrest its evolution; it is just at this juncture that the very
\par hope of an eventual redemption _has to_ put itself once for all into
\par the prison of pessimism, it is at this juncture that the eye _has to_
\par recoil and rebound in despair from off an adamantine impossibility,
\par it is at this juncture that the ideas "guilt" and "duty" have to turn
\par backwards--turn backwards against _whom_? There is no doubt about
\par it; primarily against the "ower," in whom the bad conscience now
\par establishes itself, eats, extends, and grows like a polypus throughout
\par its length and breadth, all with such virulence, that at last, with
\par the impossibility of paying the debt, there becomes conceived the
\par idea of the impossibility of paying the penalty, the thought of its
\par inexpiability (the idea of "eternal punishment")--finally, too, it
\par turns against the "creditor," whether found in the _causa prima_ of
\par man, the origin of the human race, its sire, who henceforth becomes
\par burdened with a curse ("Adam," "original sin," "determination of the
\par will"), or in Nature from whose womb man springs, and on whom the
\par responsibility for the principle of evil is now cast ("Diabolisation of
\par Nature"), or in existence generally, on this logic an absolute _white
\par elephant_, with which mankind is landed (the Nihilistic flight from
\par life, the demand for Nothingness, or for the opposite of existence, for
\par some other existence, Buddhism and the like)--till suddenly we stand
\par before that paradoxical and awful expedient, through which a tortured
\par humanity has found a temporary alleviation, that stroke of genius
\par called Christianity:--God personally immolating himself for the debt of
\par man, God paying himself personally out of a pound of his own flesh, God
\par as the one being who can deliver man from what man had become unable to
\par deliver himself--the creditor playing scapegoat for his debtor, from
\par _love_ (can you believe it?), from love of his debtor!...
\par 
\par 
\par 22.
\par 
\par The reader will already have conjectured what took place on the stage
\par and behind the scenes of this drama. That will for self-torture, that
\par inverted cruelty of the animal man, who, turned subjective and scared
\par into introspection (encaged as he was in "the State," as part of his
\par taming process), invented the bad conscience so as to hurt himself,
\par after the _natural_ outlet for this will to hurt, became blocked--in
\par other words, this man of the bad conscience exploited the religious
\par hypothesis so as to carry his martyrdom to the ghastliest pitch of
\par agonised intensity. Owing something to _God_: this thought becomes his
\par instrument of torture. He apprehends in God the most extreme antitheses
\par that he can find to his own characteristic and ineradicable animal
\par instincts, he himself gives a new interpretation to these animal
\par instincts as being against what he "owes" to God (as enmity, rebellion,
\par and revolt against the "Lord," the "Father," the "Sire," the "Beginning
\par of the world"), he places himself between the horns of the dilemma,
\par "God" and "Devil." Every negation which he is inclined to utter to
\par himself, to the nature, naturalness, and reality of his being, he
\par whips into an ejaculation of "yes," uttering it as something existing,
\par living, efficient, as being God, as the holiness of God, the judgment
\par of God, as the hangmanship of God, as transcendence, as eternity, as
\par unending torment, as hell, as infinity of punishment and guilt. This is
\par a kind of madness of the will in the sphere of psychological cruelty
\par which is absolutely unparalleled:--man's _will_ to find himself guilty
\par and blameworthy to the point of inexpiability, his _will_ to think of
\par himself as punished, without the punishment ever being able to balance
\par the guilt, his _will_ to infect and to poison the fundamental basis
\par of the universe with the problem of punishment and guilt, in order to
\par cut off once and for all any escape out of this labyrinth of "fixed
\par ideas," his will for rearing an ideal--that of the "holy God"--face to
\par face with which he can have tangible proof of his own un-worthiness.
\par Alas for this mad melancholy beast man! What phantasies invade it,
\par what paroxysms of perversity, hysterical senselessness, and _mental
\par bestiality_ break out immediately, at the very slightest check on its
\par being the beast of action. All this is excessively interesting, but
\par at the same time tainted with a black, gloomy, enervating melancholy,
\par so that a forcible veto must be invoked against looking too long into
\par these abysses. Here is _disease_, undubitably, the most ghastly disease
\par that has as yet played havoc among men: and he who can still hear (but
\par man turns now deaf ears to such sounds), how in this night of torment
\par and nonsense there has rung out the cry of _love_, the cry of the most
\par passionate ecstasy, of redemption in _love_, he turns away gripped by
\par an invincible horror--in man there is so much that is ghastly--too long
\par has the world been a mad-house.
\par 
\par 
\par 23.
\par 
\par Let this suffice once for all concerning the origin of the "holy God."
\par The fact that _in itself_ the conception of gods is not bound to
\par lead necessarily to this degradation of the imagination (a temporary
\par representation of whose vagaries we felt bound give), the fact that
\par there exist nobler methods of utilising the invention of gods than in
\par this self-crucifixion and self-degradation of man, in which the last
\par two thousand years of Europe have been past masters--these facts can
\par fortunately be still perceived from every glance that we cast at the
\par Grecian gods, these mirrors of noble and grandiose men, in which the
\par _animal_ in man felt itself deified, and did _not_ devour itself in
\par subjective frenzy. These Greeks long utilised their gods as simple
\par buffers against the "bad conscience"--so that they could continue
\par to enjoy their freedom of soul: this, of course, is diametrically
\par opposed to Christianity's theory of its god. They went _very far_ on
\par this principle, did these splendid and lion-hearted children; and
\par there is no lesser authority than that of the Homeric Zeus for making
\par them realise occasionally that they are taking life too casually.
\par "Wonderful," says he on one occasion--it has to do with the case of
\par \'c6gistheus, a _very_ bad case indeed--
\par 
\par     "Wonderful how they grumble, the mortals against the immortals,
\par     _Only from us_, they presume, _comes evil_, but in their folly,
\par     Fashion they, spite of fate, the doom of their own disaster."
\par 
\par Yet the reader will note and observe that this Olympian spectator and
\par judge is far from being angry with them and thinking evil of them on
\par this score. "How _foolish_ they are," so thinks he of the misdeeds
\par of mortals--and "folly," "imprudence," "a little brain disturbance,"
\par and nothing more, are what the Greeks, even of the strongest, bravest
\par period, have admitted to be the ground of much that is evil and
\par fatal.--Folly, _not_ sin, do you understand?... But even this brain
\par disturbance was a problem--"Come, how is it even possible? How could it
\par have really got in brains like ours, the brains of men of aristocratic
\par ancestry, of men of fortune, of men of good natural endowments, of
\par men of the best society, of men of nobility and virtue?" This was the
\par question that for century on century the aristocratic Greek put to
\par himself when confronted with every (to him incomprehensible) outrage
\par and sacrilege with which one of his peers had polluted himself. "It
\par must be that a god had infatuated him," he would say at last, nodding
\par his head.--This solution is _typical_ of the Greeks, ... accordingly
\par the gods in those times subserved the functions of justifying man to a
\par certain extent even in evil--in those days they took upon themselves
\par not the punishment, but, what is more noble, the guilt.
\par 
\par 
\par 24.
\par 
\par I conclude with three queries, as you will see. "Is an ideal actually
\par set up here, or is one pulled down?" I am perhaps asked.... But have
\par ye sufficiently asked yourselves how dear a payment has the setting up
\par of every ideal in the world exacted? To achieve that consummation how
\par much truth must always be traduced and misunderstood, how many lies
\par must be sanctified, how much conscience has got to be disturbed, how
\par many pounds of "God" have got to be sacrificed every time? To enable
\par a sanctuary to be set up _a sanctuary has got to be destroyed_: that
\par is a law--show me an instance where it has not been fulfilled!...
\par We modern men, we inherit the immemorial tradition of vivisecting
\par the conscience, and practising cruelty to our animal selves. That is
\par the sphere of our most protracted training, perhaps of our artistic
\par prowess, at any rate of our dilettantism and our perverted taste. Man
\par has for too long regarded his natural proclivities with an "evil eye,"
\par so that eventually they have become in his system affiliated to a
\par bad conscience. A converse endeavour would be intrinsically feasible
\par --but who is strong enough to attempt it?--namely, to affiliate to
\par the "bad conscience" all those _unnatural_ proclivities, all those
\par transcendental aspirations, contrary to sense, instinct, nature, and
\par animalism--in short, all past and present ideals, which are all ideals
\par opposed to life, and traducing the world. To whom is one to turn
\par nowadays with _such_ hopes and pretensions?--It is just the _good_
\par men that we should thus bring about our ears; and in addition, as
\par stands to reason, the indolent, the hedgers, the vain, the hysterical,
\par the tired.... What is more offensive or more thoroughly calculated
\par to alienate, than giving any hint of the exalted severity with which
\par we treat ourselves? And again how conciliatory, how full of love
\par does all the world show itself towards us so soon as we do as all
\par the world docs, and "let ourselves go" like all the world. For such
\par a consummation we need spirits of _different_ calibre than seems
\par really feasible in this age; spirits rendered potent through wars and
\par victories, to whom conquest, adventure, danger, even pain, have become
\par a need; for such a consummation we need habituation to sharp, rare air,
\par to winter wanderings, to literal and metaphorical ice and mountains; we
\par even need a kind of sublime malice, a supreme and most self-conscious
\par insolence of knowledge, which is the appanage of great health; we need
\par (to summarise the awful truth) just this _great health_!
\par 
\par Is this even feasible to-day?... But some day, in a stronger age
\par than this rotting and introspective present, must he in sooth come
\par to us, even the _redeemer_ of great love and scorn, the creative
\par spirit, rebounding by the impetus of his own force back again away
\par from every transcendental plane and dimension, he whose solitude
\par is misunderstanded (sic) of the people, as though it were a flight
\par _from_ reality;--while actually it is only his diving, burrowing, and
\par penetrating _into_ reality, so that when he comes again to the light
\par he can at once bring about by these means the _redemption_ of this
\par reality; its redemption from the curse which the old ideal has laid
\par upon it. This man of the future, who in this wise will redeem us from
\par the old ideal, as he will from that ideal's necessary corollary of
\par great nausea, will to nothingness, and Nihilism; this tocsin of noon
\par and of the great verdict, which renders the will again free, who gives
\par back to the world its goal and to man his hope, this Antichrist and
\par Antinihilist, this conqueror of God and of Nothingness--_he must one
\par day come_.
\par 
\par 
\par 25.
\par 
\par But what am I talking of? Enough! Enough? At this juncture I have
\par only one proper course, silence: otherwise tresspass on a domain open
\par alone to one who is younger than I, one stronger, more "_future_" than
\par I--open alone to _Zarathustra, Zarathustra the godless._
