\par 
\par 
\par 
\par THIRD ESSAY.
\par 
\par 
\par WHAT IS THE MEANING OF ASCETIC IDEALS?
\par 
\par 
\par "Careless, mocking, forceful--so does wisdom wish us: she is a woman,
\par and never loves any one but a warrior." Thus Spake Zarathustra.
\par 
\par 
\par 1.
\par 
\par What is the meaning of ascetic ideals? In artists, nothing, or too
\par much; in philosophers and scholars, a kind of "flair" and instinct for
\par the conditions most favourable to advanced intellectualism; in women,
\par at best an _additional_ seductive fascination, a little _morbidezza_
\par on a fine piece of flesh, the angelhood of a fat, pretty animal; in
\par physiological failures and whiners (in the _majority_ of mortals),
\par an attempt to pose as "too good" for this world, a holy form of
\par debauchery, their chief weapon in the battle with lingering pain and
\par ennui; in priests, the actual priestly faith, their best engine of
\par power, and also the supreme authority for power; in saints, finally
\par a pretext for hibernation, their _novissima glori\'e6 cupido_, their
\par peace in nothingness ("God"), their form of madness.
\par 
\par But in the very fact that the ascetic ideal has meant so much to
\par man, lies expressed the fundamental feature of man's will, his
\par _horror vacui: he needs a goal_--and he will sooner will nothingness
\par than not will at all.--Am I not understood?--Have I not been
\par understood?--"Certainly not, sir?"--Well, let us begin at the beginning.
\par 
\par 
\par 2.
\par 
\par What is the meaning of ascetic ideals? Or, to take an individual
\par case in regard to which I have often been consulted, what is the
\par meaning, for example, of an artist like Richard Wagner paying homage
\par to chastity in his old age? He had always done so, of course, in a
\par certain sense, but it was not till quite the end, that he did so in
\par an ascetic sense. What is the meaning of this "change of attitude,"
\par this radical revolution in his attitude--for that was what it was?
\par Wagner veered thereby straight round into his own opposite. What is
\par the meaning of an artist veering round into his own opposite? At
\par this point (granted that we do not mind stopping a little over this
\par question), we immediately call to mind the best, strongest, gayest,
\par and boldest period, that there perhaps ever was in Wagner's life: that
\par was the period, when he was genuinely and deeply occupied with the
\par idea of "Luther's Wedding." Who knows what chance is responsible for
\par our now having the _Meistersingers_ instead of this wedding music?
\par And how much in the latter is perhaps just an echo of the former? But
\par there is no doubt but that the theme would have dealt with the praise
\par of chastity. And certainly it would also have dealt with the praise
\par of sensuality, and even so, it would seem quite in order, and even
\par so, it would have been equally Wagnerian. For there is no necessary
\par antithesis between chastity and sensuality: every good marriage, every
\par authentic heart-felt love transcends this antithesis. Wagner would, it
\par seems to me, have done well to have brought this _pleasing_ reality
\par home once again to his Germans, by means of a bold and graceful "Luther
\par Comedy," for there were and are among the Germans many revilers of
\par sensuality; and perhaps Luther's greatest merit lies just in the fact
\par of his having had the courage of his _sensuality_ (it used to be
\par called, prettily enough, "evangelistic freedom "). But even in those
\par cases where that antithesis between chastity and sensuality does exist,
\par there has fortunately been for some time no necessity for it to be in
\par any way a tragic antithesis. This should, at any rate, be the case with
\par all beings who are sound in mind and body, who are far from reckoning
\par their delicate balance between "animal" and "angel," as being on the
\par face of it one of the principles opposed to existence--the most subtle
\par and brilliant spirits, such as Goethe, such as Hafiz,> have even seen
\par in this a _further_ charm of life. Such "conflicts" actually allure
\par one to life. On the other hand, it is only too clear that when once
\par these ruined swine are reduced to worshipping chastity--and there
\par are such swine--they only see and worship in it the antithesis to
\par themselves, the antithesis to ruined swine. Oh what a tragic grunting
\par and eagerness! You can just think of it--they worship that painful
\par and superfluous contrast, which Richard Wagner in his latter days
\par undoubtedly wished to set to music, and to place on the stage! "_For
\par what purpose, forsooth?_" as we may reasonably ask. What did the swine
\par matter to him; what do they matter to us?
\par 
\par 
\par 3.
\par 
\par At this point it is impossible to beg the further question of what he
\par really had to do with that manly (ah, so unmanly) country bumpkin,
\par that poor devil and natural, Parsifal, whom he eventually made a
\par Catholic by such fraudulent devices. What? Was this Parsifal really
\par meant _seriously_? One might be tempted to suppose the contrary, even
\par to wish it--that the Wagnerian Parsifal was meant joyously, like a
\par concluding play of a trilogy or satyric drama, in which Wagner the
\par tragedian wished to take farewell of us, of himself, above all of
\par tragedy, and to do so in a manner that should be quite fitting and
\par worthy, that is, with an excess of the most extreme and flippant parody
\par of the tragic itself, of the ghastly earthly seriousness and earthly
\par woe of old--a parody of that _most crude phase_ in the unnaturalness
\par of the ascetic ideal, that had at length been overcome. That, as I
\par have said, would have been quite worthy of a great tragedian; who like
\par every artist first attains the supreme pinnacle of his greatness when
\par he can look _down_ into himself and his art, when he can _laugh_ at
\par himself. Is Wagner's Parsifal his secret laugh of superiority over
\par himself, the triumph of that supreme artistic freedom and artistic
\par transcendency which he has at length attained. We might, I repeat,
\par wish it were so, for what can Parsifal, _taken seriously_, amount to?
\par Is it really necessary to see in it (according to an expression once
\par used against me) the product of an insane hate of knowledge, mind,
\par and flesh? A curse on flesh and spirit in one breath of hate? An
\par apostasy and reversion to the morbid Christian and obscurantist ideals?
\par And finally a self-negation and self-elimination on the part of an
\par artist, who till then had devoted all the strength of his will to the
\par contrary, namely, the _highest_ artistic expression of soul and body.
\par And not only of his art; of his life as well. Just remember with what
\par enthusiasm Wagner followed in the footsteps of Feuerbach. Feuerbach's
\par motto of "healthy sensuality" rang in the ears of Wagner during the
\par thirties and forties of the century, as it did in the ears of many
\par Germans (they dubbed themselves "_Young_ Germans"), like the word of
\par redemption. Did he eventually _change his mind_ on the subject? For it
\par seems at any rate that he eventually wished to _change his teaching_
\par on that subject ... and not only is that the case with the Parsifal
\par trumpets on the stage: in the melancholy, cramped, and embarrassed
\par lucubrations of his later years, there are a hundred places in which
\par there are manifestations of a secret wish and will, a despondent,
\par uncertain, unavowed will to preach actual retrogression, conversion,
\par Christianity, medi\'e6valism, and to say to his disciples, "All is vanity!
\par Seek salvation elsewhere!" Even the "blood of the Redeemer" is once
\par invoked.
\par 
\par 
\par 4.
\par 
\par Let me speak out my mind in a case like this, which has many painful
\par elements--and it is a typical case: it is certainly best to separate
\par an artist from his work so completely that he cannot be taken as
\par seriously as his work. He is after all merely the presupposition of
\par his work, the womb, the soil, in certain cases the dung and manure,
\par on which and out of which it grows--and consequently, in most cases,
\par something that must be forgotten if the work itself is to be enjoyed.
\par The insight into the _origin_ of a work is a matter for psychologists
\par and vivisectors, but never either in the present or the future for the
\par \'e6sthetes, the artists. The author and creator of Parsifal was as little
\par spared the necessity of sinking and living himself into the terrible
\par depths and foundations of medi\'e6val soul-contrasts, the necessity of a
\par malignant abstraction from all intellectual elevation, severity, and
\par discipline, the necessity of a kind of mental perversity (if the reader
\par will pardon me such a word), as little as a pregnant woman is spared
\par the horrors and marvels of pregnancy, which, as I have said, must
\par be forgotten if the child is to be enjoyed. We must guard ourselves
\par against the confusion, into which an artist himself would fall only
\par too easily (to employ the English terminology) out of psychological
\par "contiguity"; as though the artist himself actually were the object
\par which he is able to represent, imagine, and express. In point of fact,
\par the position is that even if he conceived he were such an object, he
\par would certainly not represent, conceive, express it. Homer would not
\par have created an Achilles, nor Goethe a Faust, if Homer had been an
\par Achilles or if Goethe had been a Faust. A complete and perfect artist
\par is to all eternity separated from the "real," from the actual; on the
\par other hand, it will be appreciated that he can at times get tired to
\par the point of despair of this eternal "unreality" and falseness of his
\par innermost being--and that he then sometimes attempts to trespass on
\par to the most forbidden ground, on reality, and attempts to have real
\par _existence_. With what success? The success will be guessed--it is the
\par _typical velleity_ of the artist; the same velleity to which Wagner
\par fell a victim in his old age, and for which he had to pay so dearly and
\par so fatally (he lost thereby his most valuable friends). But after all,
\par quite apart from this velleity, who would not wish emphatically for
\par Wagner's own sake that he had taken farewell of us and of his art in a
\par _different_ manner, not with a _Parsifal_, but in more victorious, more
\par self-confident, more Wagnerian style--a style less misleading, a style
\par less ambiguous with regard to his whole meaning, less Schopenhauerian,
\par less Nihilistic?...
\par 
\par 
\par 5.
\par 
\par What, then, is the meaning of ascetic ideals? In the case of an artist
\par we are getting to understand their meaning: _Nothing at all_ ... or so
\par much that it is as good as nothing at all. Indeed, what is the use of
\par them? Our artists have for a long time past not taken up a sufficiently
\par independent attitude, either in the world or against it, to warrant
\par their valuations and the changes in these valuations exciting interest.
\par At all times they have played the valet of some morality, philosophy,
\par or religion, quite apart from the fact that unfortunately they
\par have often enough been the inordinately supple courtiers of their
\par clients and patrons, and the inquisitive toadies of the powers that
\par are existing, or even of the new powers to come. To put it at the
\par lowest, they always need a rampart, a support, an already constituted
\par authority: artists never stand by themselves, standing alone is opposed
\par to their deepest instincts. So, for example, did _Richard Wagner_
\par take, "when the time had come," the philosopher Schopenhauer for his
\par covering man in front, for his rampart. Who would consider it even
\par thinkable, that he would have had the _courage_ for an ascetic ideal,
\par without the support afforded him by the philosophy of Schopenhauer,
\par without the authority of Schopenhauer, which _dominated_ Europe in the
\par seventies? (This is without consideration of the question whether an
\par artist without the milk[1] of an orthodoxy would have been possible at
\par all.) This brings us to the more serious question: What is the meaning
\par of a real _philosopher_ paying homage to the ascetic ideal, a really
\par self-dependent intellect like Schopenhauer, a man and knight with a
\par glance of bronze, who has the courage to be himself, who knows how to
\par stand alone without first waiting for men who cover him in front, and
\par the nods of his superiors? Let us now consider at once the remarkable
\par attitude of Schopenhauer towards _art_, an attitude which has even a
\par fascination for certain types. For that is obviously the reason why
\par Richard Wagner _all at once_ went over to Schopenhauer (persuaded
\par thereto, as one knows, by a poet, Herwegh), went over so completely
\par that there ensued the cleavage of a complete theoretic contradiction
\par between his earlier and his later \'e6sthetic faiths--the earlier, for
\par example, being expressed in _Opera and Drama_, the later in the
\par writings which he published from 1870 onwards. In particular, Wagner
\par from that time onwards (and this is the volte-face which alienates us
\par the most) had no scruples about changing his judgment concerning the
\par value and position of music itself. What did he care if up to that time
\par he had made of music a means, a medium, a "woman," that in order to
\par thrive needed an end, a man--that is, the drama? He suddenly realised
\par that _more_ could be effected by the novelty of the Schopenhauerian
\par theory in _majorem music\'e6 gloriam_--that is to say, by means of the
\par _sovereignty_ of music, as Schopenhauer understood it; music abstracted
\par from and opposed to all the other arts, music as the independent
\par art-in-itself, _not_ like the other arts, affording reflections of the
\par phenomenal world, but rather the language of the will itself, speaking
\par straight out of the "abyss" as its most personal, original, and direct
\par manifestation. This extraordinary rise in the value of music (a rise
\par which seemed to grow out of the Schopenhauerian philosophy) was at
\par once accompanied by an unprecedented rise in the estimation in which
\par the musician himself was held: he became now an oracle, a priest, nay,
\par more than a priest, a kind of mouthpiece for the "intrinsic essence
\par of things," a telephone from the other world--from henceforward
\par he talked not only music, did this ventriloquist of God, he talked
\par metaphysic; what wonder that one day he eventually talked _ascetic
\par ideals_.
\par 
\par 
\par 6.
\par 
\par Schopenhauer has made use of the Kantian treatment of the \'e6sthetic
\par problem--though he certainly did not regard it with the Kantian eyes.
\par Kant thought that he showed honour to art when he favoured and placed
\par in the foreground those of the predicates of the beautiful, which
\par constitute the honour of knowledge: impersonality and universality.
\par This is not the place to discuss whether this was not a complete
\par mistake; all that I wish to emphasise is that Kant, just like other
\par philosophers, instead of envisaging the \'e6sthetic problem from the
\par standpoint of the experiences of the artist (the creator), has only
\par considered art and beauty from the standpoint of the spectator, and
\par has thereby imperceptibly imported the spectator himself into the idea
\par of the "beautiful"! But if only the philosophers of the beautiful had
\par sufficient knowledge of this "spectator"!--Knowledge of him as a great
\par fact of personality, as a great experience, as a wealth of strong and
\par most individual events, desires, surprises, and raptures in the sphere
\par of beauty! But, as I feared, the contrary was always the case. And so
\par we get from our philosophers, from the very beginning, definitions
\par on which the lack of a subtler personal experience squats like a fat
\par worm of crass error, as it does on Kant's famous definition of the
\par beautiful. "That is beautiful," says Kant, "which pleases without
\par interesting." Without interesting! Compare this definition with this
\par other one, made by a real "spectator" and "artist"--by Stendhal, who
\par once called the beautiful _une promesse de bonheur_. Here, at any rate,
\par the one point which Kant makes prominent in the \'e6sthetic position is
\par repudiated and eliminated--_le d\'e9sint\'e9ressement_. Who is right, Kant
\par or Stendhal? When, forsooth, our \'e6sthetes never get tired of throwing
\par into the scales in Kant's favour the fact that under the magic of
\par beauty men can look at even naked female statues "without interest,"
\par we can certainly laugh a little at their expense:--in regard to this
\par ticklish point the experiences of _artists_ are more "interesting,"
\par and at any rate Pygmalion was not necessarily an "un\'e6sthetic man." Let
\par us think all the better of the innocence of our \'e6sthetes, reflected
\par as it is in such arguments; let us, for instance, count to Kant's
\par honour the country-parson na\'efvet\'e9 of his doctrine concerning the
\par peculiar character of the sense of touch! And here we come back to
\par Schopenhauer, who stood in much closer neighbourhood to the arts
\par than did Kant, and yet never escaped outside the pale of the Kantian
\par definition; how was that? The circumstance is marvellous enough: he
\par interprets the expression, "without interest," in the most personal
\par fashion, out of an experience which must in his case have been part and
\par parcel of his regular routine. On few subjects does Schopenhauer speak
\par with such certainty as on the working of \'e6sthetic contemplation: he
\par says of it that it simply counteracts sexual interest, like lupulin
\par and camphor; he never gets tired of glorifying this escape from
\par the "Life-will" as the great advantage and utility of the \'e6sthetic
\par state. In fact, one is tempted to ask if his fundamental conception
\par of Will and Idea, the thought that there can only exist freedom from
\par the "will" by means of "idea," did not originate in a generalisation
\par from this sexual experience. (In all questions concerning the
\par Schopenhauerian philosophy, one should, by the bye, never lose sight of
\par the consideration that it is the conception of a youth of twenty-six,
\par so that it participates not only in what is peculiar to Schopenhauer's
\par life, but in what is peculiar to that special period of his life.)
\par Let us listen, for instance, to one of the most expressive among the
\par countless passages which he has written in honour of the \'e6sthetic
\par state (_World as Will and Idea_, i. 231); let us listen to the tone,
\par the suffering, the happiness, the gratitude, with which such words
\par are uttered: "This is the painless state which Epicurus praised as
\par the highest good and as the state of the gods; we are during that
\par moment freed from the vile pressure of the will, we celebrate the
\par Sabbath of the will's hard labour, the wheel of Ixion stands still."
\par What vehemence of language! What images of anguish and protracted
\par revulsion! How almost pathological is that temporal antithesis between
\par "that moment" and everything else, the "wheel of Ixion," "the hard
\par labour of the will," "the vile pressure of the will." But granted
\par that Schopenhauer was a hundred times right for himself personally,
\par how does that help our insight into the nature of the beautiful?
\par Schopenhauer has described one effect of the beautiful,--the calming
\par of the will,--but is this effect really normal? As has been mentioned,
\par Stendhal, an equally sensual but more happily constituted nature than
\par Schopenhauer, gives prominence to another effect of the "beautiful."
\par "The beautiful promises happiness." To him it is just the excitement
\par of the "will"(the "interest") by the beauty that seems the essential
\par fact. And does not Schopenhauer ultimately lay himself open to the
\par objection, that he is quite wrong in regarding himself as a Kantian on
\par this point, that he has absolutely failed to understand in a Kantian
\par sense the Kantian definition of the beautiful--;that the beautiful
\par pleased him as well by means of an interest, by means, in fact, of the
\par strongest and most personal interest of all, that: of the victim of
\par torture who escapes from his torture?--And to come back again to our
\par first question, "What is the meaning of a philosopher paying homage to
\par ascetic ideals?" We get now, at any rate, a first hint; he wishes to
\par escape _from a torture_.
\par 
\par 
\par 7.
\par 
\par Let us beware of making dismal faces at the word "torture"--there is
\par certainly in this case enough to deduct, enough to discount--there is
\par even something to laugh at. For we must certainly not underestimate
\par the fact that Schopenhauer, who in practice treated sexuality as
\par a personal enemy (including its tool, woman, that "_instrumentum
\par diaboli_"), needed enemies to keep him in a good humour; that he loved
\par grim, bitter, blackish-green words; that he raged for the sake of
\par raging, out of passion; that he would have grown ill, would have become
\par a _pessimist_ (for he was not a pessimist, however much he wished to
\par be), without his enemies, without Hegel, woman, sensuality, and the
\par whole "will for existence" "keeping on." Without them Schopenhauer
\par would not have "kept on," that is a safe wager; he would have run away:
\par but his enemies held him fast, his enemies always enticed him back
\par again to existence, his wrath was just as theirs' was to the ancient
\par Cynics, his balm, his recreation, his recompense, his _remedium_
\par against disgust, his _happiness_. So much with regard to what is most
\par personal in the case of Schopenhauer; on the other hand, there is
\par still much which is typical in him--and only now we come back to our
\par problem. It is an accepted and indisputable fact, so long as there
\par are philosophers in the world and wherever philosophers have existed
\par (from India to England, to take the opposite poles of philosophic
\par ability), that there exists a real irritation and rancour on the part
\par of philosophers towards sensuality. Schopenhauer is merely the most
\par eloquent, and if one has the ear for it, also the most fascinating
\par and enchanting outburst. There similarly exists a real philosophic
\par bias and affection for the whole ascetic ideal; there should be no
\par illusions on this score. Both these feelings, as has been said, belong
\par to the type; if a philosopher lacks both of them, then he is--you may
\par be certain of it--never anything but a "pseudo." What does this mean?
\par For this state of affairs must first be, interpreted: in itself it
\par stands there stupid, to all eternity, like any "Thing-in-itself." Every
\par animal, including la b\'eate philosophe, strives instinctively after an
\par _optimum_ of favourable conditions, under which he can let his whole
\par strength have play, and achieves his maximum consciousness of power;
\par with equal instinctiveness, and with a fine perceptive flair which is
\par superior to any reason, every animal shudders mortally at every kind
\par of disturbance and hindrance which obstructs or could obstruct his way
\par to that optimum (it is not his way to happiness of which I am talking,
\par but his way to power, to action, the most powerful action, and in
\par point of fact in many cases his way to unhappiness). Similarly, the
\par philosopher shudders mortally at <b>marriage</b>, together with all
\par that could persuade him to it--marriage as a fatal hindrance on the
\par way to the _optimum_. Up to the present what great philosophers have
\par been married? Heracleitus, Plato, Descartes, Spinoza, Leibnitz, Kant,
\par Schopenhauer--they were not married, and, further, one cannot _imagine_
\par them as married. A married philosopher belongs to _comedy_, that is
\par my rule; as for that exception of a Socrates--the malicious Socrates
\par married himself, it seems, _ironice_, just to prove this _very_ rule.
\par Every philosopher would say, as Buddha said, when the birth of a son
\par was announced to him: "R\'e2houla has been born to me, a fetter has been
\par forged for me" (R\'e2houla means here "a little demon"); there must come
\par an hour of reflection to every "free spirit" (granted that he has had
\par previously an hour of thoughtlessness), just as one came once to the
\par same Buddha: "Narrowly cramped," he reflected, "is life in the house;
\par it is a place of uncleanness; freedom is found in leaving the house."
\par Because he thought like this, he left the house. So many bridges to
\par independence are shown in the ascetic idea], that the philosopher
\par cannot refrain from exultation and clapping of hands when he hears
\par the history of all those resolute ones, who on one day uttered a nay
\par to all servitude and went into some _desert_; even granting that they
\par were only strong asses, and the absolute opposite of strong minds.
\par What, then, does the ascetic ideal mean in a philosopher? This is my
\par answer--it will have been guessed long ago: when he sees this ideal
\par the philosopher smiles because he sees therein an _optimum_ of the
\par conditions of the highest and boldest intellectuality; he does not
\par thereby deny "existence," he rather affirms thereby _his_ existence
\par and _only_ his existence, and this perhaps to the point of not being
\par far off the blasphemous wish, _pereat mundus, fiat philosophia, fiat
\par philosophus, fiam!_
\par 
\par 
\par 8.
\par 
\par These philosophers, you see, are by no means uncorrupted witnesses and
\par judges of the _value_ of the ascetic ideal. They think _of themselves_
\par --what is the "saint" to them? They think of that which to them
\par personally is most indispensable; of freedom from compulsion,
\par disturbance, noise: freedom from business, duties, cares; of clear
\par head; of the dance, spring, and flight of thoughts; of good air--rare,
\par clear, free, dry, as is the air on the heights, in which every animal
\par creature becomes more intellectual and gains wings; they think of
\par peace in every cellar; all the hounds neatly chained; no baying of
\par enmity and uncouth rancour; no remorse of wounded ambition; quiet
\par and submissive internal organs, busy as mills, but unnoticed; the
\par heart alien, transcendent, future, posthumous--to summarise, they
\par mean by the ascetic ideal the joyous asceticism of a deified and
\par newly fledged animal, sweeping over life rather than resting. We know
\par what are the three great catch-words of the ascetic ideal: poverty,
\par humility, chastity; and now just look closely at the life of all
\par the great fruitful inventive spirits--you will always find again
\par and again these three qualities up to a certain extent. _Not_ for a
\par minute, as is self-evident, as though, perchance, they were part of
\par their virtues--what has this type of man to do with virtues?--but as
\par the most essential and natural conditions of their _best_ existence,
\par their _finest_ fruitfulness. In this connection it is quite possible
\par that their predominant intellectualism had first to curb an unruly and
\par irritable pride, or an insolent sensualism, or that it had all its
\par work cut out to maintain its wish for the "desert" against perhaps
\par an inclination to luxury and dilettantism, or similarly against an
\par extravagant liberality of heart and hand. But their intellect did
\par effect all this, simply because it was the _dominant_ instinct, which
\par carried through its orders in the case of all the other instincts.
\par It effects it still; if it ceased to do so, it would simply not be
\par dominant. But there is not one iota of "virtue" in all this. Further,
\par the _desert_, of which I just spoke, in which the strong, independent,
\par and well-equipped spirits retreat into their hermitage--oh, how
\par different is it from the cultured classes' dream of a desert! In
\par certain cases, in fact, the cultured classes themselves are the desert.
\par And it is certain that all the actors of the intellect would not endure
\par this desert for a minute. It is nothing like romantic and Syrian enough
\par for them, nothing like enough of a stage desert! Here as well there
\par are plenty of asses, but at this point the resemblance ceases. But a
\par desert nowadays is something like this--perhaps a deliberate obscurity;
\par a getting-out-of the way of one's self; a fear of noise, admiration,
\par papers, influence; a little office, a daily task, something that hides
\par rather than brings to light; sometimes associating with harmless,
\par cheerful beasts and fowls, the sight of which refreshes; a mountain for
\par company, but not a dead one, one with _eyes_ (that is, with lakes);
\par in certain cases even a room in a crowded hotel where one can reckon
\par on not being recognised, and on being able to talk with impunity to
\par every one: here is the desert--oh, it is lonely enough, believe me!
\par I grant that when Heracleitus retreated to the courts and cloisters
\par of the colossal temple of Artemis, that "wilderness" was worthier;
\par why do we _lack_ such temples? (perchance we do not lack them: I just
\par think of my splendid study in the _Piazza di San Marco_, in spring, of
\par course, and in the morning, between ten and twelve). But that which
\par Heracleitus shunned is still just what we too avoid nowadays: the
\par noise and democratic babble of the Ephesians, their politics, their
\par news from the "empire" (I mean, of course, Persia), their market-trade
\par in "the things of to-day "--for there is one thing from which we
\par philosophers especially need a rest--from the things of "to-day." We
\par honour the silent, the cold, the noble, the far, the past, everything,
\par in fact, at the sight of which the soul is not bound to brace itself up
\par and defend itself--something with which one can speak without _speaking
\par aloud_. Just listen now to the tone a spirit has when it speaks; every
\par spirit has its own tone and loves its own tone. That thing yonder, for
\par instance, is bound to be an agitator, that is, a hollow head, a hollow
\par mug: whatever may go into him, everything comes back from him dull and
\par thick, heavy with the echo of the great void. That spirit yonder nearly
\par always speaks hoarse: has he, perchance, _thought_ himself hoarse?
\par It may be so--ask the physiologists--but he who thinks in _words_,
\par thinks as a speaker and not as a thinker (it shows that he does not
\par think of objects or think objectively, but only of his relations
\par with objects--that, in point of fact, he only thinks of himself and
\par his audience). This third one speaks aggressively, he comes too near
\par our body, his breath blows on us--we shut our mouth involuntarily,
\par although he speaks to us through a book: the tone of his style supplies
\par the reason--he has no time, he has small faith in himself, he finds
\par expression now or never. But a spirit who is sure of himself speaks
\par softly; he seeks secrecy, he lets himself be awaited, A philosopher
\par is recognised by the fact that he shuns three brilliant and noisy
\par things--fame, princes, and women: which is not to say that they do not
\par come to him. He shuns every glaring light: therefore he shuns his time
\par and its "daylight." Therein he is as a shadow; the deeper sinks the
\par sun, the greater grows the shadow. As for his humility, he endures, as
\par he endures darkness, a certain dependence and obscurity: further, he is
\par afraid of the shock of lightning, he shudders at the insecurity of a
\par tree which is too isolated and too exposed, on which every storm vents
\par its temper, every temper its storm. His "maternal" instinct, his secret
\par love for that which grows in him, guides him into states where he is
\par relieved from the necessity of taking care of _himself_, in the same
\par way in which the "_mother_" instinct in woman has thoroughly maintained
\par up to the present woman's dependent position. After all, they demand
\par little enough, do these philosophers, their favourite motto is, "He
\par who possesses is possessed." All this is _not_, as I must say again
\par and again, to be attributed to a virtue, to a meritorious wish for
\par moderation and simplicity; but because their supreme lord so demands
\par of them, demands wisely and inexorably; their lord who is eager only
\par for one thing, for which alone he musters, and for which alone he
\par hoards everything--time, strength, love, interest. This kind of man
\par likes not to be disturbed by enmity, he likes not to be disturbed by
\par friendship, it is a type which forgets or despises easily. It strikes
\par him as bad form to play the martyr, "to _suffer_ for truth"--he leaves
\par all that to the ambitious and to the stage-heroes of the intellect,
\par and to all those, in fact, who have time enough for such luxuries
\par (they themselves, the philosophers, have something _to do_ for truth).
\par They make a sparing use of big words; they are said to be adverse to
\par the word "truth" itself: it has a "high falutin'" ring. Finally, as
\par far as the chastity of philosophers is concerned, the fruitfulness
\par of this type of mind is manifestly in another sphere than that of
\par children; perchance in some other sphere, too, they have the survival
\par of their name, their little immortality (philosophers in ancient
\par India would express themselves with still greater boldness: "Of what
\par use is posterity to him whose soul is the world?"). In this attitude
\par there is not a trace of chastity, by reason of any ascetic scruple or
\par hatred of the flesh, any more than it is chastity for an athlete or a
\par jockey to abstain from women; it is rather the will of the dominant
\par instinct, at any rate, during the period of their advanced philosophic
\par pregnancy. Every artist knows the harm done by sexual intercourse
\par on occasions of great mental strain and preparation; as far as the
\par strongest artists and those with the surest instincts are concerned,
\par this is not necessarily a case of experience--hard experience--but it
\par is simply their "maternal" instinct which, in order to benefit the
\par growing work, disposes recklessly (beyond all its normal stocks and
\par supplies) of the _vigour_ of its _animal_ life; the greater power then
\par _absorbs_ the lesser. Let us now apply this interpretation to gauge
\par correctly the case of Schopenhauer, which we have already mentioned: in
\par his case, the sight of the beautiful acted manifestly like a resolving
\par irritant on the chief power of his nature (the power of contemplation
\par and of intense penetration); so that this strength exploded and became
\par suddenly master of his consciousness. But this by no means excludes
\par the possibility of that particular sweetness and fulness, which is
\par peculiar to the \'e6sthetic state, springing directly from the ingredient
\par of sensuality (just as that "idealism" which is peculiar to girls at
\par puberty originates in the same source)--it may be, consequently, that
\par sensuality is not removed by the approach of the \'e6sthetic state, as
\par Schopenhauer believed, but merely becomes transfigured, and ceases to
\par enter into the consciousness as sexual excitement. (I shall return once
\par again to this point in connection with the more delicate problems of
\par the _physiology of the \'e6sthetic_, a subject which up to the present has
\par been singularly untouched and unelucidated.)
\par 
\par 
\par 9.
\par 
\par A certain asceticism, a grimly gay whole-hearted renunciation, is, as
\par we have seen, one of the most favourable conditions for the highest
\par intellectualism, and, consequently, for the most natural corollaries
\par of such intellectualism: we shall therefore be proof against any
\par surprise at the philosophers in particular always treating the ascetic
\par ideal with a certain amount of predilection. A serious historical
\par investigation shows the bond between the ascetic ideal and philosophy
\par to be still much tighter and still much stronger. It may be said that
\par it was only in the _leading strings_ of this ideal that philosophy
\par really learnt to make its first steps and baby paces--alas how
\par clumsily, alas how crossly, alas how ready to tumble down and lie on
\par its stomach was this shy little darling of a brat with its bandy legs!
\par The early history of philosophy is like that of all good things;--for a
\par long time they had not the courage to be themselves, they kept always
\par looking round to see if no one would come to their help; further, they
\par were afraid of all who looked at them. Just enumerate in order the
\par particular tendencies and virtues of the philosopher--his tendency to
\par doubt, his tendency to deny, his tendency to wait (to be "ephectic"),
\par his tendency to analyse, search, explore, dare, his tendency to compare
\par and to equalise, his will to be neutral and objective, his will for
\par everything which is "_sine ira et studio_":--has it yet been realised
\par that for quite a lengthy period these tendencies went counter to the
\par first claims of morality and conscience? (To say nothing at all of
\par _Reason_, which even Luther chose to call _Frau Kl\'fcglin_,[2] the sly
\par whore.) Has it been yet appreciated that a philosopher, in the event
\par of his _arriving_ at self-consciousness, must needs feel himself an
\par incarnate "nitimur in vetitum"--and consequently guard himself against
\par "his own sensations," against self-consciousness? It is, I repeat, just
\par the same with all good things, on which we now pride ourselves; even
\par judged by the standard of the ancient Greeks, our whole modern life,
\par in so far as it is not weakness, but power and the consciousness of
\par power, appears pure "Hybris" and godlessness: for the things which are
\par the very reverse of those which we honour to-day, have had for a long
\par time conscience on their side, and God as their guardian. "Hybris"
\par is our whole attitude to nature nowadays, our violation of nature
\par with the help of machinery, and all the unscrupulous ingenuity of our
\par scientists and engineers. "Hybris" is our attitude to God, that is, to
\par some alleged teleological and ethical spider behind the meshes of the
\par great trap of the causal web. Like Charles the Bold in his war with
\par Louis the Eleventh, we may say, "je combats l'universelle araign\'e9e";
\par "Hybris" is our attitude to ourselves--for we experiment with ourselves
\par in a way that we would not allow with any animal, and with pleasure
\par and curiosity open our soul in our living body: what matters now to
\par us the "salvation" of the soul? We heal ourselves afterwards: being
\par ill is instructive, we doubt it not, even more instructive than being
\par well--inoculators of disease seem to us to-day even more necessary
\par than any medicine-men and "saviours." There is no doubt we do violence
\par to ourselves nowadays, we crackers of the soul's kernel, we incarnate
\par riddles, who are ever asking riddles, as though life were naught else
\par than the cracking of a nut; and even thereby must we necessarily become
\par day by day more and more worthy to be asked questions and worthy to ask
\par them, even thereby do we perchance also become worthier to--live?
\par 
\par ... All good things were once bad things; from every original sin has
\par grown an original virtue. Marriage, for example, seemed for a long time
\par a sin against the rights of the community; a man formerly paid a fine
\par for the insolence of claiming one woman to himself (to this phase
\par belongs, for instance, the _jus prim\'e6 noctis_, to-day still in Cambodia
\par the privilege of the priest, that guardian of the "good old customs").
\par 
\par The soft, benevolent, yielding, sympathetic feelings--eventually valued
\par so highly that they almost became "intrinsic values," were for a very
\par long time actually despised by their possessors: gentleness was then
\par a subject for shame, just as hardness is now (compare _Beyond Good
\par and Evil_, Aph. 260). The submission to law: oh, with what qualms of
\par conscience was it that the noble races throughout the world renounced
\par the _vendetta_ and gave the law power over themselves! Law was long a
\par _vetitum_, a blasphemy, an innovation; it was introduced with force,
\par like a force, to which men only submitted with a sense of personal
\par shame. Every tiny step forward in the world was formerly made at
\par the cost of mental and physical torture. Nowadays the whole of this
\par point of view--"that not only stepping forward, nay, stepping at all,
\par movement, change, all needed their countless martyrs," rings in our
\par ears quite strangely. I have put it forward in the _Dawn of Day_, Aph.
\par 18. "Nothing is purchased more dearly," says the same book a little
\par later, "than the modicum of human reason and freedom which is now our
\par pride. But that pride is the reason why it is now almost impossible
\par for us to feel in sympathy with those immense periods of the 'Morality
\par of Custom,' which lie at the beginning of the 'world's history,'
\par constituting as they do the real decisive historical principle which
\par has fixed the character of humanity; those periods, I repeat, when
\par throughout the world suffering passed for virtue, cruelty for virtue,
\par deceit for virtue, revenge for virtue, repudiation of the reason for
\par virtue; and when, conversely, well-being passed current for danger, the
\par desire for knowledge for danger, pity for danger, peace for danger,
\par being pitied for shame, work for shame, madness for divinity, and
\par _change_ for immorality and incarnate corruption!"
\par 
\par 
\par 10.
\par 
\par There is in the same book, Aph. 12, an explanation of the _burden_
\par of unpopularity under which the earliest race of contemplative men
\par had to live--despised almost as widely as they were first feared!
\par Contemplation first appeared on earth in a disguised shape, in an
\par ambiguous form, with an evil heart and often with an uneasy head:
\par there is no doubt about it. The inactive, brooding, unwarlike element
\par in the instincts of contemplative men long invested them with a cloud
\par of suspicion: the only way to combat this was to excite a definite
\par _fear_. And the old Brahmans, for example, knew to a nicety how to do
\par this! The oldest philosophers were well versed in giving to their very
\par existence and appearance, meaning, firmness, background, by reason
\par whereof men learnt to _fear_ them; considered more precisely, they
\par did this from an even more fundamental need, the need of inspiring
\par in themselves fear and self-reverence. For they found even in their
\par own souls all the valuations turned _against_ themselves; they had
\par to fight down every kind of suspicion and antagonism against "the
\par philosophic element in themselves." Being men of a terrible age,
\par they did this with terrible means: cruelty to themselves, ingenious
\par self-mortification--this was the chief method of these ambitious
\par hermits and intellectual revolutionaries, who were obliged to force
\par down the gods and the traditions of their own soul, so as to enable
\par themselves to _believe_ in their own revolution. I remember the famous
\par story of the King Vicvamitra, who, as the result of a thousand years
\par of self-martyrdom, reached such a consciousness of power and such a
\par confidence in himself that he undertook to build a _new heaven_: the
\par sinister symbol of the oldest and newest history of philosophy in the
\par whole world. Every one who has ever built anywhere a "_new heaven_"
\par first found the power thereto in his _own hell_.. .. Let us compress
\par the facts into a short formula. The philosophic spirit had, in order
\par to be _possible_ to any extent at all, to masquerade and disguise
\par itself as one of the _previously fixed_ types of the contemplative
\par man, to disguise itself as priest, wizard, soothsayer, as a religious
\par man generally: the _ascetic ideal_ has for a long time served the
\par philosopher as a superficial form, as a condition which enabled him
\par to exist. .. . To be able to be a philosopher he had to exemplify the
\par ideal; to exemplify it, he was bound to _believe_ in it. The peculiarly
\par etherealised abstraction of philosophers, with their negation of the
\par world, their enmity to life, their disbelief in the senses, which has
\par been maintained up to the most recent time, and has almost thereby come
\par to be accepted as the ideal _philosophic attitude_--this abstraction
\par is the result of those enforced conditions under which philosophy
\par came into existence, and continued to exist; inasmuch as for quite
\par a very long time philosophy would have been _absolutely impossible_
\par in the world without an ascetic cloak and dress, without an ascetic
\par self-misunderstanding. Expressed plainly and palpably, the _ascetic
\par priest_ has taken the repulsive and sinister form of the caterpillar,
\par beneath which and behind which alone philosophy could live and slink
\par about.. ..
\par 
\par Has all that really changed? Has that flamboyant and dangerous winged
\par creature, that "spirit" which that caterpillar concealed within itself,
\par has it, I say, thanks to a sunnier, warmer, lighter world, really
\par and finally flung off its hood and escaped into the light? Can we
\par to-day point to enough pride, enough daring, enough courage, enough
\par self-confidence, enough mental will, enough will for responsibility,
\par enough freedom of the will, to enable the philosopher to be now in the
\par world really--_possible_?
\par 
\par 
\par 11.
\par 
\par And now, after we have caught sight of the _ascetic priest_, let us
\par tackle our problem. What is the meaning of the ascetic ideal? It now
\par first becomes serious--vitally serious. We are now confronted with the
\par _real representatives of the serious_. "What is the meaning of all
\par seriousness?" This even more radical question is perchance already
\par on the tip of our tongue: a question, fairly, for physiologists, but
\par which we for the time being skip. In that ideal the ascetic priest
\par finds not only his faith, but also his will, his power, his interest.
\par His _right_ to existence stands and falls with that ideal. What wonder
\par that we here run up against a terrible opponent (on the supposition,
\par of course, that we are the opponents of that ideal), an opponent
\par fighting for his life against those who repudiate that ideal!. .. On
\par the other hand, it is from the outset improbable that such a biased
\par attitude towards our problem will do him any particular good; the
\par ascetic priest himself will scarcely prove the happiest champion of
\par his own ideal (on the same principle on which a woman usually fails
\par when she wishes to champion "woman")--let alone proving the most
\par objective critic and judge of the controversy now raised. We shall
\par therefore--so much is already obvious--rather have actually to help
\par him to defend himself properly against ourselves, than we shall have
\par to fear being too well beaten by him. The idea, which is the subject
\par of this dispute, is the value of our life from the standpoint of the
\par ascetic priests: this life, then (together with the whole of which it
\par is a part, "Nature," "the world," the whole sphere of becoming and
\par passing away), is placed by them in relation to an existence of quite
\par another character, which it excludes and to which it is opposed, unless
\par it _deny_ its own self: in this case, the case of an ascetic life,
\par life is taken as a bridge to another existence. The ascetic treats
\par life as a maze, in which one must walk backwards till one comes to the
\par place where it starts; or he treats it as an error which one may, nay
\par _must_, refute by action: for he demands that he should be followed;
\par he enforces, where he can, his valuation of existence. What does this
\par mean? Such a monstrous valuation is not an exceptional case, or a
\par curiosity recorded in human history: it is one of the most general
\par and persistent facts that there are. The reading from the vantage
\par of a distant star of the capital letters of our earthly life, would
\par perchance lead to the conclusion that the earth was the especially
\par _ascetic planet_, a den of discontented, arrogant, and repulsive
\par creatures, who never got rid of a deep disgust of themselves, of the
\par world, of all life, and did themselves as much hurt as possible out
\par of pleasure in hurting--presumably their one and only pleasure. Let
\par us consider how regularly, how universally, how practically at every
\par single period the ascetic priest puts in his appearance: he belongs to
\par no particular race; he thrives everywhere; he grows out of all classes.
\par Not that he perhaps bred this valuation by heredity and propagated
\par it--the contrary is the case. It must be a necessity of the first order
\par which makes this species, hostile, as it is, to _life_, always grow
\par again and always thrive again.--_Life_ itself must certainly _have an
\par interest_ in the continuance of such a type of self-contradiction. For
\par an ascetic life is a self-contradiction: here rules resentment without
\par parallel, the resentment of an insatiate instinct and ambition, that
\par would be master, not over some element in life, but over life itself,
\par over life's deepest, strongest, innermost conditions; here is an
\par attempt made to utilise power to dam the sources of power; here does
\par the green eye of jealousy turn even against physiological well-being,
\par especially against the expression of such well-being, beauty, joy;
\par while a sense of pleasure is experienced and _sought_ in abortion, in
\par decay, in pain, in misfortune, in ugliness, in voluntary punishment,
\par in the exercising, flagellation, and sacrifice of the self. All this
\par is in the highest degree paradoxical: we are here confronted with a
\par rift that _wills_ itself to be a rift, which _enjoys_ itself in this
\par very _suffering_, and even becomes more and more certain of itself,
\par more and more triumphant, in proportion as its own presupposition,
\par physiological vitality, _decreases_. "The triumph just in the supreme
\par agony ": under this extravagant emblem did the ascetic ideal fight from
\par of old; in this mystery of seduction, in this picture of rapture and
\par torture, it recognised its brightest light, its salvation, its final
\par victory. _Crux, nux, lux_--it has all these three in one.
\par 
\par 
\par 12.
\par 
\par Granted that such an incarnate will for contradiction and unnaturalness
\par is induced to _philosophise_; on what will it vent its pet caprice?
\par On that which has been felt with the greatest certainty to be true,
\par to be real; it will look for _error_ in those very places where the
\par life instinct fixes truth with the greatest positiveness. It will, for
\par instance, after the example of the ascetics of the Vedanta Philosophy,
\par reduce matter to an illusion, and similarly treat pain, multiplicity,
\par the whole logical contrast of "_Subject_" and "_Object_"--errors,
\par nothing but errors! To renounce the belief in one's own ego, to
\par deny to one's self one's own "reality"--what a triumph! and here
\par already we have a much higher kind of triumph, which is not merely
\par a triumph over the senses, over the palpable, but an infliction of
\par violence and cruelty on _reason_; and this ecstasy culminates in the
\par ascetic self-contempt, the ascetic scorn of one's own reason making
\par this decree: _there is_ a domain of truth and of life, but reason is
\par specially _excluded_ therefrom.. .. By the bye, even in the Kantian
\par idea of "the intellegible character of things" there remains a trace
\par of that schism, so dear to the heart of the ascetic, that schism
\par which likes to turn reason against reason; in fact, "intelligible
\par character" means in Kant a kind of quality in things of which the
\par intellect comprehends this much, that for it, the intellect, it is
\par _absolutely incomprehensible_. After all, let us, in our character
\par of knowers, not be ungrateful towards such determined reversals of
\par the ordinary perspectives and values, with which the mind had for
\par too long raged against itself with an apparently futile sacrilege!
\par In the same way the very seeing of another vista, the very _wishing_
\par to see another vista, is no little training and preparation of the
\par intellect for its eternal "_Objectivity_"--objectivity being understood
\par not as "contemplation without interest" (for that is inconceivable
\par and non-sensical), but as the ability to have the pros and cons _in
\par one's power_ and to switch them on and off, so as to get to know how
\par to utilise, for the advancement of knowledge, the _difference_ in
\par the perspective and in the emotional interpretations. But let us,
\par forsooth, my philosophic colleagues, henceforward guard ourselves more
\par carefully against this mythology of dangerous ancient ideas, which has
\par set up a "pure, will-less, painless, timeless subject of knowledge";
\par let us guard ourselves from the tentacles of such contradictory ideas
\par as "pure reason," "absolute spirituality," "knowledge-in-itself":--in
\par these theories an eye that cannot be thought of is required to think,
\par an eye which ex hypothesi has no direction at all, an eye in which
\par the active and interpreting functions are cramped, are absent; those
\par functions, I say, by means of which "abstract" seeing first became
\par seeing something; in these theories consequently the absurd and the
\par non-sensical is always demanded of the eye. There is only a seeing
\par from a perspective, only a "knowing" from a perspective, and the more
\par emotions we express over a thing, the more eyes, different eyes, we
\par train on the same thing, the more complete will be our "idea" of that
\par thing, our "objectivity." But the elimination of the will altogether,
\par the switching off of the emotions all and sundry, granted that we could
\par do so, what! would not that be called intellectual castration?
\par 
\par 
\par 13.
\par 
\par But let us turn back. Such a self-contradiction, as apparently
\par manifests itself among the ascetics, "Life turned against Life,"
\par is--this much is absolutely obvious--from the physiological and not now
\par from the psychological standpoint, simply nonsense. It can only be an
\par apparent contradiction; it must be a kind of provisional expression, an
\par explanation, a formula, an adjustment, a psychological misunderstanding
\par of something, whose real nature could not be understood for a long
\par time, and whose _real essence_ could not be described; a mere word
\par jammed into an old _gap_ of human knowledge. To put briefly the
\par facts against its being real: _the ascetic ideal springs from the
\par prophylactic and self-preservative instincts which mark a decadent
\par life_, which seeks by every means in its power to maintain its position
\par and fight for its existence; it points to a partial physiological
\par depression and exhaustion, against which the most profound and intact
\par life-instincts fight ceaselessly with new weapons and discoveries. The
\par ascetic ideal is such a weapon: its position is consequently exactly
\par the reverse of that which the worshippers of the ideal imagine--life
\par struggles in it and through it with death and against death; the
\par ascetic ideal is a dodge for the _preservation_ of life. An important
\par fact is brought out in the extent to which, as history teaches, this
\par ideal could rule and exercise power over man, especially in all those
\par places where the civilisation and taming of man was completed: that
\par fact is, the diseased state of man up to the present, at any rate, of
\par the man who has been tamed, the physiological struggle of man with
\par death (more precisely, with the disgust with life, with exhaustion,
\par with the wish for the "end"). The ascetic priest is the incarnate wish
\par for an existence of another kind, an existence on another plane,--he
\par is, in fact, the highest point of this wish, its official ecstasy and
\par passion: but it is the very _power_ of this wish which is the fetter
\par that binds him here; it is just that which makes him into a tool that
\par must labour to create more favourable conditions for earthly existence,
\par for existence on the human plane--it is with this very power that he
\par keeps the whole herd of failures, distortions, abortions, unfortunates,
\par _sufferers from themselves_ of every kind, fast to existence, while
\par he as the herdsman goes instinctively on in front. You understand
\par me already: this ascetic priest, this apparent enemy of life, this
\par denier--he actually belongs to the really great _conservative_ and
\par _affirmative_ forces of life.... What does it come from, this diseased
\par state? For man is more diseased, more uncertain, more changeable,
\par more unstable than any other animal, there is no doubt of it--he is
\par the diseased animal: what does it spring from? Certainly he has also
\par dared, innovated, braved more, challenged fate more than all the other
\par animals put together; he, the great experimenter with himself, the
\par unsatisfied, the insatiate, who struggles for the supreme mastery with
\par beast, Nature, and gods, he, the as yet ever uncompelled, the ever
\par future, who finds no more any rest from his own aggressive strength,
\par goaded inexorably on by the spur of the future dug into the flesh of
\par the present:--how should not so brave and rich an animal also be the
\par most endangered, the animal with the longest and deepest sickness
\par among all sick animals?... Man is sick of it, oft enough there are
\par whole epidemics of this satiety (as about 1348, the time of the Dance
\par of Death): but even this very nausea, this tiredness, this disgust
\par with himself, all this is discharged from him with such force that
\par it is immediately made into a new fetter. His "nay," which he utters
\par to life, brings to light as though by magic an abundance of graceful
\par "yeas"; even when he _wounds_ himself, this master of destruction, of
\par self-destruction, it is subsequently the wound itself that forces him
\par to live.
\par 
\par 
\par 14.
\par 
\par The more normal is this sickliness in man--and we cannot dispute
\par this normality--the higher honour should be paid to the rare cases
\par of psychical and physical powerfulness, the _windfalls_ of humanity,
\par and the more strictly should the sound be guarded from that worst of
\par air, the air of the sick-room. Is that done? The sick are the greatest
\par danger for the healthy; it is not from the strongest that harm comes to
\par the strong, but from the weakest. Is that known? Broadly considered,
\par it is not for a minute the fear of man, whose diminution should be
\par wished for; for this fear forces the strong to be strong, to be at
\par times terrible--it preserves in its integrity the sound type of man.
\par What is to be feared, what does work with a fatality found in no other
\par fate, is not the great fear of, but the great _nausea_ with, man; and
\par equally so the great pity for man. Supposing that both these things
\par were one day to espouse each other, then inevitably the maximum of
\par monstrousness would immediately come into the world--the "last will"
\par of man, his will for nothingness, Nihilism. And, in sooth, the way is
\par well paved thereto. He who not only has his nose to smell with, but
\par also has eyes and ears, he sniffs almost wherever he goes to-day an
\par air something like that of a mad-house, the air of a hospital--I am
\par speaking, as stands to reason, of the cultured areas of mankind, of
\par every kind of "Europe" that there is in fact in the world. The _sick_
\par are the great danger of man, _not_ the evil, _not_ the "beasts of
\par prey." They who are from the outset botched, oppressed, broken, those
\par are they, the weakest are they, who most undermine the life beneath the
\par feet of man, who instil the most dangerous venom and scepticism into
\par our trust in life, in man, in ourselves. Where shall we escape from
\par it, from that covert look (from which we carry away a deep sadness),
\par from that averted look of him who is misborn from the beginning, that
\par look which betrays what such a man says to himself--that look which is
\par a groan?" Would that I were something else," so groans this look, "but
\par there is no hope. I am what I am: how could I get away from myself?
\par And, verily--_I am sick of myself!_" On such a soil of self-contempt,
\par a veritable swamp soil, grows that weed, that poisonous growth, and
\par all so tiny, so hidden, so ignoble, so sugary. Here teem the worms
\par of revenge and vindictiveness; here the air reeks of things secret
\par and unmentionable; here is ever spun the net of the most malignant
\par conspiracy--the conspiracy of the sufferers against the sound and the
\par victorious; here is the sight of the victorious _hated_. And what
\par lying so as not to acknowledge this hate as hate! What a show of big
\par words and attitudes, what an art of "righteous" calumniation! These
\par abortions! what a noble eloquence gushes from their lips! What an
\par amount of sugary, slimy, humble submission oozes in their eyes! What do
\par they really want? At any rate to _represent_ righteousness ness, love,
\par wisdom, superiority, that is the ambition of these "lowest ones," these
\par sick ones! And how clever does such an ambition make them! You cannot,
\par in fact, but admire the counterfeiter dexterity with which the stamp
\par of virtue, even the ring, the golden ring of virtue, is here imitated.
\par They have taken a lease of virtue absolutely for themselves, have these
\par weaklings and wretched invalids, there is no doubt of it; "We alone are
\par the good, the righteous," so do they speak, "we alone are the _homines
\par bon\'e6 voluntatis_." They stalk about in our midst as living reproaches,
\par as warnings to us--as though health, fitness, strength, pride, the
\par sensation of power, were really vicious things in themselves, for
\par which one would have some day to do penance, bitter penance. Oh, how
\par they themselves are ready in their hearts to exact penance, how they
\par thirst after being _hangmen_!
\par 
\par Among them is an abundance of revengeful ones disguised as judges,
\par who ever mouth the word righteousness like a venomous spittle--with
\par mouth, I say, always pursed, always ready to spit at everything,
\par which does not wear a discontented look, but is of good cheer as it
\par goes on its way. Among them, again, is that most loathsome species
\par of the vain, the lying abortions, who make a point of representing
\par "beautiful souls," and perchance of bringing to the market as "purity
\par of heart" their distorted sensualism swathed in verses and other
\par bandages; the species of "self-comforters" and masturbators of their
\par own souls. The sick man's will to represent _some_ form or other of
\par superiority, his instinct for crooked paths, which lead to a tyranny
\par over the healthy--where can it not be found, this will to power of
\par the very weakest? The sick woman especially: no one surpasses her
\par in refinements for ruling, oppressing, tyrannising. The sick woman,
\par moreover, spares nothing living, nothing dead; she grubs up again the
\par most buried things (the Bogos say, "Woman is a hyena"). Look into
\par the background of every family, of every body, of every community:
\par everywhere the fight of the sick against the healthy--a silent fight
\par for the most part with minute poisoned powders, with pin-pricks, with
\par spiteful grimaces of patience, but also at times with that diseased
\par pharisaism of _pure_ pantomime, which plays for choice the r\'f4le of
\par "righteous indignation." Right into the hallowed chambers of knowledge
\par can it make itself heard, can this hoarse yelping of sick hounds, this
\par rabid lying and frenzy of such "noble" Pharisees (I remind readers, who
\par have ears, once more of that Berlin apostle of revenge, Eugen D\'fchring,
\par who makes the most disreputable and revolting use in all present-day
\par Germany of moral refuse; D\'fchring, the paramount moral blusterer that
\par there is to-day, even among his own kidney, the Anti-Semites). They
\par are all men of resentment, are these physiological distortions and
\par worm-riddled objects, a whole quivering kingdom of burrowing revenge,
\par indefatigable and insatiable in its outbursts against the happy, and
\par equally so in disguises for revenge, in pretexts for revenge: when
\par will they really reach their final, fondest, most sublime triumph of
\par revenge? At that time, doubtless, when they succeed in pushing their
\par own misery, in fact, all misery, _into the consciousness_ of the happy;
\par so that the latter begin one day to be ashamed of their happiness,
\par and perchance say to themselves when they meet, "It is a shame to be
\par happy! _there is too much misery!_" ... But there could not possibly
\par be a greater and more fatal misunderstanding than that of the happy,
\par the fit, the strong in body and soul, beginning in this way to doubt
\par their right to happiness. Away with this "perverse world"! Away with
\par this shameful soddenness of sentiment! Preventing the sick making the
\par healthy sick--for that is what such a soddenness comes to--this ought
\par to be our supreme object in the world--but for this it is above all
\par essential that the healthy should remain _separated_ from the sick,
\par that they should even guard themselves from the look of the sick, that
\par they should not even associate with the sick. Or may it, perchance,
\par be their mission to be nurses or doctors? But they could not mistake
\par and disown their mission more grossly--the higher must not degrade
\par itself to be the tool of the lower, the pathos of distance must to all
\par eternity keep their missions also separate. The right of the happy to
\par existence, the right of bells with a full tone over the discordant
\par cracked bells, is verily a thousand times greater: they alone are the
\par _sureties_ of the future, they alone are _bound_ to man's future. What
\par they can, what they must do, that can the sick never do, should never
\par do! but if _they are to_ be enabled to do what _only_ they must do,
\par how can they possibly be free to play the doctor, the comforter, the
\par "Saviour" of the sick?... And therefore good air! good air! and away,
\par at any rate, from the neighbourhood of all the madhouses and hospitals
\par of civilisation! And therefore good company, _our own_ company, or
\par solitude, if it must be so! but away, at any rate, from the evil fumes
\par of internal corruption and the secret worm-eaten state of the sick!
\par that, forsooth, my friends, we may defend ourselves, at any rate for
\par still a time, against the two worst plagues that could have been
\par reserved for us--against the _great nausea with man_! against the_
\par great pity for man_!
\par 
\par 
\par 15.
\par 
\par If you have understood in all their depths--and I demand that you
\par should _grasp them profoundly_ and understand them profoundly--the
\par reasons for the impossibility of its being the business of the healthy
\par to nurse the sick, to make the sick healthy, it follows that you have
\par grasped this further necessity--the necessity of doctors and nurses
\par _who themselves are sick_. And now we have and hold with both our hands
\par the essence of the ascetic priest. The ascetic priest must be accepted
\par by us as the predestined saviour, herdsman, and champion of the sick
\par herd: thereby do we first understand his awful historic mission. The
\par _lordship over sufferers_ is his kingdom, to that points his instinct,
\par in that he finds his own special art, his master-skill, his kind of
\par happiness. He must himself be sick, he must be kith and kin to the
\par sick and the abortions so as to understand them, so as to arrive at an
\par understanding with them; but he must also be strong, even more master
\par of himself than of others, impregnable, forsooth, in his will for
\par power, so as to acquire the trust and the awe of the weak, so that he
\par can be their hold, bulwark, prop, compulsion, overseer, tyrant, god.
\par He has to protect them, protect his herds--_against_ whom? Against
\par the healthy, doubtless also against the envy towards the healthy. He
\par must be the natural adversary and _scorner_ of every rough, stormy,
\par reinless, hard, violently-predatory health and power. The priest is
\par the first form of the more delicate animal that scorns more easily
\par than it hates. He will not be spared the waging of war with the beasts
\par of prey, a war of guile (of "spirit") rather than of force, as is
\par self-evident--he will in certain cases find it necessary to conjure up
\par out of himself, or at any rate to represent practically a new type of
\par the beast of prey--a new animal monstrosity in which the polar bear,
\par the supple, cold, crouching panther, and, not least important, the fox,
\par are joined together in a trinity as fascinating as it is fearsome.
\par If necessity exacts it, then will he come on the scene with bearish
\par seriousness, venerable, wise, cold, full of treacherous superiority, as
\par the herald and mouthpiece of mysterious powers, sometimes going among
\par even the other kind of beasts of prey, determined as he is to sow on
\par their soil, wherever he can, suffering, discord, self-contradiction,
\par and only too sure of his art, always to be lord of _sufferers_ at all
\par times. He brings with him, doubtless, salve and balsam; but before he
\par can play the physician he must first wound; so, while he soothes the
\par pain which the wound makes, _he at the same time poisons the wound_.
\par Well versed is he in this above all things, is this wizard and wild
\par beast tamer, in whose vicinity everything healthy must needs become
\par ill, and everything ill must needs become tame. He protects, in sooth,
\par his sick herd well enough, does this strange herdsman; he protects
\par them also against themselves, against the sparks (even in the centre
\par of the herd) of wickedness, knavery, malice, and all the other ills
\par that the plaguey and the sick are heir to; he fights with cunning,
\par hardness, and stealth against anarchy and against the ever imminent
\par break-up inside the herd, where _resentment_, that most dangerous
\par blasting-stuff and explosive, ever accumulates and accumulates. Getting
\par rid of this blasting-stuff in such a way that it does not blow up the
\par herd and the herdsman, that is his real feat, his supreme utility;
\par if you wish to comprise in the shortest formula the value of the
\par priestly life, it would be correct to say the priest is the _diverter
\par of the course of resentment_. Every sufferer, in fact, searches
\par instinctively for a cause of his suffering; to put it more exactly,
\par a doer,--to put it still more precisely, a sentient _responsible_
\par doer,--in brief, something living, on which, either actually or in
\par _effigie_, he can on any pretext vent his emotions. For the venting
\par of emotions is the sufferer's greatest attempt at alleviation, that
\par is to say, _stupefaction_, his mechanically desired narcotic against
\par pain of any kind. It is in this phenomenon alone that is found,
\par according to my judgment, the real physiological cause of resentment,
\par revenge, and their family is to be found--that is, in a demand for the
\par _deadening of pain through emotion_: this cause is generally, but in
\par my view very erroneously, looked for in the defensive parry of a bare
\par protective principle of reaction, of a "reflex movement" in the case
\par of any sudden hurt and danger, after the manner that a decapitated
\par frog still moves in order to get away from a corrosive acid. But the
\par difference is fundamental. In one case the object is to prevent being
\par hurt any more; in the other case the object is to _deaden_ a racking,
\par insidious, nearly unbearable pain by a more violent emotion of any
\par kind whatsoever, and at any rate for the time being to drive it out of
\par the consciousness--for this purpose an emotion is needed, as wild an
\par emotion as possible, and to excite that emotion some excuse or other
\par is needed. "It must be somebody's fault that I feel bad"--this kind of
\par reasoning is peculiar to all invalids, and is but the more pronounced,
\par the more ignorant they remain of the real cause of their feeling bad,
\par the physiological cause (the cause may lie in a disease of the _nervus
\par sympathicus_, or in an excessive secretion of bile, or in a want of
\par sulphate and phosphate of potash in the blood, or in pressure in the
\par bowels which stops the circulation of the blood, or in degeneration of
\par the ovaries, and so forth). Ail sufferers have an awful resourcefulness
\par and ingenuity in finding excuses for painful emotions; they even
\par enjoy their jealousy, their broodings over base actions and apparent
\par injuries, they burrow through the intestines of their past and present
\par in their search for obscure mysteries, wherein they will be at liberty
\par to wallow in a torturing suspicion and get drunk on the venom of their
\par own malice--they tear open the oldest wounds, they make themselves
\par bleed from the scars which have long been healed, they make evil-doers
\par out of friends, wife, child, and everything which is nearest to them.
\par "I suffer: it must be somebody's fault"--so thinks every sick sheep.
\par But his herdsman, the ascetic priest, says to him, "Quite so, my sheep,
\par it must be the fault of some one; but thou thyself art that some one,
\par it is all the fault of thyself alone--_it is the fault of thyself alone
\par against thyself_": that is bold enough, false enough, but one thing is
\par at least attained; thereby, as I have said, the course of resentment
\par is--_diverted_.
\par 
\par 
\par 16.
\par 
\par You can see now what the remedial instinct of life has at least _tried_
\par to effect, according to my conception, through the ascetic priest,
\par and the purpose for which he had to employ a temporary tyranny of
\par such paradoxical and anomalous ideas as "guilt," "sin," "sinfulness,"
\par "corruption," "damnation." What was done was to make the sick
\par _harmless_ up to a certain point, to destroy the incurable by means of
\par themselves, to turn the milder cases severely on to themselves, to give
\par their resentment a backward direction ("man needs but one thing"), and
\par to _exploit_ similarly the bad instincts of all sufferers with a view
\par to self-discipline, self-surveillance, self-mastery. It is obvious that
\par there can be no question at all in the case of a "medication" of this
\par kind, a mere emotional medication, of any real _healing_ of the sick in
\par the physiological sense; it cannot even for a moment be asserted that
\par in this connection the instinct of life has taken healing as its goal
\par and purpose. On the one hand, a kind of congestion and organisation of
\par the sick (the word "Church" is the most popular name for it): on the
\par other, a kind of provisional safeguarding of the comparatively healthy,
\par the more perfect specimens, the cleavage of a _rift_ between healthy
\par and sick--for a long time that was all! and it was much! it was very
\par much!
\par 
\par I am proceeding, as you see, in this essay, from an hypothesis which,
\par as far as such readers as I want are concerned, does not require to be
\par proved; the hypothesis that "sinfulness" in man is not an actual fact,
\par but rather merely the interpretation of a fact, of a physiological
\par discomfort,--a discomfort seen through a moral religious perspective
\par which is no longer binding upon us. The fact, therefore, that any one
\par feels "guilty," "sinful," is certainly not yet any proof that he is
\par right in feeling so, any more than any one is healthy simply because
\par he feels healthy. Remember the celebrated witch-ordeals: in those days
\par the most acute and humane judges had no doubt but that in these cases
\par they were confronted with guilt,--the "witches"_ themselves had no
\par doubt on the point_,--and yet the guilt was lacking. Let me elaborate
\par this hypothesis: I do not for a minute accept the very "pain in the
\par soul" as a real fact, but only as an explanation (a casual explanation)
\par of facts that could not hitherto be precisely formulated; I regard
\par it therefore as something as yet absolutely in the air and devoid of
\par scientific cogency--just a nice fat word in the place of a lean note
\par of interrogation. When any one fails to get rid of his "pain in the
\par soul," the cause is, speaking crudely, to be found _not_ in his "soul"
\par but more probably in his stomach (speaking crudely, I repeat, but by
\par no means wishing thereby that you should listen to me or understand
\par me in a crude spirit). A strong and well-constituted man digests his
\par experiences (deeds and misdeeds all included) just as he digests his
\par meats, even when he has some tough morsels to swallow. If he fails to
\par "relieve himself" of an experience, this kind of indigestion is quite
\par as much physiological as the other indigestion--and indeed, in more
\par ways than one, simply one of the results of the other. You can adopt
\par such a theory, and yet _entre nous_ be nevertheless the strongest
\par opponent of all materialism.
\par 
\par 
\par 17.
\par 
\par But is he really a _physician_, this ascetic priest? We already
\par understand why we are scarcely allowed to call him a physician, however
\par much he likes to feel a "saviour" and let himself be worshipped as a
\par saviour.[3] It is only the actual suffering, the discomfort of the
\par sufferer, which he combats, _not_ its cause, not the actual state of
\par sickness--this needs must constitute our most radical objection to
\par priestly medication. But just once put yourself into that point of
\par view, of which the priests have a monopoly, you will find it hard to
\par exhaust your amazement, at what from that standpoint he has completely
\par seen, sought, and found. The _mitigation_ of suffering, every kind of
\par "consoling"--all this manifests itself as his very genius: with what
\par ingenuity has he interpreted his mission of consoler, with what aplomb
\par and audacity has he chosen weapons necessary for the part. Christianity
\par in particular should be dubbed a great treasure-chamber of ingenious
\par consolations,--such a store of refreshing, soothing, deadening drugs
\par has it accumulated within itself; so many of the most dangerous and
\par daring expedients has it hazarded; with such subtlety, refinement,
\par Oriental refinement, has it divined what emotional stimulants can
\par conquer, at any rate for a time, the deep depression, the leaden
\par fatigue, the black melancholy of physiological cripples--for, speaking
\par generally, all religions are mainly concerned with fighting a certain
\par fatigue and heaviness that has infected everything. You can regard it
\par as _prima facie_ probable that in certain places in the world there
\par was almost bound to prevail from time to time among large masses of
\par the population a _sense of physiological depression_, which, however,
\par owing to their lack of physiological knowledge, did not appear to their
\par consciousness as such, so that consequently its "cause" and its _cure_
\par can only be sought and essayed in the science of moral psychology
\par (this, in fact, is my most general formula for what is generally called
\par a "_religion_"). Such a feeling of depression can have the most diverse
\par origins; it may be the result of the crossing of too heterogeneous
\par races (or of classes--genealogical and racial differences are also
\par brought out in the classes: the European "Weltschmerz," the "Pessimism"
\par of the nineteenth century, is really the result of an absurd and sudden
\par class-mixture); it may be brought about by a mistaken emigration--a
\par race falling into a climate for which its power of adaptation is
\par insufficient (the case of the Indians in India); it may be the effect
\par of old age and fatigue (the Parisian pessimism from 1850 onwards); it
\par may be a wrong diet (the alcoholism of the Middle Ages, the nonsense
\par of vegetarianism--which, however, have in their favour the authority
\par of Sir Christopher in Shakespeare); it may be blood-deterioration,
\par malaria, syphilis, and the like (German depression after the Thirty
\par Years' War, which infected half Germany with evil diseases, and
\par thereby paved the way for German servility, for German pusillanimity).
\par In such a case there is invariably recourse to a _war_ on a grand scale
\par with the feeling of depression; let us inform ourselves briefly on its
\par most important practices and phases (I leave on one side, as stands to
\par reason, the actual _philosophic_ war against the feeling of depression
\par which is usually simultaneous--it is interesting enough, but too
\par absurd, too practically negligible, too full of cobwebs, too much of a
\par hole-and-corner affair, especially when pain is proved to be a mistake,
\par on the _na\'eff_ hypothesis that pain must needs _vanish_ when the mistake
\par underlying it is recognised--but behold! it does anything but vanish
\par ...). That dominant depression is _primarily fought_ by weapons which
\par reduce the consciousness of life itself to the lowest degree. Wherever
\par possible, no more wishes, no more wants; shun everything which produces
\par emotion, which produces "blood" (eating no salt, the fakir hygiene);
\par no love; no hate; equanimity; no revenge; no getting rich; no work;
\par begging; as far as possible, no woman, or as little woman as possible;
\par as far as the intellect is concerned, Pascal's principle, "_il faut
\par s'ab\'eatir._" To put the result in ethical and psychological language,
\par "self-annihilation," "sanctification"; to put it in physiological
\par language, "hypnotism"--the attempt to find some approximate human
\par equivalent for what _hibernation_ is for certain animals, for what
\par _\'e6stivation_ is for many tropical plants, a minimum of assimilation
\par and metabolism in which life just manages to subsist without really
\par coming into the consciousness. An amazing amount of human energy
\par has been devoted to this object--perhaps uselessly? There cannot be
\par the slightest doubt but that such _sportsmen_ of "saintliness," in
\par whom at times nearly every nation has abounded, have really found a
\par genuine relief from that which they have combated with such a rigorous
\par _training_--in countless cases they really escaped by the help of their
\par system of hypnotism _away_ from deep physiological depression; their
\par method is consequently counted among the most universal ethnological
\par facts. Similarly it is improper to consider such a plan for starving
\par the physical element and the desires, as in itself a symptom of
\par insanity (as a clumsy species of roast-beef-eating "freethinkers" and
\par Sir Christophers are fain to do); all the more certain is it that their
\par method can and does pave the way to all kinds of mental disturbances,
\par for instance, "inner lights" (as far as the case of the Hesychasts of
\par Mount Athos), auditory and visual hallucinations, voluptuous ecstasies
\par and effervescences of sensualism (the history of St. Theresa). The
\par explanation of such events given by the victims is always the acme of
\par fanatical falsehood; this is self-evident. Note well, however, the tone
\par of implicit gratitude that rings in the very _will_ for an explanation
\par of such a character. The supreme state, salvation itself, that final
\par goal of universal hypnosis and peace, is always regarded by them as
\par the mystery of mysteries, which even the most supreme symbols are
\par inadequate to express; it is regarded as an entry and homecoming to the
\par essence of things, as a liberation from all illusions, as "knowledge,"
\par as "truth," as "being" as an escape from every end, every wish, every
\par action, as something even beyond Good and Evil.
\par 
\par "Good and Evil," quoth the Buddhists, "both are fetters. The perfect
\par man is master of them both."
\par 
\par "The done and the undone," quoth the disciple of the Vedanta, "do
\par him no hurt; the good and the evil he shakes from off him, sage that
\par he is; his kingdom suffers no more from any act; good and evil, he
\par goes beyond them both."--An absolutely Indian conception, as much
\par Brahmanist as Buddhist. Neither in the Indian nor in the Christian
\par doctrine is this "Redemption" regarded as attainable by means of
\par virtue and moral improvement, however high they may place the value of
\par the hypnotic efficiency of virtue: keep clear on this point--indeed
\par it simply corresponds with the facts. The fact that they remained
\par _true_ on this point is perhaps to be regarded as the best specimen
\par of realism in the three great religions, absolutely soaked as they
\par are with morality, with this one exception. "For those who know,
\par there is no duty." "Redemption is not attained by the acquisition of
\par virtues; for redemption consists in being one with Brahman, who is
\par incapable of acquiring any perfection; and equally little does it
\par consist in the _giving up of faults_, for the Brahman, unity with whom
\par is what constitutes redemption, is eternally pure" (these passages
\par are from the Commentaries of the Cankara, quoted from the first real
\par European _expert_ of the Indian philosophy, my friend Paul Deussen).
\par We wish, therefore, to pay honour to the idea of "redemption" in
\par the great religions, but it is somewhat hard to remain serious in
\par view of the appreciation meted out to the _deep sleep_ by these
\par exhausted pessimists who are too tired even to dream--to the deep
\par sleep considered, that is, as already a fusing into Brahman, as the
\par attainment of the _unio mystica_ with God. "When he has completely gone
\par to sleep," says on this point the oldest and most venerable "script,"
\par "and come to perfect rest, so that he sees no more any vision, then,
\par oh dear one, is he united with Being, he has entered into his own
\par self--encircled by the Self with its absolute knowledge, he has no
\par more any consciousness of that which is without or of that which is
\par within. Day and night cross not these bridges, nor age, nor death,
\par nor suffering, nor good deeds, nor evil deeds." "In deep sleep," say
\par similarly the believers in this deepest of the three great religions,
\par "does the soul lift itself from out this body of ours, enters the
\par supreme light and stands out therein in its true shape: therein is it
\par the supreme spirit itself, which travels about, while it jests and
\par plays and enjoys itself, whether with women, or chariots, or friends;
\par there do its thoughts turn no more back to this appanage of a body,
\par to which the 'prana' (the vital breath) is harnessed like a beast of
\par burden to the cart." None the less we will take care to realise (as
\par we did when discussing "redemption") that in spite of all its pomps
\par of Oriental extravagance this simply expresses the same criticism on
\par life as did the clear, cold, Greekly cold, but yet suffering Epicurus.
\par The hypnotic sensation of nothingness, the peace of deepest sleep,
\par an\'e6sthesia in short\endash \endash that is what passes with the sufferers and the
\par absolutely depressed for, forsooth, their supreme good, their value
\par of values; that is what <b>must</b> be treasured by them as something
\par positive, be felt by them as the essence of _the_ Positive (according
\par to the same logic of the feelings, nothingness is in all pessimistic
\par religions called God).
\par 
\par 
\par 18.
\par 
\par Such a hypnotic deadening of sensibility and susceptibility to pain,
\par which presupposes somewhat rare powers, especially courage, contempt
\par of opinion, intellectual stoicism, is less frequent than another
\par and certainly easier _training_ which is tried against states of
\par depression. I mean _mechanical activity_. It is indisputable that a
\par suffering existence can be thereby considerably alleviated. This fact
\par is called to-day by the somewhat ignoble title of the "Blessing of
\par work." The alleviation consists in the attention of the sufferer being
\par absolutely diverted from suffering, in the incessant monopoly of the
\par consciousness by action, so that consequently there is little room left
\par for suffering\endash \endash for _narrow_ is it, this chamber of human consciousness!
\par Mechanical activity and its corollaries, such as absolute regularity,
\par punctilious unreasoning obedience, the chronic routine of life, the
\par complete occupation of time, a certain liberty to be impersonal, nay, a
\par training in "impersonality," self-forgetfulness, "_incuria sui_"\endash \endash with
\par what thoroughness and expert subtlety have all these methods been
\par exploited by the ascetic priest in his war with pain!
\par 
\par When he has to tackle sufferers of the lower orders, slaves, or
\par prisoners (or women, who for the most part are a compound of
\par labour-slave and prisoner), all he has to do is to juggle a little
\par with the names, and to rechristen, so as to make them see henceforth
\par a benefit, a comparative happiness, in objects which they hated--the
\par slave's discontent with his lot was at any rate not invented by the
\par priests. An even more popular means of fighting depression is the
\par ordaining of a _little joy_, which is easily accessible and can be made
\par into a rule; this medication is frequently used in conjunction with
\par the former ones. The most frequent form in which joy is prescribed
\par as a cure is the joy in _producing_ joy (such as doing good, giving
\par presents, alleviating, helping, exhorting, comforting, praising,
\par treating with distinction); together with the prescription of "love
\par your neighbour." The ascetic priest prescribes, though in the most
\par cautious doses, what is practically a stimulation of the strongest
\par and most life-assertive impulse--the Will for Power. The happiness
\par involved in the "smallest superiority" which is the concomitant of all
\par benefiting, helping, extolling, making one's self useful, is the most
\par ample consolation, of which, if they are well-advised, physiological
\par distortions avail themselves: in other cases they hurt each other, and
\par naturally in obedience to the same radical instinct. An investigation
\par of the origin of Christianity in the Roman world shows that
\par co-operative unions for poverty, sickness, and burial sprang up in the
\par lowest stratum of contemporary society, amid which the chief antidote
\par against depression, the little joy experienced in mutual benefits,
\par was deliberately fostered. Perchance this was then a novelty, a real
\par discovery? This conjuring up of the will for co-operation, for family
\par organisation, for communal life, for "_C\'9cnacula_" necessarily brought
\par the Will for Power, which had been already infinitesimally stimulated,
\par to a new and much fuller manifestation. The herd organisation is a
\par genuine advance and triumph in the fight with depression. With the
\par growth of the community there matures even to individuals a new
\par interest, which often enough takes him out of the more personal
\par element in his discontent, his aversion to himself, the "_despectus
\par sui_" of Geulincx. All sick and diseased people strive instinctively
\par after a herd-organisation, out of a desire to shake off their sense of
\par oppressive discomfort and weakness; the ascetic priest divines this
\par instinct and promotes it; wherever a herd exists it is the instinct
\par of weakness which has wished for the herd, and the cleverness of the
\par priests which has organised it, for, mark this: by an equally natural
\par necessity the strong strive as much for _isolation_ as the weak for
\par _union_: when the former bind themselves it is only with a view to an
\par aggressive joint action and joint satisfaction of their Will for Power,
\par much against the wishes of their individual consciences; the latter,
\par on the contrary, range themselves together with positive _delight_ in
\par such a muster--their instincts are as much gratified thereby as the
\par instincts of the "born master" (that is, the solitary beast-of-prey
\par species of man) are disturbed and wounded to the quick by organisation.
\par There is always lurking beneath every oligarchy--such is the
\par universal lesson of history--the desire for tyranny. Every oligarchy
\par is continually quivering with the tension of the effort required by
\par each individual to keep mastering this desire. (Such, _e.g._, was
\par the Greek; Plato shows it in a hundred places, Plato, who knew his
\par contemporaries--and _himself_.)
\par 
\par 
\par 19.
\par 
\par The methods employed by the ascetic priest, which we have already
\par learnt to know--stifling of all vitality, mechanical energy, the
\par little joy, and especially the method of "love your neighbour"
\par herd-organisation, the awaking of the communal consciousness of power,
\par to such a pitch that the individual's disgust with himself becomes
\par eclipsed by his delight in the thriving of the community--these are,
\par according to modern standards, the "innocent" methods employed in
\par the fight with depression; let us turn now to the more interesting
\par topic of the "guilty" methods. The guilty methods spell one thing:
\par to produce _emotional excess_--which is used as the most efficacious
\par an\'e6sthetic against their depressing state of protracted pain; this
\par is why priestly ingenuity has proved quite inexhaustible in thinking
\par out this one question: "_By what means_ can you produce an emotional
\par excess?" This sounds harsh: it is manifest that it would sound nicer
\par and would grate on one's ears less, if I were to say, forsooth: "The
\par ascetic priest made use at all times of the enthusiasm contained in all
\par strong emotions." But what is the good of still soothing the delicate
\par ears of our modern effeminates? What is the good _on our side_ of
\par budging one single inch before their verbal Pecksniffianism. For us
\par psychologists to do that would be at once _practical Pecksniffianism_,
\par apart from the fact of its nauseating us. The _good taste_ (others
\par might say, the righteousness) of a psychologist nowadays consists, if
\par at all, in combating the shamefully moralised language with which all
\par modern judgments on men and things are smeared. For, do not deceive
\par yourself: what constitutes the chief characteristic of modern souls and
\par of modern books is not the lying, but the _innocence_ which is part
\par and parcel of their intellectual dishonesty. The inevitable running up
\par against this "innocence" everywhere constitutes the most distasteful
\par feature of the somewhat dangerous business which a modern psychologist
\par has to undertake: it is a part of our great danger--it is a road which
\par perhaps leads us straight to the great nausea--I know quite well the
\par purpose which all modern books will and can serve (granted that they
\par last, which I am not afraid of, and granted equally that there is to
\par be at some future day a generation with a more rigid, more severe,
\par and _healthier_ taste)--the _function_ which all modernity generally
\par will serve with posterity: that of an emetic,--and this by reason of
\par its moral sugariness and falsity, its ingrained feminism, which it is
\par pleased to call "Idealism," and at any rate believes to be idealism.
\par Our cultured men of to-day, our "good" men, do not lie--that is true;
\par but it does _not_ redound to their honour! The real lie, the genuine,
\par determined, "honest" lie (on whose value you can listen to Plato) would
\par prove too tough and strong an article for them by a long way; it would
\par be asking them to do what people have been forbidden to ask them to do,
\par to open their eyes to their own selves, and to learn to distinguish
\par between "true" and "false" in their own selves. The dishonest lie alone
\par suits them: everything which feels a good man is perfectly incapable of
\par any other attitude to anything than that of a dishonourable liar, an
\par absolute liar, but none the less an innocent liar, a blue-eyed liar, a
\par virtuous liar. These "good men," they are all now tainted with morality
\par through and through, and as far as honour is concerned they are
\par disgraced and corrupted for all eternity. Which of them _could stand_ a
\par further truth "about man"? or, put more tangibly, which of them could
\par put up with a true biography? One or two instances: Lord Byron composed
\par a most personal autobiography, but Thomas Moore was "too good" for it;
\par he burnt his friend's papers. Dr. Gwinner, Schopenhauer's executor, is
\par said to have done the same; for Schopenhauer as well wrote much about
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af64 \ltrch\fcs0 \f64 himself, and perhaps also against himself: (\'e5}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af2 \ltrch\fcs0 \f2 \u7984\'3f}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af64 \ltrch\fcs0 \f64 \'f2 }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af2 \ltrch\fcs0 \f2 \u7953\'3f}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af64 \ltrch\fcs0 \f64 
\'e1\'ed\'f4\'fc\'ed). The virtuous
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af2 \ltrch\fcs0 \f2 American Thayer, Beethoven's biographer, suddenly stopped his work: he
\par had come to a certain point in that honourable and simple life, and
\par could stand it no longer. Moral: What sensible man nowadays writes one
\par honest word about himself? He must already belong to the Order of Holy
\par Foolhardiness. We are promised an autobiography of Richard Wagner; who
\par doubts but that it would be a _clever_ autobiography? Think, forsooth,
\par of the grotesque horror which the Catholic priest Janssen aroused in
\par Germany with his inconceivably square and harmless pictures of the
\par German Reformation; what wouldn't people do if some real psychologist
\par were to tell us about a genuine Luther, tell us, not with the moralist
\par simplicity of a country priest or the sweet and cautious modesty of a
\par Protestant historian, but say with the fearlessness of a Taine, that
\par springs from force of character and not from a prudent toleration of
\par force. (The Germans, by the bye, have already produced the classic
\par specimen of this toleration--they may well be allowed to reckon him as
\par one of their own, in Leopold Ranke, that born classical advocate of
\par every _causa fortior_, that cleverest of all the clever opportunists.)
\par 
\par 
\par 20.
\par 
\par But you will soon understand me.--Putting it shortly, there is reason
\par enough, is there not, for us psychologists nowadays never getting from
\par a certain mistrust of out _own selves_? Probably even we ourselves are
\par still "too good" for our work, probably, whatever contempt we feel
\par for this popular craze for morality, we ourselves are perhaps none
\par the less its victims, prey, and slaves; probably it infects even us.
\par Of what was that diplomat warning us, when he said to his colleagues:
\par "Let us especially mistrust our first impulses, gentlemen! _they are
\par almost always good_"? So should nowadays every psychologist talk to
\par his colleagues. And thus we get back to our problem, which in point
\par of fact does require from us a certain severity, a certain mistrust
\par especially against "first impulses." The ascetic ideal in the service
\par of projected emotional excess:--he who remembers the previous essay
\par will already partially anticipate the essential meaning compressed
\par into these above ten words. The thorough unswitching of the human
\par soul, the plunging of it into terror, frost, ardour, rapture, so as
\par to free it, as through some lightning shock, from all the smallness
\par and pettiness of unhappiness, depression, and discomfort: what ways
\par lead to _this_ goal? And which of these ways does so most safely?...
\par At bottom all great emotions have this power, provided that they find
\par a sudden outlet--emotions such as rage, fear, lust, revenge, hope,
\par triumph, despair, cruelty; and, in sooth, the ascetic priest has had
\par no scruples in taking into his service the whole pack of hounds that
\par rage in the human kennel, unleashing now these and now those, with the
\par same constant object of waking man out of his protracted melancholy,
\par of chasing away, at any rate for a time, his dull pain, his shrinking
\par misery, but always under the sanction of a religious interpretation
\par and justification. This emotional excess has subsequently to be _paid
\par for_, this is self-evident--it makes the ill more ill--and therefore
\par this kind of remedy for pain is according to modern standards a
\par "guilty" kind.
\par 
\par The dictates of fairness, however, require that we should all the
\par more emphasise the fact that this remedy is applied with _a good
\par conscience_, that the ascetic priest has prescribed it in the most
\par implicit belief in its utility and indispensability;--often enough
\par almost collapsing in the presence of the pain which he created;--that
\par we should similarly emphasise the fact that the violent physiological
\par revenges of such excesses, even perhaps the mental disturbances, are
\par not absolutely inconsistent with the general tenor of this kind of
\par remedy; this remedy, which, as we have shown previously, is _not_ for
\par the purpose of healing diseases, but of fighting the unhappiness of
\par that depression, the alleviation and deadening of which was its object.
\par The object was consequently achieved. The keynote by which the ascetic
\par priest was enabled to get every kind of agonising and ecstatic music
\par to play on the fibres of the human soul--was, as every one knows, the
\par exploitation of the feeling of "_guilt_." I have already indicated in
\par the previous essay the origin of this feeling--as a piece of animal
\par psychology and nothing else: we were thus confronted with the
\par feeling of "guilt," in its crude state, as it were. It was first in
\par the hands of the priest, real artist that he was in the feeling of
\par guilt, that it took shape--oh, what a shape! "Sin"--for that is the
\par name of the new priestly version of the animal "bad-conscience" (the
\par inverted cruelty)--has up to the present been the greatest event in the
\par history of the diseased soul: in "sin" we find the most perilous and
\par fatal masterpiece of religious interpretation. Imagine man, suffering
\par from himself, some way or other but at any rate physiologically,
\par perhaps like an animal shut up in a cage, not clear as to the why and
\par the wherefore! imagine him in his desire for reasons--reasons bring
\par relief--in his desire again for remedies, narcotics at last, consulting
\par one, who knows even the occult--and see, lo and behold, he gets a hint
\par from his wizard, the ascetic priest, his _first_ hint on the "cause" of
\par his trouble: he must search for it in _himself_, in his guiltiness, in
\par a piece of the past, he must understand his very suffering as a _state
\par of punishment_. He has heard, he has understood, has the unfortunate:
\par he is now in the plight of a hen round which a line has been drawn. He
\par never gets out of the circle of lines. The sick man has been turned
\par into "the sinner"--and now for a few thousand years we never get away
\par from the sight of this new invalid, of "a sinner"--shall we ever get
\par away from it?--wherever we just look, everywhere the hypnotic gaze of
\par the sinner always moving in one direction (in the direction of guilt,
\par the _only_ cause of suffering); everywhere the evil conscience, this
\par "_greuliche thier_,"[4] to use Luther's language; everywhere rumination
\par over the past, a distorted view of action, the gaze of the "green-eyed
\par monster" turned on all action; everywhere the wilful misunderstanding
\par of suffering, its transvaluation into feelings of guilt, fear of
\par retribution; everywhere the scourge, the hairy shirt, the starving
\par body, contrition; everywhere the sinner breaking himself on the ghastly
\par wheel of a restless and morbidly eager conscience; everywhere mute
\par pain, extreme fear, the agony of a tortured heart, the spasms of an
\par unknown happiness, the shriek for "redemption." In point of fact,
\par thanks to this system of procedure, the old depression, dullness,
\par and fatigue were absolutely conquered, life itself became _very_
\par interesting again, awake, eternally awake, sleepless, glowing, burnt
\par away, exhausted and yet not tired--such was the figure cut by man,
\par "the sinner," who was initiated into these mysteries. This grand old
\par wizard of an ascetic priest fighting with depression--he had clearly
\par triumphed, _his_ kingdom had come: men no longer grumbled at pain, men
\par _panted_ after pain: "_More pain!_ More pain!" So for centuries on end
\par shrieked the demand of his acolytes and initiates. Every emotional
\par excess which hurt; everything which broke, overthrew, crushed,
\par transported, ravished; the mystery of torture-chambers, the ingenuity
\par of hell itself--all this was now discovered, divined, exploited, all
\par this was at the service of the wizard, all this served to promote the
\par triumph of his ideal, the ascetic ideal. "_My kingdom is not of this
\par world_," quoth he, both at the beginning and at the end: had he still
\par the right to talk like that?--Goethe has maintained that there are only
\par thirty-six tragic situations: we would infer from that, did we not know
\par otherwise, that Goethe was no ascetic priest. He--knows more.
\par 
\par 
\par 21.
\par 
\par So far as all _this_ kind of priestly medicine-mongering, the "guilty"
\par kind, is concerned, every word of criticism is superfluous. As for the
\par suggestion that emotional excess of the type, which in these cases
\par the ascetic priest is fain to order to his sick patients (under the
\par most sacred euphemism, as is obvious, and equally impregnated with
\par the sanctity of his purpose), has ever really been of use to any sick
\par man, who, forsooth, would feel inclined to maintain a proposition of
\par that character? At any rate, some understanding should be come to as
\par to the expression "be of use." If you only wish to express that such a
\par system of treatment has _reformed_ man, I do not gainsay it: I merely
\par add that "reformed" conveys to my mind as much as "tamed," "weakened,"
\par "discouraged," "refined," "daintified," "emasculated" (and thus it
\par means almost as much as injured). But when you have to deal principally
\par with sick, depressed, and oppressed creatures, such a system, even
\par granted that it makes the ill "better," under any circumstances also
\par makes them more _ill_: ask the mad-doctors the invariable result of a
\par methodical application of penance-torture, contrition, and salvation
\par ecstasies. Similarly ask history. In every body politic where the
\par ascetic priest has established this treatment of the sick, disease has
\par on every occasion spread with sinister speed throughout its length
\par and breadth. What was always the "result"? A shattered nervous system,
\par in addition to the existing malady, and this in the greatest as in the
\par smallest, in the individuals as in masses. We find, in consequence of
\par the penance and redemption-training, awful epileptic epidemics, the
\par greatest known to history, such as the St. Vitus and St. John dances
\par of the Middle Ages; we find, as another phase of its after-effect,
\par frightful mutilations and chronic depressions, by means of which the
\par temperament of a nation or a city (Geneva, Bale) is turned once for
\par all into its opposite;--this _training_, again, is responsible for
\par the witch-hysteria, a phenomenon analogous to somnambulism (eight
\par great epidemic outbursts of this only between 1564 and 1605);--we
\par find similarly in its train those delirious death-cravings of large
\par masses, whose awful "shriek," "_evviva la morte!_" was heard over the
\par whole of Europe, now interrupted by voluptuous variations and anon by
\par a rage for destruction, just as the same emotional sequence with the
\par same intermittencies and sudden changes is now universally observed
\par in every case where the ascetic doctrine of sin scores once more a
\par great success (religious neurosis _appears_ as a manifestation of the
\par devil, there is no doubt of it. What is it? _Qu\'e6ritur_). Speaking
\par generally, the ascetic ideal and its sublime-moral cult, this most
\par ingenious, reckless, and perilous systematisation of all methods of
\par emotional excess, is writ large in a dreadful and unforgettable fashion
\par on the whole history of man, and unfortunately not only on history.
\par I was scarcely able to put forward any other element which attacked
\par the health and race efficiency of Europeans with more destructive
\par power than did this ideal; it can be dubbed,without exaggeration,
\par _the real fatality_ in the history of the health of the European man.
\par At the most you can merely draw a comparison with the specifically
\par German influence: I mean the alcohol poisoning of Europe, which up
\par to the present has kept pace exactly with the political and racial
\par pre\endash dominance of the Germans (where they inoculated their blood,
\par there too did they inoculate their vice). Third in the series comes
\par syphilis--_magno sed proximo intervallo_.
\par 
\par 
\par 22.
\par 
\par The ascetic priest has, wherever he has obtained the mastery, corrupted
\par the health of the soul, he has consequently also corrupted _taste in
\par artibus et litteris_--he corrupts it still. "Consequently?" I hope I
\par shall be granted this "consequently "; at any rate, I am not going to
\par prove it first. One solitary indication, it concerns the arch-book of
\par Christian literature, their real model, their "book-in-itself." In the
\par very midst of the Gr\'e6co-Roman splendour, which was also a splendour
\par of books, face to face with an ancient world of writings which had
\par not yet fallen into decay and ruin, at a time when certain books were
\par still to be read, to possess which we would give nowadays half our
\par literature in exchange, at that time the simplicity and vanity of
\par Christian agitators (they are generally called Fathers of the Church)
\par dared to declare: "We too have our classical literature, we _do not
\par need that of the Greeks_"--and meanwhile they proudly pointed to their
\par books of legends, their letters of apostles, and their apologetic
\par tractlets, just in the same way that to-day the English "Salvation
\par Army" wages its fight against Shakespeare and other "heathens" with
\par an analogous literature. You already guess it, I do not like the "New
\par Testament"; it almost upsets me that I stand so isolated in my taste
\par so far as concerns this valued, this over-valued Scripture; the taste
\par of two thousand years is _against_ me; but what boots it! "Here I
\par stand! I cannot help myself"[5]--I have the courage of my bad taste.
\par The Old Testament--yes, that is something quite different, all honour
\par to the Old Testament! I find therein great men, an heroic landscape,
\par and one of the rarest phenomena in the world, the incomparable na\'efvet\'e9
\par _of the strong heart_; further still, I find a people. In the New, on
\par the contrary, just a hostel of petty sects, pure rococo of the soul,
\par twisting angles and fancy touches, nothing but conventicle air, not to
\par forget an occasional whiff of bucolic sweetness which appertains to the
\par epoch (_and_ the Roman province) and is less Jewish than Hellenistic.
\par Meekness and braggadocio cheek by jowl; an emotional garrulousness
\par that almost deafens; passionate hysteria, but no passion; painful
\par pantomime; here manifestly every one lacked good breeding. How dare any
\par one make so much fuss about their little failings as do these pious
\par little fellows! No one cares a straw about it--let alone God. Finally
\par they actually wish to have "the crown of eternal life," do all these
\par little provincials! In return for what, in sooth? For what end? It is
\par impossible to carry insolence any further. An immortal Peter! who could
\par stand _him_! They have an ambition which makes one laugh: the _thing_
\par dishes up cut and dried his most personal life, his melancholies, and
\par common-or-garden troubles, as though the Universe itself were under
\par an obligation to bother itself about them, for it never gets tired of
\par wrapping up God Himself in the petty misery in which its troubles are
\par involved. And how about the atrocious form of this chronic hobnobbing
\par with God? This Jewish, and not merely Jewish, slobbering and clawing
\par importunacy towards God!--There exist little despised "heathen nations"
\par in East Asia, from whom these first Christians could have learnt
\par something worth learning, a little tact in worshiping; these nations
\par do not allow themselves to say aloud the name of their God. This seems
\par to me delicate enough, it is certain that it is _too_ delicate, and
\par not only for primitive Christians; to take a contrast, just recollect
\par Luther, the most "eloquent" and insolent peasant whom Germany has had,
\par think of the Lutherian tone, in which he felt quite the most in his
\par element during his _t\'eate-\'e0-t\'eates_ with God. Luther's opposition to the
\par medi\'e6val saints of the Church (in particular, against "that devil's
\par hog, the Pope"), was, there is no doubt, at bottom the opposition of
\par a boor, who was offended at the _good etiquette_ of the Church, that
\par worship-etiquette of the sacerdotal code, which only admits to the
\par holy of holies the initiated and the silent, and shuts the door against
\par the boors. These definitely were not to be allowed a hearing in this
\par planet--but Luther the peasant simply wished it otherwise; as it was,
\par it was not German enough for him. He personally wished himself to talk
\par direct, to talk personally, to talk "straight from the shoulder" with
\par his God. Well, he's done it. The ascetic ideal, you will guess, was at
\par no time and in no place, a school of good taste, still less of good
\par manners--at the best it was a school for sacerdotal manners: that is,
\par it contains in itself something which was a deadly enemy to all good
\par manners. Lack of measure, opposition to measure, it is itself a "_non
\par plus ultra_."
\par 
\par 
\par 23.
\par 
\par The ascetic ideal has corrupted not only health and taste, there are
\par also third, fourth, fifth, and sixth things which it has corrupted--I
\par shall take care not to go through the catalogue (when should I get to
\par the end?). I have here to expose not what this ideal effected; but
\par rather only what it _means_, on what it is based, what lies lurking
\par behind it and under it, that of which it is the provisional expression,
\par an obscure expression bristling with queries and misunderstandings.
\par And with _this_ object only in view I presumed "not to spare" my
\par readers a glance at the awfulness of its results, a glance at its
\par fatal results; I did this to prepare them for the final and most
\par awful aspect presented to me by the question of the significance of
\par that ideal. What is the significance of the _power_ of that ideal,
\par the monstrousness of its power? Why is it given such an amount of
\par scope? Why is not a better resistance offered against it? The ascetic
\par ideal expresses one will: where is the opposition will, in which an
\par opposition ideal expresses itself? The ascetic ideal has an aim--
\par this goal is, putting it generally, that all the other interests of
\par human life should, measured by its standard, appear petty and narrow;
\par it explains epochs, nations, men, in reference to this one end; it
\par forbids any other interpretation, any other end; it repudiates, denies,
\par affirms, confirms, only in the sense of its own interpretation (and was
\par there ever a more thoroughly elaborated system of interpretation?);
\par it subjects itself to no power, rather does it believe in its own
\par precedence over every power--it believes that nothing powerful exists
\par in the world that has not first got to receive from "it" a meaning,
\par a right to exist, a value, as being an instrument in its work, a
\par way and means to its end, to one end. Where is the _counterpart_ of
\par this complete system of will, end, and interpretation? Why is the
\par counterpart lacking? Where is the other "one aim"? But I am told it
\par is not lacking, that not only has it fought a long and fortunate fight
\par with that ideal, but that further it has already won the mastery over
\par that ideal in all essentials: let our whole modern _science_ attest
\par this--that modern science, which, like the genuine reality-philosophy
\par which it is, manifestly believes in itself alone, manifestly has the
\par courage to be itself, the will to be itself, and has got on well
\par enough without God, another world, and negative virtues.
\par 
\par With all their noisy agitator-babble, however, they effect nothing with
\par me; these trumpeters of reality are bad musicians, their voices do
\par not come from the deeps with sufficient audibility, they are not the
\par mouthpiece for the abyss of scientific knowledge--for to-day scientific
\par knowledge is an abyss--the word "science," in such trumpeter-mouths,
\par is a prostitution, an abuse, an impertinence. The truth is just the
\par opposite from what is maintained in the ascetic theory. Science has
\par to-day absolutely no belief in itself, let alone in an ideal superior
\par to itself, and wherever science still consists of passion, love,
\par ardour, suffering, it is not the opposition to that ascetic ideal, but
\par rather the _incarnation of its latest and noblest form_. Does that ring
\par strange? There are enough brave and decent working people, even among
\par the learned men of to-day, who like their little corner, and who, just
\par because they are pleased so to do, become at times indecently loud with
\par their demand, that people to-day should be quite content, especially
\par in science--for in science there is so much useful work to do. I do
\par not deny it--there is nothing I should like less than to spoil the
\par delight of these honest workers in their handiwork; for I rejoice in
\par their work. But the fact of science requiring hard work, the fact of
\par its having contented workers, is absolutely no proof of science as a
\par whole having to-day one end, one will, one ideal, one passion for a
\par great faith; the contrary, as I have said, is the case. When science
\par is not the latest manifestation of the ascetic ideal--but these are
\par cases of such rarity, selectness, and exquisiteness, as to preclude the
\par general judgment being affected thereby--science is a _hiding-place_
\par for every kind of cowardice, disbelief, remorse, _despectio sui_, bad
\par conscience--it is the very _anxiety_ that springs from having no ideal,
\par the suffering from the _lack_ of a great love, the discontent with an
\par enforced moderation. Oh, what does all science not cover to-day? How
\par much, at any rate, does it not try to cover? The diligence of our best
\par scholars, their senseless industry, their burning the candle of their
\par brain at both ends--their very mastery in their handiwork--how often is
\par the real meaning of all that to prevent themselves continuing to see a
\par certain thing? Science as a self-an\'e6sthetic: _do you know that_? You
\par wound them--every one who consorts with scholars experiences this--you
\par wound them sometimes to the quick through just a harmless word; when
\par you think you are paying them a compliment you embitter them beyond all
\par bounds, simply because you didn't have the _finesse_ to infer the real
\par kind of customers you had to tackle, the _sufferer_ kind (who won't own
\par up even to themselves what they really are), the dazed and unconscious
\par kind who have only one fear--_coming to consciousness_.
\par 
\par 
\par 24.
\par 
\par And now look at the other side, at those rare cases, of which I spoke,
\par the most supreme idealists to be found nowadays among philosophers and
\par scholars. Have we, perchance, found in them the sought-for _opponents_
\par of the ascetic ideal, its _anti-idealists_? In fact, they _believe_
\par themselves to be such, these "unbelievers" (for they are all of them
\par that): it seems that this idea is their last remnant of faith, the idea
\par of being opponents of this ideal, so earnest are they on this subject,
\par so passionate in word and gesture;--but does it follow that what
\par they believe must necessarily be _true_? We "knowers" have grown by
\par degrees suspicious of all kinds of believers, our suspicion has step by
\par step habituated us to draw just the opposite conclusions to what people
\par have drawn before; that is to say, wherever the strength of a belief
\par is particularly prominent to draw the conclusion of the difficulty of
\par proving what is believed, the conclusion of its actual _improbability_.
\par We do not again deny that "faith produces salvation": _for that very
\par reason_ we do deny that faith _proves_ anything,--a strong faith, which
\par produces happiness, causes suspicion of the object of that faith, it
\par does not establish its "truth," it does establish a certain probability
\par of--_illusion_. What is now the position in these cases? These
\par solitaries and deniers of to-day; these fanatics in one thing, in their
\par claim to intellectual cleanness; these hard, stern, continent, heroic
\par spirits, who constitute the glory of our time; all these pale atheists,
\par anti-Christians, immoralists, Nihilists; these sceptics, "ephectics,"
\par and "hectics" of the intellect (in a certain sense they are the
\par latter, both collectively and individually); these supreme idealists
\par of knowledge, in whom alone nowadays the intellectual conscience
\par dwells and is alive--in point of fact they believe themselves as far
\par away as possible from the ascetic ideal, do these "free, very free
\par spirits": and yet, if I may reveal what they themselves cannot see--for
\par they stand too near themselves: this ideal is simply _their_ ideal,
\par they represent it nowadays and perhaps no one else, they themselves
\par are its most spiritualised product, its most advanced picket of
\par skirmishers and scouts, its most insidious delicate and elusive form
\par of seduction.--If I am in any way a reader of riddles, then I will
\par be one with this sentence: for some time past there have been no
\par free spirits; _for they still believe in truth_. When the Christian
\par Crusaders in the East came into collision with that invincible order
\par of assassins, that order of free spirits _par excellence_, whose
\par lowest grade lives in a state of discipline such as no order of monks
\par has ever attained, then in some way or other they managed to get an
\par inkling of that symbol and tally-word, that was reserved for the
\par highest grade alone as their _secretum_, "Nothing is true, everything
\par is allowed,"--in sooth, that was _freedom_ of thought, thereby was
\par _taking leave_ of the very belief in truth. Has indeed any European,
\par any Christian freethinker, ever yet wandered into this proposition
\par and its labyrinthine consequences? Does he know _from experience_ the
\par Minotauros of this den.--I doubt it--nay, I know otherwise. Nothing
\par is more really alien to these "mono-fanatics," these _so-called_
\par "free spirits," than freedom and unfettering in that sense; in no
\par respect are they more closely tied, the absolute fanaticism of their
\par belief in truth is unparalleled. I know all this perhaps too much from
\par experience at close quarters--that dignified philosophic abstinence
\par to which a belief like that binds its adherents, that stoicism of
\par the intellect, which eventually vetoes negation as rigidly as it does
\par affirmation, that wish for standing still in front of the actual,
\par the _factum brutum_, that fatalism in "_petits faits_" (ce petit
\par faitalism, as I call it), in which French Science now attempts a kind
\par of moral superiority over German, this renunciation of interpretation
\par generally (that is, of forcing, doctoring, abridging, omitting,
\par suppressing, inventing, falsifying, and all the other _essential_
\par attributes of interpretation)--all this, considered broadly, expresses
\par the asceticism of virtue, quite as efficiently as does any repudiation
\par of the senses (it is at bottom only a _modus_ of that repudiation.)
\par But what forces it into that unqualified will for truth is the faith
\par _in the ascetic ideal itself_, even though it take the form of its
\par unconscious imperatives,--make no mistake about it, it is the faith,
\par I repeat, in a _metaphysical_ value, an _intrinsic_ value of truth,
\par of a character which is only warranted and guaranteed in this ideal
\par (it stands and falls with that ideal). Judged strictly, there does
\par not exist a science without its "hypotheses," the thought of such a
\par science is inconceivable, illogical: a philosophy, a faith, must always
\par exist first to enable science to gain thereby a direction, a meaning,
\par a limit and method, a _right_ to existence. (He who holds a contrary
\par opinion on the subject--he, for example, who takes it upon himself to
\par establish philosophy "upon a strictly scientific basis"--has first got
\par to "turn up-side-down" not only philosophy but also truth itself--the
\par gravest insult which could possibly be offered to two such respectable
\par females!) Yes, there is no doubt about it--and here I quote my _Joyful
\par Wisdom_, cp. Book V. Aph. 344: "The man who is truthful in that
\par daring and extreme fashion, which is the presupposition of the faith
\par in science, _asserts thereby a different world_ from that of life,
\par nature, and history; and in so far as he asserts the existence of that
\par different world, come, must he not similarly repudiate its counterpart,
\par this world, _our_ world? The belief on which our faith in science is
\par based has remained to this day a metaphysical belief--even we knowers
\par of to-day, we godless foes of metaphysics, we too take our fire from
\par that conflagration which was kindled by a thousand-year-old faith,
\par from that Christian belief, which was also Plato's belief, the belief
\par that God is truth, that truth is _divine_.... But what if this belief
\par becomes more and more incredible, what if nothing proves itself to
\par be divine, unless it be error, blindness, lies--what if God, Himself
\par proved Himself to be our _oldest lie_?"--It is necessary to stop at
\par this point and to consider the situation carefully. Science itself now
\par _needs_ a justification (which is not for a minute to say that there
\par is such a justification). Turn in this context to the most ancient and
\par the most modern philosophers: they all fail to realise the extent of
\par the need of a justification on the part of the Will for Truth--here
\par is a gap in every philosophy--what is it caused by? Because up to the
\par present the ascetic ideal dominated all philosophy, because Truth was
\par fixed as Being, as God, as the Supreme Court of Appeal, because Truth
\par was not allowed to be a problem. Do you understand this "allowed"?
\par From the minute that the belief in the God of the ascetic ideal is
\par repudiated, there exists _a new problem_: the problem of the value of
\par truth. The Will for Truth needed a critique--let us define by these
\par words our own task---the value of truth is tentatively _to be called
\par in question_.... (If this seems too laconically expressed, I recommend
\par the reader to peruse again that passage from the _Joyful Wisdom_ which
\par bears the title, "How far we also are still pious," Aph. 344, and best
\par of all the whole fifth book of that work, as well as the Preface to
\par _The Dawn of Day_.)
\par 
\par 
\par 25.
\par 
\par No! You can't get round me with science, when I search for the natural
\par antagonists of the ascetic ideal, when I put the question: "_Where_
\par is the opposed will in which the _opponent ideal_ expresses itself?"
\par Science is not, by a long way, independent enough to fulfil this
\par function; in every department science needs an ideal value, a power
\par which creates values, and in whose _service_ it _can believe_ in itself
\par --science itself never creates values. Its relation to the ascetic
\par ideal is not in itself antagonistic; speaking roughly, it rather
\par represents the progressive force in the inner evolution of that ideal.
\par Tested more exactly, its opposition and antagonism are concerned not
\par with the ideal itself, but only with that ideal's outworks, its outer
\par garb, its masquerade, with its temporary hardening, stiffening, and
\par dogmatising--it makes the life in the ideal free once more, while it
\par repudiates its superficial elements. These two phenomena, science and
\par the ascetic ideal, both rest on the same basis\endash \endash I have already made
\par this clear\endash \endash the basis, I say, oft the same over-appreciation of truth
\par (more accurately the same belief in the _impossibility_ of valuing and
\par of criticising truth), and consequently they are _necessarily_ allies,
\par so that, in the event of their being attacked, they must always be
\par attacked and called into question together. A valuation of the ascetic
\par ideal inevitably entails a valuation of science as well; lose no time
\par in seeing this clearly, and be sharp to catch it! (_Art_, I am speaking
\par provisionally, for I will treat it on some other occasion in greater
\par detail,\endash \endash art, I repeat, in which lying is sanctified and the _will for
\par deception_ has good conscience on its side, is much more fundamentally
\par opposed to the ascetic ideal than is science: Plato's instinct felt
\par this\endash \endash Plato, the greatest enemy of art which Europe has produced up
\par to the present. Plato _versus_ Homer, that is the complete, the true
\par antagonism\endash \endash on the one side, the whole\endash hearted "transcendental," the
\par great defamer of life; on the other, its involuntary panegyrist, the
\par _golden_ nature. An artistic subservience to the service of the ascetic
\par ideal is consequently the most absolute artistic _corruption_ that
\par there can be, though unfortunately it is one of the most frequent
\par phases, for nothing is more corruptible than an artist.) Considered
\par physiologically, moreover, science rests on the same, basis as
\par does the ascetic ideal: a certain _impoverishment of life_ is the
\par presupposition of the latter as of the former\endash \endash add, frigidity of the
\par emotions, slackening of the _tempo_, the substitution of dialectic for
\par instinct, _seriousness_ impressed on mien and gesture (seriousness,
\par that most unmistakable sign of strenuous metabolism, of struggling,
\par toiling life). Consider the periods in a nation in which the learned
\par man comes into prominence; they are the periods of exhaustion, often
\par of sunset, of decay--the effervescing strength, the confidence in
\par life, the confidence in the future are no more. The preponderance of
\par the mandarins never signifies any good, any more than does the advent
\par of democracy, or arbitration instead of war, equal rights for women,
\par the religion of pity, and all the other symptoms of declining life.
\par (Science handled as a problem! what is the meaning of science?--upon
\par this point the Preface to the _Birth of Tragedy_.) No! this "modern
\par science"--mark you this well--is at times the _best_ ally for the
\par ascetic ideal, and for the very reason that it is the ally which is
\par most unconscious, most automatic, most secret, and most subterranean!
\par They have been playing into each other's hands up to the present, have
\par these "poor in spirit" and the scientific opponents of that ideal (take
\par care, by the bye, not to think that these opponents are the antithesis
\par of this ideal, that they are the _rich_ in spirit--that they are _not_;
\par I have called them the _hectic_ in spirit). As for these celebrated
\par victories of science; there is no doubt that they are _victories_--but
\par victories over what? There was not for a single minute any victory
\par among their list over the ascetic ideal, rather was it made stronger,
\par that is to say, more elusive, more abstract, more insidious, from
\par the fact that a wall, an outwork, that had got built on to the main
\par fortress and disfigured its appearance, should from time to time be
\par ruthlessly destroyed and broken down by science. Does any one seriously
\par suggest that the downfall of the theological astronomy signified the
\par downfall of that ideal?--Has, perchance, man grown _less in need_ of a
\par transcendental solution of his riddle of existence, because since that
\par time this existence has become more random, casual, and superfluous in
\par the _visible_ order of the universe? Has there not been since the time
\par of Copernicus an unbroken progress in the self-belittling of man and
\par his _will_ for belittling himself? Alas, his belief in his dignity, his
\par uniquenesses irreplaceableness in the scheme of existence, is gone--he
\par has become animal, literal, unqualified, and unmitigated animal, he
\par who in his earlier belief was almost God ("child of God," "demi-God").
\par Since Copernicus man seems to have fallen on to a steep plane--he rolls
\par faster and faster away from the centre--whither? into nothingness?
\par into the "thrilling sensation of his own nothingness"--Well! this
\par would be the straight way--to the old ideal?--All science (and by no
\par means only astronomy, with regard to the humiliating and deteriorating
\par effect of which Kant has made a remarkable confession, "it annihilates
\par my own importance"), all science, natural as much as _unnatural_--by
\par unnatural I mean the self-critique of reason--nowadays sets out to
\par talk man out of his present opinion of himself, as though that opinion
\par had been nothing but a bizarre piece of conceit; you might go so far
\par as to say that science finds its peculiar pride, its peculiar bitter
\par form of stoical ataraxia, in preserving man's _contempt of himself_,
\par that state which it took so much trouble to bring about, as man's final
\par and most serious claim to self-appreciation (rightly so, in point
\par of fact, for he who despises is always "one who has not forgotten
\par how to appreciate"). But does all this involve any real effort to
\par _counteract_ the ascetic ideal? Is it really seriously suggested that
\par Kant's _victory_ over the theological dogmatism about "God," "Soul,"
\par "Freedom," "Immortality," has damaged that ideal in any way (as the
\par theologians have imagined to be the case for a long time past)?\endash \endash 
\par And in this connection it does not concern us for a single minute,
\par if Kant himself intended any such consummation. It is certain that
\par from the time of Kant every type of transcendentalist is playing a
\par winning game\endash \endash they are emancipated from the theologians; what luck!\endash \endash he
\par has revealed to them that secret art, by which they can now pursue
\par their "heart's desire" on their own responsibility, and with all the
\par respectability of science. Similarly, who can grumble at the agnostics,
\par reverers, as they are, of the unknown and the absolute mystery, if they
\par now worship _their very query_ as God? (Xaver Doudan talks somewhere
\par of the _ravages_ which _l'habitude d'admirer l'inintelligible au lieu
\par de rester tout simplement dans l'inconnu_ has produced\endash \endash the ancients,
\par he thinks, must have been exempt from those ravages.) Supposing that
\par everything, "known" to man, fails to satisfy his desires, and on the
\par contrary contradicts and horrifies them, what a divine way out of all
\par this to be able to look for the responsibility, not in the "desiring"
\par but in "knowing"!\endash \endash "There is no knowledge. _Consequently_\endash \endash there is
\par a God"; what a novel _elegantia syllogism_i! what a triumph for the
\par ascetic ideal!
\par 
\par 
\par 26.
\par 
\par Or, perchance, does the whole of modern history show in its demeanour
\par greater confidence in life, greater confidence in its ideals? Its
\par loftiest pretension is now to be a _mirror_; it repudiates all
\par teleology; it will have no more "proving"; it disdains to play the
\par judge, and thereby shows its good taste\endash \endash it asserts as little as it
\par denies, it fixes, it "describes." All this is to a high degree ascetic,
\par but at the same time it is to a much greater degree _nihilistic_; make
\par no mistake about this! You see in the historian a gloomy, hard, but
\par determined gaze,\endash \endash an eye that _looks out_ as an isolated North Pole
\par explorer looks out (perhaps so as not to look within, so as not to look
\par back?)\endash \endash there is snow\endash \endash here is life silenced, the last crows which
\par caw here are called "whither?" "Vanity," "Nada"\endash \endash here nothing more
\par flourishes and grows, at the most the metapolitics of St. Petersburg
\par and the "pity" of Tolstoi. But as for that other school of historians,
\par a perhaps still more "modern" school, a voluptuous and lascivious
\par school which ogles life and the ascetic ideal with equal fervour,
\par which uses the word "artist" as a glove, and has nowadays established
\par a "corner" for itself, in all the praise given to contemplation; oh,
\par what a thirst do these sweet intellectuals excite even for ascetics
\par and winter landscapes! Nay! The devil take these "contemplative" folk!
\par How much liefer would I wander with those historical Nihilists through
\par the gloomiest, grey, cold mist!\endash \endash nay, I shall not mind listening
\par (supposing I have to choose) to one who is completely unhistorical
\par and anti-historical (a man, like D\'fchring for instance, over whose
\par periods a hitherto shy and unavowed species of "beautiful souls" has
\par grown intoxicated in contemporary Germany, _the species anarchistica_
\par within the educated proletariate). The "contemplative" are a hundred
\par times worse\endash \endash I never knew anything which produced such intense
\par nausea as one of those "objective" _chairs_,[6] one of those scented
\par mannikins-about-town of history, a thing half-priest, half-satyr (Renan
