\par what he lacks and where he lacks it, who betrays where in this case
\par the Fates have plied their ghastly shears, alas! in too surgeon-like
\par a fashion! This is distasteful to me, and irritates my patience; let
\par him keep patient at such sights who has nothing to lose thereby,\endash \endash such
\par a sight enrages me, such spectators embitter me against the "play,"
\par even more than does the play itself (history itself, you understand);
\par Anacreontic moods imperceptibly come over me. This Nature, who gave
\par to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af64 \ltrch\fcs0 \f64 the steer its horn, to the lion its \'f7\'dc\'f3\'ec }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af2 \ltrch\fcs0 \f2 \u8000\'3f}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af64 \ltrch\fcs0 \f64 \'e4\'ef\'ed\'f4\'f9\'ed, for what purpose
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af2 \ltrch\fcs0 \f2 did Nature give me my foot?\endash \endash To kick, by St. Anacreon, and not merely
