\par 
\par 
\par 27.
\par 
\par Enough! enough! let us leave these curiosities and complexities of
\par the modern spirit, which excite as much laughter as disgust. Our
\par problem can certainly do without them, the problem of _meaning_ of
\par the ascetic ideal--what has it got to do with yesterday or to-day?
\par those things shall be handled by me more thoroughly and severely in
\par another connection (under the title "A Contribution to the History of
\par European Nihilism," I refer for this to a work which I am preparing:
\par _The Will to Power, an Attempt at a Transvaluation of All Values_).
\par The only reason why I come to allude to it here is this: the ascetic
\par ideal has at times, even in the most intellectual sphere, only one
\par real kind of enemies and _damagers_: these are the comedians of this
\par ideal--for they awake mistrust. Everywhere otherwise, where the mind
\par is at work seriously, powerfully, and without counterfeiting, it
\par dispenses altogether now with an ideal (the popular expression for this
\par abstinence is "Atheism")--_with the exception of the will for truth_.
\par But this will, this _remnant_ of an ideal, is, if you will believe me,
\par that ideal itself in its severest and cleverest formulation, esoteric
\par through and through, stripped of all outworks, and consequently not so
\par much its remnant as its _kernel_. Unqualified honest atheism (and its
\par air only do we breathe, we, the most intellectual men of this age) is
\par _not_ opposed to that ideal, to the extent that it appears to be; it is
\par rather one of the final phases of its evolution, one of its syllogisms
\par and pieces of inherent logic--it is the awe-inspiring catastrophe of
\par a two-thousand-year training in truth, which finally forbids itself
\par _the lie of the belief in God_. (The same course of development in
\par India--quite independently, and consequently of some demonstrative
\par value--the same ideal driving to the same conclusion the decisive point
\par reached five hundred years before the European era, or more precisely
\par at the time of Buddha--it started in the Sankhyam philosophy, and then
\par this was popularised through Buddha, and made into a religion.)
\par 
\par _What_, I put the question with all strictness, has really _triumphed_
\par over the Christian God? The answer stands in my _Joyful Wisdom_, Aph.
\par 357: "the Christian morality itself, the idea of truth, taken as it was
\par with increasing seriousness, the confessor-subtlety of the Christian
\par conscience translated and sublimated into the scientific conscience
\par into intellectual cleanness at any price. Regarding Nature as though
\par it were a proof of the goodness and guardianship of God; interpreting
\par history in honour of a divine reason, as a constant proof of a moral
\par order of the world and a moral teleology; explaining our own personal
\par experiences, as pious men have for long enough explained them, as
\par though every arrangement, every nod, every single thing were invented
\par and sent out of love for the salvation of the soul; all this is now
\par done away with, all this has the conscience _against_ it, and is
\par regarded by every subtler conscience as disreputable, dishonourable,
\par as lying, feminism, weakness, cowardice--by means of this severity,
\par if by means of anything at all, are we, in sooth, _good Europeans_
\par and heirs of Europe's longest and bravest self-mastery.". .. All
\par great things go to ruin by reason of themselves, by reason of an act
\par of self-dissolution: so wills the law of life, the law of necessary
\par "self-mastery" even in the essence of life--ever is the law-giver
\par finally exposed to the cry, "_patere legem quam ipse tulisti_"; in
\par thus wise did Christianity _go to ruin as a dogma_, through its own
\par morality; in thus wise must Christianity go again to ruin to-day as
\par a morality--we are standing on the threshold of this event. After
\par Christian truthfulness has drawn one conclusion after the other, it
\par finally draws its _strongest conclusion_, its conclusion against
\par itself; this, however, happens, when it puts the question, "_what is
\par the meaning of every will for truth?_" And here again do I touch on my
\par problem, on our problem, my unknown friends (for as yet _I know_ of no
\par friends): what sense has our whole being, if it does not mean that in
\par our own selves that will for truth has come to its own consciousness
\par _as a problem_?---By reason of this attainment of self-consciousness
\par on the part of the will for truth, morality from henceforward--there
\par is no doubt about it--goes _to pieces_: this is that great hundred-act
\par play that is reserved for the next two centuries of Europe, the most
\par terrible, the most mysterious, and perhaps also the most hopeful of all
\par plays.
\par 
\par 
\par 28.
\par 
\par If you except the ascetic ideal, man, the animal man had no meaning.
\par His existence on earth contained no end; "What is the purpose of man
\par at all?" was a question without an answer; the _will_ for man and the
\par world was lacking; behind every great human destiny rang as a refrain
\par a still greater "Vanity!" The ascetic ideal simply means this: that
\par something _was lacking_, that a tremendous _void_ encircled man--he did
\par not know how to justify himself, to explain himself, to affirm himself,
\par he _suffered_ from the problem of his own meaning. He suffered also in
\par other ways, he was in the main a _diseased_ animal; but his problem
\par was not suffering itself, but the lack of an answer to that crying
\par question, "_To what purpose_ do we suffer?" Man, the bravest animal
\par and the one most inured to suffering, does _not_ repudiate suffering in
\par itself: he _wills_ it, he even seeks it out, provided that he is shown
\par a meaning for it, a _purpose_ of suffering. _Not_ suffering, but the
\par senselessness of suffering was the curse which till then lay spread
\par over humanity--_and the ascetic ideal gave it a meaning!_ It was up
\par till then the only meaning; but any meaning is better than no meaning;
\par the ascetic ideal was in that connection the _"faute de mieux" par
\par excellence_ that existed at that time. In that ideal suffering _found
\par an explanation_; the tremendous gap seemed filled; the door to all
\par suicidal Nihilism was closed. The explanation--there is no doubt about
\par it--brought in its train new suffering, deeper, more penetrating, more
\par venomous, gnawing more brutally into life: it brought all suffering
\par under the perspective of _guilt_; but in spite of all that--man was
\par _saved_ thereby, he had a _meaning_, and from henceforth was no more
\par like a leaf in the wind, a shuttle-cock of chance, of nonsense, he
\par could now "will" something--absolutely immaterial to what end, to what
\par purpose, with what means he wished: _the will itself was saved_. It
\par is absolutely impossible to disguise _what_ in point of fact is made
\par clear by every complete will that has taken its direction from the
\par ascetic ideal: this hate of the human, and even more of the animal,
\par and more still of the material, this horror of the senses, of reason
\par itself, this fear of happiness and beauty, this desire to get right
\par away from all illusion, change, growth, death, wishing and even
\par desiring--all this means--let us have the courage to grasp it--a will
\par for Nothingness, a will opposed to life, a repudiation of the most
\par fundamental conditions of life, but it is and remains _a will_!--and
\par to say at the end that which I said at the beginning--man will wish
\par _Nothingness_ rather than not wish _at all_.
