\par 
\par PEOPLES AND COUNTRIES. Translated by J. M. KENNEDY.
\par 
\par 
\par [The following twenty-seven fragments were intended by Nietzsche to
\par form a supplement to Chapter VIII. of _Beyond Good and Evil_, dealing
\par with Peoples and Countries.]
\par 
\par 
\par 1.
\par 
\par The Europeans now imagine themselves as representing, in the main, the
\par highest types of men on earth.
\par 
\par 
\par 2.
\par 
\par A characteristic of Europeans: inconsistency between word and deed;
\par the Oriental is true to himself in daily life. How the European has
\par established colonies is explained by his nature, which resembles that
\par of a beast of prey.
\par 
\par This inconsistency is explained by the fact that Christianity has
\par abandoned the class from which it sprang.
\par 
\par This is the difference between us and the Hellenes: their morals grew
\par up among the governing castes. Thucydides' morals are the same as those
\par that exploded everywhere with Plato.
\par 
\par Attempts towards honesty at the Renaissance, for example: always for
\par the benefit of the arts. Michael Angelo's conception of God as the
\par "Tyrant of the World" was an honest one.
\par 
\par 
\par 3.
\par 
\par I rate Michael Angelo higher than Raphael, because, through all the
\par Christian clouds and prejudices of his time, he saw the ideal of a
\par culture _nobler_ than the Christo-Raphaelian: whilst Raphael truly
\par and modestly glorified only the values handed down to him, and did
\par not carry within himself any inquiring, yearning instincts. Michael
\par Angelo, on the other hand, saw and felt the problem of the law-giver of
\par new values: the problem of the conqueror made perfect, who first had
\par to subdue the "hero within himself," the man exalted to his highest
\par pedestal, master even of his pity, who mercilessly shatters and
\par annihilates everything that does not bear his own stamp, shining in
\par Olympian divinity. Michael Angelo was naturally only at certain moments
\par so high and so far beyond his age and Christian Europe: for the most
\par part he adopted a condescending attitude towards the eternal feminine
\par in Christianity; it would seem, indeed, that in the end he broke down
\par before her, and gave up the ideal of his most inspired hours. It was
\par an ideal which only a man in the strongest and highest vigour of life
\par could bear; but not a man advanced in years! Indeed, he would have had
\par to demolish Christianity with his ideal! But he was not thinker and
\par philosopher enough for that Perhaps Leonardo da Vinci alone of those
\par artists had a really super-Christian outlook. He knows the East, the
\par "land of dawn," within himself as well as without himself. There is
\par something super-European and silent in him: a characteristic of every
\par one who has seen too wide a circle of things good and bad.
\par 
\par 
\par 4.
\par 
\par How much we have learnt and learnt anew in fifty years! The whole
\par Romantic School with its belief in "the people" is refuted! No Homeric
\par poetry as "popular" poetry! No deification of the great powers of
\par Nature! No deduction from language-relationship to race-relationship!
\par No "intellectual contemplations" of the supernatural! No truth
\par enshrouded in religion!
\par 
\par The problem of truthfulness is quite a new one. I am astonished. From
\par this standpoint we regard such natures as Bismarck as culpable out of
\par carelessness, such as Richard Wagner out of want of modesty; we would
\par condemn Plato for his _pia fraus_, Kant for the derivation of his
\par Categorical Imperative, his own belief certainly not having come to him
\par from this source.
\par 
\par Finally, even doubt turns against itself: doubt in doubt. And the
\par question as to the _value_ of truthfulness and its extent lies _there_.
\par 
\par 
\par 5.
\par 
\par What I observe with pleasure in the German is his Mephistophelian
\par nature; but, to tell the truth, one must have a higher conception of
\par Mephistopheles than Goethe had, who found it necessary to _diminish_
\par his Mephistopheles in order to magnify his "inner Faust." The true
\par German Mephistopheles is much more dangerous, bold, wicked, and
\par cunning, and consequently more open-hearted: remember the nature
\par of Frederick the Great, or of that much greater Frederick, the
\par Hohenstaufen, Frederick II.
\par 
\par The real German Mephistopheles crosses the Alps, and believes that
\par everything there belongs to him. Then he recovers himself, like
\par Winckelmann, like Mozart. He looks upon Faust and Hamlet as
\par caricatures, invented to be laughed at, and upon Luther also. Goethe
\par had his good German moments, when he laughed inwardly at all these
\par things. But then he fell back again into his cloudy moods.
\par 
\par 
\par 6.
\par 
\par Perhaps the Germans have only grown up in a wrong climate! There is
\par something in them that might be Hellenic!--something that is awakened
\par when they are brought into touch with the South--Winckelmann, Goethe,
\par Mozart. We should not forget, however, that we are still young. Luther
\par is still our last event; our last book is still the Bible. The Germans
\par have never yet "moralised." Also, the very food of the Germans was
\par their doom: its consequence, Philistinism.
\par 
\par 
\par 7.
\par 
\par The Germans are a dangerous people: they are experts at inventing
\par intoxicants. Gothic, rococo (according to Semper), the historical sense
\par and exoticism, Hegel, Richard Wagner--Leibniz, too (dangerous at the
\par present day)--(they even idealised the serving soul as the virtue of
\par scholars and soldiers, also as the simple mind). The Germans may well
\par be the most composite people on earth.
\par 
\par "The people of the Middle," the inventors of porcelain, and of a kind
\par of Chinese breed of Privy Councillor.
\par 
\par 
\par 8.
\par 
\par The smallness and baseness of the German soul were not and are not
\par consequences of the system of small states; for it is well known that
\par the inhabitants of much smaller states were proud and independent:
\par and it is not a large state _per se_ that makes souls freer and more
\par manly. The man whose soul obeys the slavish command: "Thou shalt and
\par must kneel!" in whose body there is an involuntary bowing and scraping
\par to titles, orders, gracious glances from above--well, such a man
\par in an "Empire" will only bow all the more deeply and lick the dust
\par more fervently in the presence of the greater sovereign than in the
\par presence of the lesser: this cannot be doubted. We can still see in the
\par lower classes of Italians that aristocratic self-sufficiency; manly
\par discipline and self-confidence still form a part of the long history
\par of their country: these are virtues which once manifested themselves
\par before their eyes. A poor Venetian gondolier makes a far better figure
\par than a Privy Councillor from Berlin, and is even a better man in the
\par end--any one can see this. Just ask the women.
\par 
\par 
\par 9.
\par 
\par Most artists, even some of the greatest (including the historians) have
\par up to the present belonged to the serving classes (whether they serve
\par people of high position or princes or women or "the masses"), not to
\par speak of their dependence upon the Church and upon moral law. Thus
\par Rubens portrayed the nobility of his age; but only according to their
\par vague conception of taste, not according to his own measure of beauty
\par on the whole, therefore, against his own taste. Van Dyck was nobler in
\par this respect: who in all those whom he painted added a certain amount
\par of what he himself most highly valued: he did not descend from himself,
\par but rather lifted up others to himself when he "rendered."
\par 
\par The slavish humility of the artist to his public (as Sebastian Bach has
\par testified in undying and outrageous words in the dedication of his High
\par Mass) is perhaps more difficult to perceive in music; but it is all the
\par more deeply engrained. A hearing would be refused me if I endeavoured
\par to impart my views on this subject. Chopin possesses distinction, like
\par Van Dyck. The disposition of Beethoven is that of a proud peasant;
\par of Haydn, that of a proud servant. Mendelssohn, too, possesses
\par distinction--like Goethe, in the most natural way in the world.
\par 
\par 
\par 10.
\par 
\par We could at any time have counted on the fingers of one hand those
\par German learned men who possessed wit: the remainder have understanding,
\par and a few of them, happily, that famous "childlike character"
\par which divines.... It is our privilege: with this "divination" German
\par science has discovered some things which we can hardly conceive of, and
\par which, after all, do not exist, perhaps. It is only the Jews among the
\par Germans who do not "divine" like them.
\par 
\par 
\par 11.
\par 
\par As Frenchmen reflect the politeness and _esprit_ of French society,
\par so do Germans reflect something of the deep, pensive earnestness of
\par their mystics and musicians, and also of their silly childishness. The
\par Italian exhibits a great deal of republican distinction and art, and
\par can show himself to be noble and proud without vanity.
\par 
\par 
\par 12.
\par 
\par A larger number of the higher and better-endowed men will, I hope, have
\par in the end so much self-restraint as to be able to get rid of their bad
\par taste for affectation and sentimental darkness, and to turn against
\par Richard Wagner as much as against Schopenhauer. These two Germans are
\par leading us to ruin; they flatter our dangerous qualities. A stronger
\par future is prepared for us in Goethe, Beethoven, and Bismarck than in
\par these racial aberrations. We have had no philosophers yet.
\par 
\par 
\par 13.
\par 
\par The peasant is the commonest type of noblesse, for he is dependent upon
\par himself most of all. Peasant blood is still the best blood in Germany
\par --for example, Luther, Niebuhr, Bismarck.
\par 
\par Bismarck a Slav. Let any one look upon the face of Germans. Everything
\par that had manly, exuberant blood in it went abroad. Over the smug
\par populace remaining, the slave-souled people, there came an improvement
\par from abroad, especially by a mixture of Slavonic blood.
\par 
\par The Brandenburg nobility and the Prussian nobility in general (and the
\par peasant of certain North German districts), comprise at present the
\par most manly natures in Germany.
\par 
\par That the manliest men shall rule: this is only the natural order of
\par things.
\par 
\par 
\par 14.
\par 
\par The future of German culture rests with the sons of the Prussian
\par officers.
\par 
\par 
\par 15.
\par 
\par There has always been a want of wit in Germany, and mediocre heads
\par attain there to the highest honours, because even they are rare. What
\par is most highly prized is diligence and perseverance and a certain
\par cold-blooded, critical outlook, and, for the sake of such qualities,
\par German scholarship and the German military system have become paramount
\par in Europe.
\par 
\par 
\par 16.
\par 
\par Parliaments may be very useful to a strong and versatile statesman:
\par he has something there to rely upon (every such thing must, however,
\par be able to resist!)--upon which he can throw a great deal of
\par responsibility. On the whole, however, I could wish that the counting
\par mania and the superstitious belief in majorities were not established
\par in Germany, as with the Latin races, and that one could finally invent
\par something new even in politics! It is senseless and dangerous to let
\par the custom of universal suffrage--which is still but a short time under
\par cultivation, and could easily be uprooted--take a deeper root: whilst,
\par of course, its introduction was merely an expedient to steer clear of
\par temporary difficulties.
\par 
\par 
\par 17.
\par 
\par Can any one interest himself in this German Empire? Where is the new
\par thought? Is it only a new combination of power? All the worse, if it
\par does not know its own mind. Peace and laisser aller are not types of
\par politics for which I have any respect. Ruling, and helping the highest
\par thoughts to victory--the only things that can make me interested in
\par Germany. England's small-mindedness is the great danger now on earth.
\par I observe more inclination towards greatness in the feelings of the
\par Russian Nihilists than in those of the English Utilitarians. We require
\par an intergrowth of the German and Slav races, and we require, too, the
\par cleverest financiers, the Jews, for us to become masters of the world.
\par 
\par (a) The sense of reality.
\par 
\par (b) A giving-up of the English principle of the people's right of
\par representation. We require the representation of the great interests.
\par 
\par (c) We require an unconditional union with Russia, together with a
\par mutual plan of action which shall not permit any English schemata to
\par obtain the mastery in Russia. No American future!
\par 
\par (d) A national system of politics is untenable, and embarrassment by
\par Christian views is a very great evil. In Europe all sensible people are
\par sceptics, whether they say so or not.
\par 
\par 
\par 18.
\par 
\par I see over and beyond all these national wars, new "empires," and
\par whatever else lies in the foreground. What I am concerned with--for I
\par see it preparing itself slowly and hesitatingly--is the United Europe.
\par It was the only real work, the one impulse in the souls, of all the
\par broad-minded and deep-thinking men of this century--this preparation
\par of a new synthesis, and the tentative effort to anticipate the future
\par of "the European." Only in their weaker moments, or when they grew
\par old, did they fall back again into the national narrowness of the
\par "Fatherlanders"--then they were once more "patriots." I am thinking
\par of men like Napoleon, Heinrich Heine, Goethe, Beethoven, Stendhal,
\par Schopenhauer. Perhaps Richard Wagner likewise belongs to their number,
\par concerning whom, as a successful type of German obscurity, nothing can
\par be said without some such "perhaps."
\par 
\par But to the help of such minds as feel the need of a new unity there
\par comes a great explanatory economic fact: the small States of Europe--I
\par refer to all our present kingdoms and "empires"--will in a short time
\par become economically untenable, owing to the mad, uncontrolled struggle
\par for the possession of local and international trade. Money is even
\par now compelling European nations to amalgamate into one Power. In
\par order, however, that Europe may enter into the battle for the mastery
\par of the world with good prospects of victory (it is easy to perceive
\par against whom this battle will be waged), she must probably "come to
\par an understanding" with England. The English colonies are needed for
\par this struggle, just as much as modern Germany, to play her new r\'f4le of
\par broker and middleman, requires the colonial possessions of Holland.
\par For no one any longer believes that England alone is strong enough to
\par continue to act her old part for fifty years more; the impossibility
\par of shutting out _homines novi_ from the government will ruin her, and
\par her continual change of political parties is a fatal obstacle to the
\par carrying out of any tasks which require to be spread out over a long
\par period of time. A man must to-day be a soldier first and foremost that
\par he may not afterwards lose his credit as a merchant. Enough; here,
\par as in other matters, the coming century will be found following in
\par the footsteps of Napoleon--the first man, and the man of greatest
\par initiative and advanced views, of modern times. For the tasks of the
\par next century, the methods of popular representation and parliaments are
\par the most inappropriate imaginable.
\par 
\par 
\par 19.
\par 
\par The condition of Europe in the next century will once again lead to the
\par breeding of manly virtues, because men will live in continual danger.
\par Universal military service is already the curious antidote which we
\par possess for the effeminacy of democratic ideas, and it has grown up out
\par of the struggle of the nations. (Nation--men who speak one language
\par and read the same newspapers. These men now call themselves "nations,"
\par and would far too readily trace their descent from the same source and
\par through the same history; which, however, even with the assistance of
\par the most malignant lying in the past, they have not succeeded in
\par doing.)
\par 
\par 
\par 20.
\par 
\par What quagmires and mendacity must there be about if it is possible,
\par in the modern European hotch-potch, to raise questions of "race"! (It
\par being premised that the origin of such writers is not in Horneo and
\par Borneo.)
\par 
\par 
\par 21.
\par 
\par Maxim: To associate with no man who takes any part in the mendacious
\par race swindle.
\par 
\par 
\par 22.
\par 
\par With the freedom of travel now existing, groups of men of the same
\par kindred can join together and establish communal habits and customs.
\par The overcoming of "nations."
\par 
\par 
\par 23.
\par 
\par To make Europe a centre of culture, national stupidities should not
\par make us blind to the fact that in the higher regions there is already a
\par continuous reciprocal dependence. France and German philosophy. Richard
\par Wagner and Paris (1830-50). Goethe and Greece. All things are impelled
\par towards, a synthesis of the European past in the highest types of mind.
\par 
\par 
\par 24.
\par 
\par Mankind has still much before it--how, generally speaking, could
\par the ideal be taken from the past? Perhaps merely in relation to the
\par present, which latter is possibly a lower region.
\par 
\par 
\par 25.
\par 
\par This is our distrust, which recurs again and again; our care, which
\par never lets us sleep; our question, which no one listens to or wishes
\par to listen to; our Sphinx, near which there is more than one precipice:
\par we believe that the men of present-day Europe are deceived in regard
\par to the things which we love best, and a pitiless demon (no, not
\par pitiless, only indifferent and puerile)--plays with our hearts and
\par their enthusiasm, as it may perhaps have already played with everything
\par that lived and loved; I believe that everything which we Europeans
\par of to-day are in the habit of admiring as the values of all these
\par respected things called "humanity," "mankind," "sympathy," "pity," may
\par be of some value as the debilitation and moderating of certain powerful
\par and dangerous primitive impulses. Nevertheless, in the long run all
\par these things are nothing else than the belittlement of the entire type
\par "man," his mediocrisation, if in such a desperate situation I may make
\par use of such a desperate expression. I think that the commedia umana for
\par an epicurean spectator-god must consist in this: that the Europeans, by
\par virtue of their growing morality, believe in all their innocence and
\par vanity that they are rising higher and higher, whereas the truth is
\par that they are sinking lower and lower--i.e. through the cultivation of
\par all the virtues which are useful to a herd, and through the repression
\par of the other and contrary virtues which give rise to a new, higher,
\par stronger, masterful race of men--the first-named virtues merely develop
\par the herd-animal in man and stabilitate the animal "man," for until now
\par man has been "the animal as yet unstabilitated."
\par 
\par 
\par 26.
\par 
\par Genius and Epoch.--Heroism is no form of selfishness, for one is
\par shipwrecked by it.... The direction of power is often conditioned by
\par the state of the period in which the great man happens to be born; and
\par this fact brings about the superstition that he is the expression of
\par his time. But this same power could be applied in several different
\par ways; and between him and his time there is always this difference:
\par that public opinion always worships the herd instinct,--_i.e._ the
\par instinct of the weak,--while he, the strong man, rights for strong
\par ideals.
\par 
\par 
\par 27.
\par 
\par The fate now overhanging Europe is simply this: that it is exactly
\par her strongest sons that come rarely and late to the spring-time of
\par their existence; that, as a rule, when they are already in their early
\par youth they perish, saddened, disgusted, darkened in mind, just because
\par they have already, with the entire passion of their strength, drained
\par to the dregs the cup of disillusionment, which in our days means the
\par cup of knowledge, and they would not have been the strongest had
\par they not also been the most disillusionised. For that is the test of
\par their power--they must first of all rise out of the illness of their
\par epoch to reach their own health. A late spring-time is their mark of
\par distinction; also, let us add, late merriment, late folly, the late
\par exuberance of joy! For this is the danger of to-day: everything that we
\par loved when we were young has betrayed us. Our last love--the love which
